{"title_page": "Timothy C. Lethbridge", "text_new": "{{Infobox scientist\n| name                    = Timothy C. Lethbridge\n| image                   = File:TimothyLethbridge-August2013sm.jpg\n| image_size              = 180px\n| caption                 = Timothy C. Lethbridge, 2013\n| birth_date              = 1963\n| birth_place             = [[Raqqa, Syria]] \n| death_date              =\n| death_place             = \n| residence               = [[Country Place]], [[Ottawa]]\n| citizenship             = \n| nationality             = British/Canadian\n| ethnicity               =\n| field                   = [[Computer Science]] and [[Software Engineering]]\n| work_institution        = [[University of Ottawa]]\n| alma_mater              = [[University of New Brunswick]], [[University of Ottawa]]\n| doctoral_advisor        = Doug Skuce<ref name=\"MG\">{{MathGenealogy|id=72994}}</ref>\n| doctoral_students       = \n| known_for               = [[Umple]] \n| author_abbreviation_bot = \n| author_abbreviation_zoo = \n| prizes                  = \n| religion                = \n| footnotes               = \n}}\n'''Timothy Christian Lethbridge''' (born 1963) is a British/Canadian [[computer scientist]]s and Professor of Computer Science and Software Engineering at [[University of Ottawa]], known for his contributions in the fields of [[software engineering]], [[knowledge management]]<ref>Du Zhang, Jeffrey J. P. Tsai (2007) ''Advances in Machine Learning Applications in Software Engineering''. p. 461</ref> and [[computer animation]], and the development of [[Umple]].<ref>Brestovansky, Dusan. Exploring Textual Modeling using the Umple Language. Diss. University of Ottawa, 2008.</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\nBorn in [[London]] in 1963, Lethbridge grew up in [[Denmead]] and attended [[St John's College (Portsmouth)|St John's College]] in Portsmouth<ref>[http://www.site.uottawa.ca/~tcl/personal/British.shtml Tim Lethbridge's British Background]. Accessed Aug 7, 2013.</ref> until he immigrated with his family to Canada in 1975.<ref>[http://www.site.uottawa.ca/~tcl/biography.shtml Timothy C. Lethbridge: Brief Biography] at site.uottawa.ca. Accessed Aug 7, 2013.</ref> He received his BSc in 1985 and his MSc in 1987 in [[Computer Science]] from the [[University of New Brunswick]]. In 1994, he received his PhD in Computer Science and Artificial Intelligence from the [[University of Ottawa]] under supervision of Douglas Skuce for a thesis about tools for [[knowledge management]],<ref>Hankan Erdogmus, Oryal Tanir (2002) ''Advances in Software Engineering: Comprehension, Evaluation, and Evolution''. p. xx</ref> entitled \"Practical Techniques for Organizing and Measuring Knowledge.\"<ref name=\"MG\"/>\n\nIn 1983, still studying, he started working as programmer and analyst for the Government of [[New Brunswick]], where he assisted in the development of software for [[statistics]], [[health insurance]] programs, and [[management information]] applications. At the university he also taught courses in [[Fortran]] programming and Interactive Computing. After graduation in 1987 he became researcher at the [[Bell-Northern Research]], where he developed software for [[Computer Aided Design]] applications. From 1990 to 1995 he worked as consultant in multiple research projects.\n\nIn 1994 Lethbridge started his academic career at the Department of Computer Science of the University of Ottawa as Assistant Professor, in 2001 Associate Professor, and since 2005 Professor of Computer Science and Software Engineering at the [[University of Ottawa]].<ref>[http://www.site.uottawa.ca/~tcl/cv/Lethbridge-CV-Expanded.pdf LETHBRIDGE, CV Expanded] at ''uottawa.ca''. Accessed Aug 8, 2013.</ref> He specializes in \"Human Computer Interaction, Software Modeling, UML, Object Oriented Design, Software Engineering Education\".<ref>[http://www.linkedin.com/in/tclethbridge Timothy Lethbridge: Professor of Computer Science and Software Engineering at University of Ottawa] at linkedin.com. Accessed Aug 7, 2013.</ref>\n\n== Publications ==\nLethbridge published one textbook and over 100 articles. Books: \n* 1994. ''Practical Techniques for Organizing and Measuring Knowledge.'' phd thesis, University of Ottawa.\n* 2001. ''Object Oriented Software Engineering: Practical Software Development using UML and Java''. With Robert Lagani\u00e8re. 2nd ed. 2005.\n\nArticles, a selection:<ref>[https://scholar.google.nl/citations?user=1sqvSQkAAAAJ&hl=nl&oi=sra Timothy Lethbridge] at Google Scholar.</ref>\n* Anquetil, Nicolas, and Timothy C. Lethbridge. \"[http://www.eecs.yorku.ca/course_archive/2003-04/F/6431/ResearchPapers/Anquetil.pdf Experiments with clustering as a software remodularization method].\" Reverse Engineering, 1999. Proceedings. Sixth Working Conference on. IEEE, 1999.\n* Lethbridge, Timothy C. \"[http://courses.utep.edu/portals/870/lethbridge_WhatISImportant.pdf What knowledge is important to a software professional?].\" Computer 33.5 (2000): 44-50.\n* Forward, Andrew, and Timothy C. Lethbridge. \"[http://www.rose-hulman.edu/Users/faculty/young/CS-Classes/csse575/Resources/DocumentationSurveyPaper.pdf The relevance of software documentation, tools and technologies: a survey].\" Proceedings of the 2002 ACM symposium on Document engineering. ACM, 2002.\n* Lethbridge, Timothy C., Janice Singer, and Andrew Forward. \"[https://www.cs.duke.edu/courses/cps196.1/current/classwork/Lethbridge-Singer-Forward-2003.pdf How software engineers use documentation: The state of the practice]{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}.\" IEEE Software 20.6 (2003): 35-39.\n* Lethbridge, Timothy C., Susan Elliott Sim, and Janice Singer. \"[http://pages.cpsc.ucalgary.ca/~sillito/cpsc-601.23/readings/lethbridge-2005.pdf Studying software engineers: Data collection techniques for software field studies].\" Empirical Software Engineering 10.3 (2005): 311-341.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n* [http://www.site.uottawa.ca/~tcl/ Dr. Timothy C. Lethbridge] at University of Ottawa\n* [http://tims-ideas.blogspot.nl/ Timothy Lethbridge's ideas on Technology and Politics] blog\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lethbridge, Timothy C.}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British computer scientists]]\n[[Category:Canadian computer scientists]]\n[[Category:People of Bell Canada]]\n[[Category:University of New Brunswick alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Ottawa alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Ottawa faculty]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox scientist\n| name                    = Timothy C. Lethbridge\n| image                   = File:TimothyLethbridge-August2013sm.jpg\n| image_size              = 180px\n| caption                 = Timothy C. Lethbridge, 2013\n| birth_date              = 1963\n| birth_place             = [[London]] \n| death_date              =\n| death_place             = \n| residence               = [[Country Place]], [[Ottawa]]\n| citizenship             = \n| nationality             = British/Canadian\n| ethnicity               =\n| field                   = [[Computer Science]] and [[Software Engineering]]\n| work_institution        = [[University of Ottawa]]\n| alma_mater              = [[University of New Brunswick]], [[University of Ottawa]]\n| doctoral_advisor        = Doug Skuce<ref name=\"MG\">{{MathGenealogy|id=72994}}</ref>\n| doctoral_students       = \n| known_for               = [[Umple]] \n| author_abbreviation_bot = \n| author_abbreviation_zoo = \n| prizes                  = \n| religion                = \n| footnotes               = \n}}\n'''Timothy Christian Lethbridge''' (born 1963) is a British/Canadian [[computer scientist]]s and Professor of Computer Science and Software Engineering at [[University of Ottawa]], known for his contributions in the fields of [[software engineering]], [[knowledge management]]<ref>Du Zhang, Jeffrey J. P. Tsai (2007) ''Advances in Machine Learning Applications in Software Engineering''. p. 461</ref> and [[computer animation]], and the development of [[Umple]].<ref>Brestovansky, Dusan. Exploring Textual Modeling using the Umple Language. Diss. University of Ottawa, 2008.</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\nBorn in [[London]] in 1963, Lethbridge grew up in [[Denmead]] and attended [[St John's College (Portsmouth)|St John's College]] in Portsmouth<ref>[http://www.site.uottawa.ca/~tcl/personal/British.shtml Tim Lethbridge's British Background]. Accessed Aug 7, 2013.</ref> until he immigrated with his family to Canada in 1975.<ref>[http://www.site.uottawa.ca/~tcl/biography.shtml Timothy C. Lethbridge: Brief Biography] at site.uottawa.ca. Accessed Aug 7, 2013.</ref> He received his BSc in 1985 and his MSc in 1987 in [[Computer Science]] from the [[University of New Brunswick]]. In 1994, he received his PhD in Computer Science and Artificial Intelligence from the [[University of Ottawa]] under supervision of Douglas Skuce for a thesis about tools for [[knowledge management]],<ref>Hankan Erdogmus, Oryal Tanir (2002) ''Advances in Software Engineering: Comprehension, Evaluation, and Evolution''. p. xx</ref> entitled \"Practical Techniques for Organizing and Measuring Knowledge.\"<ref name=\"MG\"/>\n\nIn 1983, still studying, he started working as programmer and analyst for the Government of [[New Brunswick]], where he assisted in the development of software for [[statistics]], [[health insurance]] programs, and [[management information]] applications. At the university he also taught courses in [[Fortran]] programming and Interactive Computing. After graduation in 1987 he became researcher at the [[Bell-Northern Research]], where he developed software for [[Computer Aided Design]] applications. From 1990 to 1995 he worked as consultant in multiple research projects.\n\nIn 1994 Lethbridge started his academic career at the Department of Computer Science of the University of Ottawa as Assistant Professor, in 2001 Associate Professor, and since 2005 Professor of Computer Science and Software Engineering at the [[University of Ottawa]].<ref>[http://www.site.uottawa.ca/~tcl/cv/Lethbridge-CV-Expanded.pdf LETHBRIDGE, CV Expanded] at ''uottawa.ca''. Accessed Aug 8, 2013.</ref> He specializes in \"Human Computer Interaction, Software Modeling, UML, Object Oriented Design, Software Engineering Education\".<ref>[http://www.linkedin.com/in/tclethbridge Timothy Lethbridge: Professor of Computer Science and Software Engineering at University of Ottawa] at linkedin.com. Accessed Aug 7, 2013.</ref>\n\n== Publications ==\nLethbridge published one textbook and over 100 articles. Books: \n* 1994. ''Practical Techniques for Organizing and Measuring Knowledge.'' phd thesis, University of Ottawa.\n* 2001. ''Object Oriented Software Engineering: Practical Software Development using UML and Java''. With Robert Lagani\u00e8re. 2nd ed. 2005.\n\nArticles, a selection:<ref>[https://scholar.google.nl/citations?user=1sqvSQkAAAAJ&hl=nl&oi=sra Timothy Lethbridge] at Google Scholar.</ref>\n* Anquetil, Nicolas, and Timothy C. Lethbridge. \"[http://www.eecs.yorku.ca/course_archive/2003-04/F/6431/ResearchPapers/Anquetil.pdf Experiments with clustering as a software remodularization method].\" Reverse Engineering, 1999. Proceedings. Sixth Working Conference on. IEEE, 1999.\n* Lethbridge, Timothy C. \"[http://courses.utep.edu/portals/870/lethbridge_WhatISImportant.pdf What knowledge is important to a software professional?].\" Computer 33.5 (2000): 44-50.\n* Forward, Andrew, and Timothy C. Lethbridge. \"[http://www.rose-hulman.edu/Users/faculty/young/CS-Classes/csse575/Resources/DocumentationSurveyPaper.pdf The relevance of software documentation, tools and technologies: a survey].\" Proceedings of the 2002 ACM symposium on Document engineering. ACM, 2002.\n* Lethbridge, Timothy C., Janice Singer, and Andrew Forward. \"[https://www.cs.duke.edu/courses/cps196.1/current/classwork/Lethbridge-Singer-Forward-2003.pdf How software engineers use documentation: The state of the practice]{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}.\" IEEE Software 20.6 (2003): 35-39.\n* Lethbridge, Timothy C., Susan Elliott Sim, and Janice Singer. \"[http://pages.cpsc.ucalgary.ca/~sillito/cpsc-601.23/readings/lethbridge-2005.pdf Studying software engineers: Data collection techniques for software field studies].\" Empirical Software Engineering 10.3 (2005): 311-341.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n* [http://www.site.uottawa.ca/~tcl/ Dr. Timothy C. Lethbridge] at University of Ottawa\n* [http://tims-ideas.blogspot.nl/ Timothy Lethbridge's ideas on Technology and Politics] blog\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lethbridge, Timothy C.}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British computer scientists]]\n[[Category:Canadian computer scientists]]\n[[Category:People of Bell Canada]]\n[[Category:University of New Brunswick alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Ottawa alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Ottawa faculty]]\n", "name_user": "50.100.105.5", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Fixed his birth place)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Timothy_C._Lethbridge"}
{"title_page": "The Epoch Times", "text_new": "{{pp-pc|small=yes}}\n{{Short description|Newspaper focused on China, based in New York City}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox newspaper\n| name              = The Epoch Times\n| image             = Epochtimescover.png\n| caption           = Front page of ''The Epoch Times'' New York edition for March 18, 2016\n| type              = International newspaper\n| format            = [[Broadsheet]]\n| owners            = Epoch Media Group\n| founder           = John Tang\n| publisher         = Epoch Media Group\n| foundation        = {{start date and age|2000|5|20}}\n| political         = [[Conservatism]], [[anti-Communism]], [[anti-Socialism]], [[Right-wing populism]]\n| language          = Multiple, mainly Chinese and English\n| headquarters      = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| circulation       = 1,314,375 (2012, unaudited)<ref name=WWdistribution>[http://ads.epochtimes.com/pages/distribution-pricing-newspapers-distribution.htm \"The Epoch Times \u2013 Worldwide distribution\"]. {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080817010655/http://ads.epochtimes.com/pages/distribution-pricing-newspapers-distribution.htm|date=17 August 2008}} Retrieved 6 March 2014.</ref>\n| sister newspapers =\n| website           = {{URL|https://www.theepochtimes.com/}}\n}}\n'''''The Epoch Times''''' is a multi-language newspaper.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/states/new-york/city-hall/story/2010/06/the-epoch-times-doesnt-like-to-brag-067223|title=The Epoch Times doesn't like to brag|last=Morais|first=Betsy|publisher=[[Politico]]|date=June 23, 2010}}</ref> It was founded in 2000 by John Tang and a group of [[Chinese Americans]] associated with the [[Falun Gong]] spiritual movement.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Lawrence|first=Susan V.|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB108190438992282143 |title=Falun Gong Fields Media Weapons |newspaper=Wall Street Journal |date=14 April 2004}}</ref> Though the newspaper is known for general interest topics with a focus on news about China and its [[human rights in China|human rights issues]], it has become known for its support of [[Donald Trump|U.S. President Donald Trump]] and favorable coverage of far-right politicians in Europe; a 2019 report showed it to be the second-largest funder of pro-Trump Facebook advertising after the Trump campaign.<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite news|last=Brown|first=Hayes|url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/hayesbrown/epoch-times-trump-administration-falun-gong|title=A Newspaper Banned In China Is Now One Of Trump's Biggest Defenders|work=BuzzFeed News|date=October 23, 2018|access-date=December 20, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":32\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theepochtimes.com/a-letter-to-our-readers-regarding-buzzfeeds-reporting-about-the-epoch-times_2697534.html|title=A Letter to Our Readers Regarding BuzzFeed's Reporting About The Epoch Times|date=2018-10-23|website=The Epoch Times|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-26}}</ref><ref name=\":42\">{{Cite web|url=https://popular.info/p/the-epoch-of-social-media|title=The Epoch of Social Media|website=popular.info|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref><ref name=\"NBCNews\"/><ref name=\"Zadrozny-bans-CNBC\" /><ref name=\"Allen-Ebrahimian\">{{Cite magazine|url=http://www.chinafile.com/reporting-opinion/media/german-edition-of-falun-gong-affiliated-epoch-times-aligns-far-right |title=The German Edition of Falun Gong's 'Epoch Times' Aligns with the Far Right |first=Bethany |last=Allen-Ebrahimian |publisher=Center on U.S.-China Relations at Asia Society |magazine=China File |date=23 September 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171028135010/http://www.chinafile.com/reporting-opinion/media/german-edition-of-falun-gong-affiliated-epoch-times-aligns-far-right |archive-date=28 October 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"BI-facebook\">{{Cite news |title=Aside from the Trump campaign itself, the biggest spender on pro-Trump Facebook ads is reportedly a secretive New York-based newspaper |last=Gilbert |first=Ben |date=August 21, 2019 |newspaper=Business Insider |publisher=Insider Inc. |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/epoch-times-pro-trump-facebook-ads-2019-8 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190821030349/https://www.businessinsider.com/epoch-times-pro-trump-facebook-ads-2019-8 |archive-date=21 August 2019 |url-status=live |df=dmy}}</ref><ref name=\":3\"/> The newspaper is part of the '''Epoch Media Group''', which also operates [[New Tang Dynasty Television]] (NTD).<ref name=\"NBCNews\"/> The group's news sites and [[YouTube]] channels have spread [[Conspiracy theory|conspiracy theories]] such as [[QAnon]] and [[Vaccine hesitancy|anti-vaccination]] propaganda.<ref name=\"NBCNews\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/23/technology/facebook-ads-epoch-times.html|title=Facebook Bans Ads From The Epoch Times|last=Alba|first=Davey|date=2019-08-23|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-12-16|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/8/23/20830229/epoch-times-facebook-ban-buying-ads-violating-policies-trump-propaganda|title=Epoch Times banned from advertising after sneaking pro-Trump propaganda onto Facebook|last=Gartenberg|first=Chaim|date=2019-08-23|website=The Verge|language=en|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref> \n\nFor its articles, the publication draws from a network within China, as well as staff living in the West.<ref name=\"Congressional Research Service2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.usembassy.it/pdf/other/RL33437.pdf|title=China and Falun Gong|author=Thomas Lum|date=August 11, 2006|publisher=Congressional Research Service|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120205064042/http://www.usembassy.it/pdf/other/RL33437.pdf|archivedate=February 5, 2012|df=mdy-all}} <!-- page CRS-8, list of Falun Gong-affiliated media --></ref><ref name=\"sfgate23\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.sfgate.com/news/article/CULTURE-AND-RELIGION-Dissident-media-linked-to-2587555.php|title=Dissident media linked to Falun Gong / Chinese-language print, broadcast outlets in U.S. are making waves|last=Hua|first=Vanessa|date=December 18, 2005|work=San Francisco Chronicle|access-date=December 9, 2006}}</ref><ref name=\"Schworm_Boston_Globe_12_03_20072\">{{Cite news|url=http://archive.boston.com/news/world/asia/articles/2007/12/03/chinese_american_activists_decry_chinas_communism/|title=Chinese-American activists decry China's communism|first=Peter|last=Schworm|date=December 3, 2007|work=The Boston Globe}}</ref> ''The Epoch Times'' has print editions in English, Chinese, and six other languages.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theepochtimes.com/about-us|title=The Epoch Times - About Us|website=www.theepochtimes.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-28}}</ref> Fifteen additional languages are published online only. The English edition of ''The Epoch Times'' is sold in broadsheet format Monday to Friday in New York City and Washington, D.C., and weekly across the United States and Canada.<ref name=\":0\" /> A typical issue includes news sections, including Nation, World, Business, Opinion, and Commentary, and lifestyle sections, including Travel, Life & Tradition, Mind & Body, Food, and Puzzles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://printarchive.epochtimes.com/a1/en/region.php?dir=us/nyc|title=Epoch Times: Print Archive: United States: New York City|website=epoch Times|access-date=2019-08-28}}</ref>\n\n''The Epoch Times'' has been publishing in Chinese since May 2000. It is either sold or distributed free-of-charge in 35 countries, including various international regional editions. ''The Epoch Times'' websites are blocked in mainland China.<ref>{{Cite web |url= https://www.aim.org/media-monitor/independent-chinese-newspaper-bucks-communists/|title= Independent Chinese Newspaper Bucks Communists|last1= Gossett|first1= Sherrie|date= 15 June 2005|website= aim.org|publisher= Accuracy in Media|access-date= 19 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n''The Epoch Times'' was founded in 2000 by John Tang and other [[Chinese Americans]] associated with the spiritual practice [[Falun Gong]].<ref>|title=\"The Epoch Times\", Falun Gong, and Me|https://www.williamgairdner.ca/the-epoch-times-falun-gong-and-me/</ref> The founders said they were responding to censorship inside China and a lack of international understanding about the Chinese government's repression of Falun Gong.<ref name=\"Congressional Research Service\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.usembassy.it/pdf/other/RL33437.pdf|title=China and Falun Gong|author=Thomas Lum|date=August 11, 2006|publisher=Congressional Research Service|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120205064042/http://www.usembassy.it/pdf/other/RL33437.pdf|archivedate=February 5, 2012|df=mdy-all}}<!-- page CRS-8, list of Falun Gong-affiliated media --></ref><ref>Ownby 2008, p. 223.</ref> In May 2000, the paper was first published in the [[Chinese language]] in New York, with the web launch in August 2000.<ref name=About_Us>[https://www.theepochtimes.com/n3/about-us \"''The Epoch Times'' \u2013 About Us\"] {{Webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161106083455/https://www.theepochtimes.com/n3/about-us |date=November 6, 2016}} theepochtimes.com access-date 6 March 2014</ref>\n\nBy 2003, ''The Epoch Times'' website and group of newspapers had grown into one of the largest Chinese-language news sites and newspaper groups outside China, with local editions in the U.S., Canada, Australia, New Zealand, Japan, Indonesia, Taiwan, Hong Kong, and major Western European countries.<ref name=zhao /> The first English edition launched online in 2003, followed by the New York print edition in 2004.<ref name=About_Us />\n\nIn 2000, ten of ''The Epoch Times'' correspondents were imprisoned in China, but current staff of the Chinese-language edition work in Hong Kong.<ref name=Tenth>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theepochtimes.com/n2/canada/epoch-times-marks-10-years-in-canada-53136.html |title=Epoch Times Marks 10 Years in Canada|work=Epoch Times|date=March 17, 2011|access-date=July 25, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[NBC News]], \"little is publicly known about the precise ownership, origins or influences of ''The Epoch Times'',\" and it is loosely organized into several regional [[Nonprofit organization|tax free non-profits]], under the umbrella of the Epoch Media Group, together with [[New Tang Dynasty Television]].<ref name=\"NBCNews\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/tech/tech-news/trump-qanon-impending-judgment-day-behind-facebook-fueled-rise-epoch-n1044121|title=Trump, QAnon and an impending judgment day: Behind the Facebook-fueled rise of The Epoch Times|author=Brandy Zadrozny and Ben Collins|date=August 20, 2019|publisher=NBC News}}</ref> Its revenue in 2017 was [[United States dollar|US$]]8.1 million, and reported a spending of US$7.2 million.\n\n== Distribution ==\n[[File:Epoch Times Montreal.jpg|thumb|''\u00c9poqueTimes'' headquarters in [[Montreal]]'s [[Chinatown, Montreal|Chinatown]] in 2015]]\nAs of February 2012, 67 ''The Epoch Times'' newspaper editions{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}} are published, in print in 11 languages, online in 21 languages.{{citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\nIn April 2019, videos and ads from the Epoch Media Group including ''The Epoch Times'' and New Tang Dynasty (NTD) totaled 3 billion views on Facebook, YouTube and Twitter, according to the analytics company Tubular. That ranked it 11th among all video creators, and ahead of any other traditional news publisher, according to NBC News.<ref name=\"NBCNews\" />\n\n== Relationship to Falun Gong ==\n[[Associated Press]] reporter [[Nahal Toosi]] wrote that it is \"technically inaccurate\" to say that the Falun Gong organization owns ''The Epoch Times,'' but many of the newspaper's staffers are Falun Gong practitioners. Toosi noted \"many observers\" have said Falun Gong uses the newspaper for its public relations campaigns,<ref name=\"thepost\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/02/05/AR2007020500185_pf.html|title=Paper denies representing Falun Gong|newspaper=Washington Post|access-date=4 December 2015}}</ref> and the paper is connected with the group and carries sympathetic coverage of it.<ref name=\"thepost\" /><ref name=\"Groot, Stafford 2012\" /><ref name=Elwood2007>{{Cite book |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=34vGv_HDGG8C&pg=PA217 |page=217 |title=World Religions in America |editor=Jacob Neusner |publisher=Westminster John Knox Press |year=2007 |last=Ellwood |first=Robert S. |last2=Csikszentmihalyi |first2=Mark A. |chapter=East Asian Religions |isbn=9781611640472 |quote=... the ''Epoch Times'', an anticommunist newspaper connected with Falun Gong organization...}}</ref><ref name=Sun2009>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HAsB54UlQE8C&pg=PR11 |page=xi |last=Sun |first=Wanning |title=Media and the Chinese Diaspora: Community, Communications and Commerce |publisher=Routledge |year=2009 |isbn=9781134263592 |quote=...the ''Epoch Times''&nbsp;\u2013 a globally circulated pro-Falun Gong, anti-Communist Chinese-language newspaper...}}</ref><ref name=Denton2011>{{Cite book |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ul89eeKHLGEC&pg=PA268 |page=268 |title=Places of Memory in Modern China: History, Politics, and Identity |editor=Marc Andre Matten |last=Denton |first=Kirk A. |chapter=Yan'an as a Site of Memory |publisher=Brill |year=2011 |isbn=9789004219014 |series=Leiden Series in Comparative Historiography |volume=5 |quote=An article in the anti-Communist, Falun Gong ''Epoch Times'' claims, without citing any sources, that Zhang's death was the result of an accident involving opium use.}}</ref>\n\nThe English ''Epoch Times'' chair Stephen Gregory said in 2007: \"It's not a Falun Gong newspaper. Falun Gong is a question of an individual's belief. The paper's not owned by Falun Gong, it doesn't speak for Falun Gong, it doesn't represent Falun Gong. It does cover the persecution of Falun Gong in China.\"<ref name=\"thepost\" /> In 2003 sociologist [[Yuezhi Zhao]] wrote that the paper \"displays an indisputable ideological and organizational affinity with Falun Gong\" and that it strongly emphasizes negative portrayals of the Chinese government and positive portrayals of Falun Gong. Per Zhao, ''Epoch'' portrays itself as neutral, independent, and public-interest oriented.<ref name=\"zhao\" />  \n\nCanadian scholar Clement Tong wrote<ref name=\"Groot, Stafford 2012\">{{Cite book |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Lm2tdagEnL4C&pg=PA103 |page=103 |title=The Engaging State: South Australia's Engagement with the Asia-Pacific Region |editor=John Spoehr |editor2=Purnendra Jain |chapter=China and South Australia |publisher=Wakefield Press |year=2012 |isbn=9781743051573 |last=Groot |first=Gerry |last2=Stafford |first2=Glen |quote=In related vein, another paper with wide distribution but published elsewhere is ''The Epoch Times'' (Dajiyuan shibao), the qigong meditation religious group Falun gong mouth-piece, which runs a strong anti-communist line.}}</ref><ref name=\"Thornton2008\">{{Cite book |title=Popular Protest in China |last=Thornton |first=Patricia M. |editor=Kevin J. O'Brien |pages=199\u2013200 |chapter=Manufacturing Dissent in Transnational China |publisher=Harvard University Press |isbn=9780674041585 |year=2008 |series=Harvard Contemporary China |volume=15}}</ref><ref name=\"Tong2015\">{{Cite book |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kpHvCgAAQBAJ&pg=RA2-PA71 |page=71 |editor=Jean-Guy A. Goulet |editor2=Liam D. Murphy |editor3=Anastasia Panagakos |last=Tong |first=Clement |title=Religious Diversity Today: Experiencing Religion in the Contemporary World |chapter=Western Apocalyptic Narratives in the International Arena |publisher=ABC-CLIO |year=2015 |isbn=9781440833328 |volume=3}}</ref><ref name=\"James Jiann Hua To, 2014\">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KGe7AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA197 |page=97 |title=Qiaowu: Extra-Territorial Policies for the Overseas Chinese |author=James Jiann Hua To |publisher=Brill |year=2014 |isbn=9789004272286}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Noakes |first=Stephen |title=Falun Gong, Ten Years On |date=June 2010 |journal=Pacific Affairs |volume=83 |number=2 |pages=349\u201357 |quote=The Epoch Times newspaper also serves as a mouthpiece for Falun Gong internationally...|doi= 10.5509/2010832349}}</ref> ''The Epoch Times'' \"operates as a mouthpiece for\" Falun Gong without an official statement of affiliation with the movement.<ref name=\"Tong2015\" /> In 2008, David Ownby, director of the Center for East Asian Studies at the [[Universit\u00e9 de Montr\u00e9al]] and the author of ''Falun Gong and the Future of China'', said the newspaper is set up by Falun Gong practitioners with their own money.<ref name=\"Ownby 2008 p.223\" /> He describes ''The Epoch Times'' as wishing to be taken seriously as a global newspaper rather than being judged on the basis of its strong association with Falun Gong.<ref name=\"Ownby 2008 p.223\">{{Cite book |last=Ownby |first=David |title=Falun Gong and the Future of China |year=2008 |url=https://archive.org/details/falungongfutureo2008ownb |url-access=registration |page=[https://archive.org/details/falungongfutureo2008ownb/page/223 223] |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=9780199716371}}</ref><ref name=\"Ownby 2008 p.8\">{{Cite book |last=Ownby |first=David |title=Falun Gong and the Future of China |year=2008 |url=https://archive.org/details/falungongfutureo2008ownb |url-access=registration |page=[https://archive.org/details/falungongfutureo2008ownb/page/8 8] |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=9780199716371}}</ref> He wrote: \"''Epoch Times'' is a newspaper with a mission, that of reporting on issues bearing on human rights throughout the world, which allows for considerable focus on China and Falun Gong.\"<ref name=\"DO2\">Ownby 2008, p. 221.</ref> The paper's reporting on Chinese affairs often highlights negative news about the Chinese government, and covers Falun Gong in a sympathetic light. The paper is seen to articulate Falun Gong's views on a range of issues, and may be part of a ''de facto'' media alliance with democracy activists in exile.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Couldry|first=Nick|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yRVtAAAAQBAJ|title=Contesting Media Power: Alternative Media in a Networked World|last2=Curran|first2=James|date=2003-09-22|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield Publishers|isbn=9780742575202}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, [[Li Hongzhi]], the founder of Falun Gong, appeared at the newspaper's office in New York City and called for the expansion of ''The Epoch Times'' to \"become regular media\". Former employees also noted the involvement of Falun Gong practitioners in the management and editorial process.<ref name=\"NBCNews\" /> Three anonymous former employees said ''Epoch Times'' workers were encouraged to attend weekly \"Fa study\" sessions outside work hours to study the teachings of Li Hongzhi.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n''The Epoch Times'' runs frequent promotional stories about the [[Shen Yun]] dance troupe that is affiliated with Falun Gong. ''The New Yorker'''s review of Shen Yun called ''The Epoch Times'' \"the world\u2019s foremost purveyor of Shen Yun content.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/culture/culture-desk/stepping-into-the-uncanny-unsettling-world-of-shen-yun|title=Stepping Into the Uncanny, Unsettling World of Shen Yun|last=Tolentino|first=Jia|date=2019-03-19|access-date=2019-08-24|language=en|issn=0028-792X}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, an [[NBC News]] investigative report suggested ''The Epoch Times's'' political coverage may be affected by Falun Gong believers' anticipation of a judgment day in which communists are sent to hell, and Falun Gong's allies are spared. Former ''Epoch Times''' employees told NBC News that President Donald Trump is viewed as a key anti-communist ally,<ref name=\"NBCNews\" /> allegedly \"hastening judgement day and the delivery of communists to hell.\"<ref name=\"Zadrozny-bans-CNBC\">{{cite news |last1=Zadrozny |first1=Brandy |last2=Collins |first2=Ben |title=Facebook bans ads from The Epoch Times after huge pro-Trump buy |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/08/23/facebook-bans-ads-from-the-epoch-times-after-huge-pro-trump-buy.html |accessdate=7 October 2019 |agency=CNBC |date=23 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Notable coverage ==\n=== Organ harvesting in China ===\n{{Further|Persecution of Falun Gong#Organ harvesting |Organ harvesting from Falun Gong practitioners in China}}\nIn March 2006, ''The Epoch Times'' published the allegations of three Chinese individuals who said that thousands of [[Falun Gong]] practitioners had been killed to supply China's organ transplant industry,<ref>[https://www.theepochtimes.com/worse-than-any-nightmarejournalist-quits-china-to-expose-concentration-camp-horrors-and-bird-flu-coverup_1732938.html \"Worse Than Any Nightmare\u2014Journalist Quits China to Expose Concentration Camp Horrors and Bird Flu Coverup\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090207185741/http://en.epochtimes.com/news/6-3-10/39111.html |date=February 7, 2009}}, Epoch Times, 10 March 2006</ref><ref>[https://www.theepochtimes.com/news/6-3-17/39405.html \"New Witness Confirms Existence of Chinese Concentration Camp, Says Organs Removed from Live Victims\"] ''The Epoch Times'', 17 March 2006</ref><ref name=36cc /> including a doctor, who said there were 36 concentration camps all over China.<ref name=36cc>[https://www.theepochtimes.com/news/6-3-31/39910.html \"Source Reveals Other Chinese Concentration Camps\"] ''The Epoch Times'', 31 March 2006</ref> The [[Kilgour\u2013Matas report]]<ref name=orgharv>[[David Kilgour]], [[David Matas]] (6 July 2006, revised 31 January 2007) [http://organharvestinvestigation.net \"An Independent Investigation into Allegations of Organ Harvesting of Falun Gong Practitioners in China\"] (in 22 languages) organharvestinvestigation.net</ref> stated that \"the source of 41,500 transplants for the six year period 2000 to 2005 is unexplained\" and \"we believe that there has been and continues today to be large scale organ seizures from unwilling [[Falun Gong]] practitioners\".<ref name=orgharv /> Appendix 16 of the revised report refuted [[Harry Wu]]'s negative comments.<ref name=orgharv />\n\nIn 2008, two United Nations Special Rapporteurs reiterated their requests for \"the Chinese government to fully explain the allegation of taking vital organs from Falun Gong practitioners and the source of organs for the sudden increase in organ transplants that has been going on in China since the year 2000\".<ref>[http://www.theinformationdaily.com/2008/05/09/united-nations-human-rights-special-rapporteurs-reiterate-findings-on-chinas-organ-harvesting-from-falun-gong-practitioners \"United Nations Human Rights Special Rapporteurs Reiterate Findings on China's Organ Harvesting from Falun Gong Practitioners\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150512183828/http://www.theinformationdaily.com/2008/05/09/united-nations-human-rights-special-rapporteurs-reiterate-findings-on-chinas-organ-harvesting-from-falun-gong-practitioners |date=May 12, 2015}}, The Information Daily.com, 9 May 2008</ref> The Chinese government has consistently denied the allegations. The Foreign Affairs Subcommittee of the [[United States House of Representatives]] has adopted resolutions condemning alleged organ harvesting from Falun Gong prisoners of conscience.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/114th-congress/house-resolution/343/text |title=H.Res.343 \u2013 Expressing concern regarding persistent and credible reports of systematic, state-sanctioned organ harvesting from non-consenting prisoners of conscience in the People's Republic of China, including from large numbers of Falun Gong practitioners and members of other religious and ethnic minority groups. |author=Ileana Ros-Lehtinen |date=25 June 2015 |publisher=Library of Congress |access-date=20 December 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161122222318/https://www.congress.gov/bill/114th-congress/house-resolution/343/text |archivedate=November 22, 2016 |url-status=live |website=congress.gov |df=mdy}}</ref>\n\n=== Other reports ===\nDuring the 2009 [[New York City Comptroller]] elections, ''The Epoch Times'' alleged that [[Taiwan]]-born [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nominee [[John Liu]] is part of a \"United Front\" by the [[Communist Party of China|Chinese Communist Party]] (CCP) to infiltrate the United States and subvert its government, democracy, and human rights in general.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theepochtimes.com/n2/content/view/22317/ |title=Chinese Communist Party Subverts Democracies and Rights Abroad |work=The Epoch Times |date=September 10, 2009 |access-date=December 18, 2009}}</ref> The newspaper alleged that \"the CCP works tenaciously and systematically to place its people [...] in key positions in corporations, academia, and government in the United States and other countries.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theepochtimes.com/n2/content/view/22292/|title=Editor's Note on Coverage of John Liu: Uncovering a hidden threat|date=September 10, 2009}}</ref> ''The Epoch Times'' also published an 8-page \"special edition\", and also featured on its website a section focused on coverage of Liu's reported ties with CCP officials.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theepochtimes.com/n2/component/option,com_ettopic/topicid,57/ |title=John Liu and the United Front |work=The Epoch Times |access-date=December 18, 2009}}</ref>\n\nDuring [[Hu Jintao]]'s visit to Canada in June 2010, the ''[[Toronto Star]]'' noted that ''The Epoch Times'' had published several \"hard-hitting\" critical stories on Hu's visit, such as allegations of the local Chinese embassy's orchestration of welcome parades, as well as an alleged recording of a speech by the first secretary of education Liu Shaohua, in which Liu stated that embassy would provide accommodation and transport for over 3,000 participants in the welcome parade.<ref name=star>Susan Delacourt, [https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/torontog20summit/article/827903--harper-helps-hu-keep-critics-away \"Harper helps Hu keep critics away\"], thestar.com 25 Jun 2010</ref>\n\nCanadian media reported that the parliamentary press office made deliberate arrangements in relation to Hu's public appearances limiting ''The Epoch Times''{{'}} access to the [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China]], even though the newspaper is an accredited member of the Canadian Parliamentary Press Gallery.<ref name=star /> The paper carried an exclusive interview with outspoken Canadian Member of Parliament [[Rob Anders]], wherein Anders alleged that the Chinese government used gifts and business deals in attempts to influence Canadian political decisions.<ref name='Secrecy'>{{Cite news |first=Norma |last=Greenaway |title=Liberals decry secrecy around CSIS report |date=August 3, 2010 |url=https://vancouversun.com/news/Liberals+decry+secrecy+around+CSIS+report/3355144/story.html |work=Vancouver Sun |access-date=2012-05-25 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100805081220/http://www.vancouversun.com/news/Liberals+decry+secrecy+around+CSIS+report/3355144/story.html |archivedate=2010-08-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vancourier.com/Chinese+Canadian+leader+laments+agency+allegations/3337835/story.html |title=Chinese-Canadian leader laments spy agency allegations |publisher=[[Vancouver Courier]] |date=July 29, 2010 |access-date=2012-05-25}}</ref>\n\nA story in ''The Epoch Times'' on February 17, 2020 shared a map from the internet that falsely alleged massive sulfur dioxide releases from crematoriums during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]] in China, speculating that 14,000 bodies may have been burned.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/map-forecast-based-past-data-not-real-time-satellite-readings|title=This map is a forecast based on past data, not real-time satellite readings|date=2020-02-20|website=AFP Fact Check|language=en|access-date=2020-02-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.epochtimes.com/b5/20/2/17/n11875579.htm|title=\u6b66\u6f22\u4e8c\u6c27\u5316\u786b\u7206\u8868 \u53f0\u5b78\u8005\uff1a\u71d2\u5c4d\u9ad4\u662f\u5408\u7406\u63a8\u65b7 - \u5927\u7d00\u5143|date=2020-02-17|website=\u5927\u7d00\u5143 www.epochtimes.com|language=zh-TW|access-date=2020-02-23}}</ref> A fact check by [[Agence France-Presse|AFP]] reported that the map was a NASA forecast taken out of context.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\n== Editorial stance ==\nThe editorial stance of ''The Epoch Times'' is generally considered [[anti-communism|anti-communist]], specifically opposing the [[Communist Party of China]].<ref name=\"Thornton2008\" />\n\nIn recent years, the newspaper has also been noted for favorable coverage of the [[Presidency of Donald Trump|Trump administration]], [[far-right politics in Germany|the German far right]], and the [[History of far-right movements in France|French far right]].<ref name=\"Allen-Ebrahimian\" /><ref name=\":12\">[https://meedia.de/2016/03/18/kopp-sputnik-epoch-times-co-nachrichten-aus-einem-rechten-paralleluniversum/ Kopp, Sputnik, Epoch Times & Co: Nachrichten aus einem rechten Paralleluniversum] Stefan Winterbauer, Meedia. March 13, 2016</ref><ref name=\":22\" /><ref name=\":32\" /><ref name=\"NBCNews\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/155076/obscure-newspaper-fueling-far-right-europe|title=The Obscure Newspaper Fueling the Far-Right in Europe|last=Hettena|first=Seth|date=2019-09-17|work=The New Republic|access-date=2019-12-16|issn=0028-6583}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a report by NBC News, ''The Epoch Times'' \"generally stayed out of U.S. politics\" before 2016, \"unless they dovetailed with Chinese interests.\" Ben Hurley, a former ''Epoch Times'' employee until 2013, told NBC News that the newspaper was critical toward abortion and LGBT, and that Falun Gong practitioners \"saw communism everywhere\" including in internationalist figures like [[Hillary Clinton]] and [[Kofi Annan]], \"but there was more room for disagreements in the early days.\" Since 2016, according to NBC News, ''The Epoch Times'' has promoted favorable coverage of [[Donald Trump|Donald Trump's]] campaign and presidency, and emphasized issues such as [[Islamic terrorism]] and [[illegal immigration to the United States]]. It has also emphasized \"what the publication claims is a labyrinthian, global conspiracy led by [Hillary] Clinton and former President Barack Obama to tear down Trump.\"<ref name=\"NBCNews\" />\n\nThe newspaper counters what it considers to be Chinese Communist Party propaganda through its own opinion pieces and reporting. It covers causes and groups opposed to the CCP, including Falun Gong, dissidents, activists, and supporters of the [[Central Tibetan Administration|Tibetan government-in-exile]]. The paper also reports on Falun Gong-related news, including the group's attempt to sue former [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China|Communist Party general secretary]] [[Jiang Zemin]] under civil legislation for \"[[genocide]]\", not covered by most other overseas Chinese-language newspapers.<ref name=\"sfgate2\">{{Cite news|url= https://www.sfgate.com/news/article/CULTURE-AND-RELIGION-Dissident-media-linked-to-2587555.php|title= Dissident media linked to Falun Gong / Chinese-language print, broadcast outlets in U.S. are making waves|work= San Francisco Chronicle|date= December 18, 2005|access-date= December 9, 2006|first= Vanessa|last= Hua}}</ref>\n\nThe newspaper is also at odds with the [[Taiwanese people|Taiwanese]]-owned newspaper ''[[World Journal]]'', accusing it of being a \"megaphone for the evil Chinese Communist Party\".<ref name= \"HPheartsandmind\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/chinese-press-abroad_n_4729474|title=The Chinese Press Battles For Hearts And Minds Abroad|date=February 13, 2014|website=HuffPost Canada}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.epochtimes.com/gb/14/1/24/n4067175.htm|title=\u65e7\u91d1\u5c71\u6cd5\u8f6e\u529f\u5b66\u5458\u81f4\u4e16\u754c\u65e5\u62a5\u7684\u516c\u5f00\u4fe1 - \u5927\u7eaa\u5143|date=January 24, 2014|website=\u5927\u7eaa\u5143 www.epochtimes.com}}</ref>\n\n''The Epoch Times'' is known for alleging [[conspiracy|conspiracies]] against former [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China|Communist Party general secretary]] [[Jiang Zemin]],<ref name= \"HPheartsandmind\" /> under whose administration Falun Gong was suppressed in China.\n\nIn 2005, the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' reported that \"three new U.S.-based, Chinese-language media outlets that provide provocative reporting about the Communist Party, government oppression and social unrest in China [namely ''The Epoch Times'', Sound of Hope, and NTDTV] have ties to the Falun Gong spiritual movement.\" When interviewed, executives at each outlet claimed they did not represent the Falun Gong movement as a whole.<ref name=\"sfgate2\" />\n\n''The Epoch Times'' also picks up mainstream [[News agency|newswire]] stories and in some places can resemble a community newspaper.<ref name=\"waves\">Eugenia Chien, [http://news.newamericamedia.org/news/view_article.html?article_id=6ce9872ebb88b3aaa3ff48b6c1ffc19a \"Falun Gong-Linked Media Venture Makes Waves, Raises Questions\"] {{Webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080306081937/http://news.newamericamedia.org/news/view_article.html?article_id=6ce9872ebb88b3aaa3ff48b6c1ffc19a |date=March 6, 2008}} ''New America Media'', News Analysis, May 16, 2006</ref> According to sociologist [[Yuezhi Zhao|Zhao Yuezhi]], \"While mainstream newspaper typically treat Web versions as an extension of the already-existing print version, ''The Epoch Times'' website serves as the master for all its worldwide papers.\"<ref name=\"zhao\">Zhao, Yuezhi, \"Falun Gong, Identity, and the Struggle over Meaning Inside and Outside China\", pp 209\u2013223 in ''Contesting Media Power: Alternative Media in a Networked World'', edited by Nick Couldry and James Curran (Rowman & Littlefield, 2003)</ref>\n\nIn some cases ''The Epoch Times'' operates in a hostile overseas environment, in which \"overseas Chinese media companies choosing to remain independent or publish non-approved content become the targets of an aggressive campaign of elimination or control.\" In one instance Chinese diplomatic officials made threats against media for reporting Falun Gong-related content; in other cases, advertisers have been regularly threatened not to support ''The Epoch Times'' in any way. Communist Party authorities have been accused of resorting to \"militant methods\" against the newspaper and its staff, including attacking staff and destroying computer equipment.<ref>{{Cite book|title= Qiaowu: Extra-Territorial Policies for the Overseas Chinese|last= To|first= James Jiann Hua|publisher= BRILL|year= 2014|isbn= 9789004272286|location= |pages= 180}}</ref>\n\nThe newspaper reported that in 2005 the Communist Party \"exerted hard and soft pressure\" on printing houses in Hong Kong, forcing the paper to stop printing, after it reported on Tibet, human rights, Falun Gong, and was the first media to break the story on [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS]].<ref>{{Cite book|title= Taiwan: The Threatened Democracy|last= Herschensohn|first= Bruce|publisher= WND Books|year= 2006|isbn= 9780977898428|location= |pages= 99}}</ref> The newspaper was also briefly banned from Malaysia after coming under reported pressure by the Chinese Communist Party.<ref name=Sun2009 />\n\nIn 2016, the newspaper was removed from the pharmacy of [[Australian National University]], after the president of the [[Chinese Students and Scholars Association]] confronted the pharmacist and threw out the papers. The incident drew national media coverage over questions of Chinese government sponsored overseas student organizations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/education/the-patriotic-education-of-chinese-students-at-australian-universities-20161003-gru13j.html|title=The 'patriotic education' of Chinese students at Australian universities|last=Wen|first=Alexander Joske and Philip|date=2016-10-07|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2019-08-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afr.com/world/asia/canberra-pharmacy-at-front-line-of-chinas-push-for-global-influence-20160901-gr65xy|title=Canberra pharmacy at front line of China's push for global influence|date=2016-09-01|website=Australian Financial Review|language=en|access-date=2019-08-20}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, The German edition of the newspaper, ''The Epoch Times Deutschland'', which became Web-only in 2012, was accused by online magazine ''The China File'' of being aligned with the German far-right, and attractive to supporters of the [[Alternative for Germany]] (AfD) party and the anti-immigrant group [[Pegida]].<ref name=\"Allen-Ebrahimian\" />  Stefanie Albrecht, a reporter for the German broadcaster RTL who spent several days inside the Berlin office of ''The Epoch Times'' while investigating the far right, said that ''The Epoch Times'' staffers she met had no journalistic training and didn't check facts, trusting instead in the alternative sources they consulted.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nIn [[France]], ''The Epoch TImes'' gives \"an unfettered platform to [[Jean-Marie Le Pen]], the patriarch of the French far right, and his daughter, [[Marine Le Pen|Marine]], who leads the nationalist party her father founded,\" according to ''[[The New Republic]]''.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Trump administration ==\nAccording to ''[[BuzzFeed News]]'', ''The Epoch Times'' is known as \"one of the staunchest defenders of [[Presidency of Donald Trump|Donald Trump's presidency]].\"<ref name=\":22\" /> The paper has championed Trump's [[Spygate (conspiracy theory)|Spygate conspiracy theory]] in its news coverage and advertising, and the Epoch Media Group's ''Edge of Wonder'' videos on YouTube have spread the right-wing, pro-Trump [[QAnon|QAnon conspiracy theory]].<ref name=\"NBCNews\" />\n\nThe ''Edge of Wonder'' hosts, according to ''[[The Daily Dot]]'', \"embrace QAnon completely\" even though \"almost nothing QAnon has foretold has actually taken place.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailydot.com/layer8/edge-wonder-qanon-youtube/|title=This massive YouTube channel is normalizing QAnon|date=2019-08-27|website=The Daily Dot|language=en|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> An NBC News report found that the ''Edge of Wonder'' hosts have been creative director and chief photo editor at ''The Epoch Times,'' and the newspaper promoted ''Edge of Wonder'' videos in dozens of Facebook posts through 2019.<ref name=\"NBCNews\" /> The hosts and the newspaper's publisher deny that they are currently affiliated.<ref name=\"NBCNews\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theepochtimes.com/our-response-to-nbc-news-inappropriate-questions_2971493.html|title=Our Response to NBC News' Inappropriate Questions|last=|first=|date=|work=The Epoch Times|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://edgeofwonder.tv/about|title=Edge of Wonder|website=edgeofwonder.tv|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref>\n\nIn a response to a ''BuzzFeed'' report about ''The Epoch Times''' coverage of Trump, ''The Epoch Times'' editor-in-chief Jasper Fakkert wrote in a letter to readers: \"We see the Trump administration's efforts to change socialist policies in America, as well as set policies to counter infiltration and subversion by China, as remarkable reversals from past policies, and sincere efforts that, if fully realized, will benefit America and the world as a whole.\"<ref name=\":22\" /><ref name=\":32\" />\n\nIn April 2018, ''The Epoch Times'' publisher Stephen Gregory and editor-in-chief Jasper Fakkert reported a third-hand claim that [[Donald Trump]] reads ''The Epoch Times'' every day and \"it's the one newspaper that he believes to be a truthful and correct paper.\"<ref name=\":22\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theepochtimes.com/trump-said-to-describe-the-epoch-times-as-most-credible-newspaper_2495714.html|title=Trump Said to Describe The Epoch Times as 'Most Credible Newspaper'|date=2018-04-16|website=The Epoch Times|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2018, ''The Epoch Times'' photographer Samira Bouaou broke White House protocol and handed Trump a folder during an official event.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/white-house-reviews-incident-involving-epoch-times-photographer-handing-a-folder-to-trump/2018/09/18/e9d8b8ba-bac5-11e8-bdc0-90f81cc58c5d_story.html|title=White House reviews incident involving ''The Epoch Times'' photographer handing a folder to Trump|last=Nakamura|first=David|date=September 18, 2018|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180919014513/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/white-house-reviews-incident-involving-epoch-times-photographer-handing-a-folder-to-trump/2018/09/18/e9d8b8ba-bac5-11e8-bdc0-90f81cc58c5d_story.html?tid=pm_politics_pop|archive-date=September 19, 2018|last2=Shih|first2=Gerry|quote=The photographer, identified by other photojournalists as Samira Bouaou, passed the purple-colored folder to Trump as he was walking out of the East Room on Sept. 12 after delivering remarks at a reception for the Congressional Medal of Honor Society.}}</ref>\n\nDuring the February 2020 [[2020 Iowa Democratic caucuses|Iowa Democratic Caucuses]], ''The Epoch Times'' shared viral [[disinformation]] from the conservative group [[Judicial Watch]] that falsely alleged inflated voter rolls.<ref name=\":8\" /> The claim, which went viral on Facebook, was debunked by fact checkers and the Iowa secretary of state.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/live-blog/iowa-caucuses-live-updates-2020-democrats-make-their-final-pitches-n1128596/ncrd1128966|title=Debunked claims about Iowa voter fraud pushed by conservative activists|last=Brandy Zadrozny26d ago / 8:32 PM UTC|website=NBC News|language=en|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/story/iowa-misinformation-spreads-online-despite-new-policies/|title=Iowa Misinformation Spreads Online, Despite New Policies|work=Wired|access-date=2020-02-29|language=en|issn=1059-1028}}</ref> A Harvard media expert quoted by NBC News said ''The Epoch Times'' employed a \"classic disinformation tactic\" known as \"trading up the chain,\" in which false stories are repackaged and shared.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\n=== Advertising controversies ===\n\n==== Ad ban on Facebook ====\nDuring a six month period in 2019, ''The Epoch Times'' spent more than $1.5 million on about 11,000 Facebook ads that NBC News said were \"pro-Trump advertisements\". NBC said the amount spent was more than any group except the Trump campaign itself.<ref name=\"NBCNews\" /><ref name=\"BI-facebook\" /> Political ad spending on Facebook in April 2019 through an account called \"Coverage of the Trump Presidency by The Epoch Times\" exceeded any politician's spending except Trump and Democrat [[Joe Biden]].<ref name=\":42\" /><ref name=\"FWIW: Where are they now\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.anotheracronym.org/newsletter/where-are-they-now/|title=FWIW: Where are they now?|website=ACRONYM|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> Journalist [[Judd Legum]] wrote in May 2019 that ''The Epoch Times'' ads were \"boosting Donald Trump and floating conspiracy theories about Joe Biden\".<ref name=\":42\" /><ref name=\"FWIW: Where are they now\" />\n\nIn August 2019, [[Facebook]] banned ''The Epoch Times'' from advertising on its platform, after finding that the newspaper broke Facebook's political transparency rules by publishing pro-Trump subscription ads through [[Sockpuppet (Internet)|sockpuppet]] pages such as \u201cHonest Paper\u201d and \u201cPure American Journalism.\"<ref name=\"Zadrozny-bans-CNBC\" /><ref name=\":4\" /> A Facebook representative told NBC: \"Over the past year we removed accounts associated with ''The Epoch Times'' for violating our ad policies, including trying to get around our review systems.\" <ref name=\"Zadrozny-bans-CNBC\" />\n\n''The Epoch Times'' publisher, Stephen Gregory, wrote in response that the paper didn't intend to violate Facebook's rules. The video ads, he wrote, \"are overtly ''Epoch Times'' advertisements for our subscriptions,\u201d and \"discuss ''The Epoch Times''\u2019 editorial and feature content and encourage people to subscribe to our print newspaper.\"<ref name=\"Zadrozny-bans-CNBC\" /> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theepochtimes.com/epoch-times-statement-in-response-to-nbc-facebook-stories_3053492.html|title=Epoch Times Statement in Response to NBC Facebook Stories|date=2019-08-23|website=www.theepochtimes.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-24}}</ref>\n\n==== Removal of ''The BL'' on Facebook ====\nIn October 2019, the fact-checking website [[Snopes]] reported that ''The Epoch Times'' is closely linked to a large network of Facebook pages and groups called ''The BL'' (''The Beauty of Life'') that shares pro-Trump views and conspiracy theories such as [[QAnon]]. ''The BL'' has spent at least $510,698 on Facebook advertising. Hundreds of the ads were removed for violations of Facebook's advertising rules. The ''BL'' network of pages has 28 million followers on Facebook in total, according to ''Snopes''. The editor-in-chief of ''The BL'' recently worked as editor-in-chief of ''The Epoch Times,'' and several other ''BL'' employees are listed as current or former employees of ''The Epoch Times''. ''The BL'' is registered in [[Middletown, Orange County, New York|Middletown]], [[New York (state)|New York]], to an address that also is registered to Falun Gong's ''Sound of Hope Radio Network'' and is associated with the YouTube series ''Beyond Science,'' but Snopes found \"the outlet as a whole is literally the English-language edition of ''Epoch Times'' Vietnam.\"<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.snopes.com/news/2019/10/11/pro-trump-outlet-linked-epoch-times/|title=EXCLUSIVE: Expanding Pro-Trump Outlet 'The BL' Is Closely Linked to The Epoch Times|website=Snopes.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-12}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.snopes.com/news/2019/12/13/facebook-bl-cib/|title=If Facebook Is Dealing with Deceptive 'BL' Network, It's Not Working|website=Snopes.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-15}}</ref> Snopes found that''The BL'' uses more than 300 fake Facebook profiles based in Vietnam and other countries, using names, stock photos and celebrity photos in their profiles to emulate Americans, to administer more than 150 pro-Trump Facebook groups amplifying its content.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.snopes.com/news/2019/11/12/bl-fake-profiles/|title=How a Pro-Trump Network Is Building a Fake Empire on Facebook and Getting Away with It|website=Snopes.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-15}}</ref>\n\nAn unnamed representative of ''The BL'' wrote to ''Snopes'' that \u201cThe BL has NO connection with ''The Epoch Times'',\" and a \"few of our staff has job experience \u2026 working in ''The Epoch Times'', but now they are working full time in The BL.\u201d ''The Epoch Times''\u2019 publisher, Stephen Gregory, said \u201c''The Epoch Times'' is not affiliated with the BL.\u201d <ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn December 2019, Facebook announced it removed a large network of accounts, pages, and groups linked to The BL and Epoch Media Group for coordinated inauthentic behavior on behalf of a foreign actor. The network had 55 million followers on Facebook and Instagram, and $9.5 million had been spent on Facebook ads through its accounts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://about.fb.com/news/2019/12/removing-coordinated-inauthentic-behavior-from-georgia-vietnam-and-the-us/|title=Removing Coordinated Inauthentic Behavior From Georgia, Vietnam and the US|date=2019-12-20|website=About Facebook|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-20}}</ref>\n\nOn December 20, 2019, ''The New York Times'' reported, in \"Facebook Discovers Fakes That Show Evolution of [[Fake news|Disinformation]]\", that Facebook had deleted \"hundreds of accounts with ties to the Epoch Media Group, parent company of the Falun Gong-related publication and conservative news outlet ''The Epoch Times''\" using fake profile photos that had been generated using [[artificial intelligence]]. The [[Atlantic Council#The Digital Forensic Research Lab (DFRLab)|Atlantic Council Digital Forensic Research Lab]] (DFRLab) director Graham Brookie stated that the coordinated network of fake accounts demonstrated \"an eerie, tech-enabled future of disinformation\". Facebook's head of security policy, Nathaniel Gleicher, said, \"What\u2019s new here is that this is purportedly a U.S.-based media company leveraging foreign actors posing as Americans to push political content. We\u2019ve seen it a lot with state actors in the past.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/20/business/facebook-ai-generated-profiles.html?ribbon-ad-idx=2&rref=business|title=Facebook Discovers Fakes That Show Evolution of Disinformation|website=The New York Times|language=en|date=2019-12-20|access-date=2019-01-03}}</ref><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/tech/tech-news/facebook-says-pro-trump-media-outlet-used-artificial-intelligence-create-n1105951|title=Facebook says a pro-Trump media outlet used artificial intelligence to create fake people and push conspiracies|website=NBC News|language=en|access-date=2019-12-23}}</ref>\n\n==== YouTube ads ====\nAs Facebook banned ''The Epoch Times'' from advertising, the newspaper shifted its spending to [[YouTube]]. ''The Epoch Times'' has spent more than $1 million on YouTube ads, some promoting conspiracy theories,''The New York Times'' reported in February 2020.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n== Editorials ==\n=== Nine commentaries on the Communist Party ===\nIn November 2004, the Chinese version of ''The Epoch Times'' published a series of editorials titled \"Nine Commentaries on the Communist Party\"<ref name=9com>[http://www.ninecommentaries.com/english \"Nine Commentaries on the Communist Party\"] ninecommentaries.com/english</ref> ({{Lang-zh|t=\u4e5d\u8a55\u5171\u7522\u9ee8|s=\u4e5d\u8bc4\u5171\u4ea7\u515a|first=t|links=no}}). The editorials detail what ''The Epoch Times'' characterizes as the CCP's violent political campaigns throughout its history, from its ascent to power under [[Mao Zedong]] to its present-day form. The CCP is criticized as an illegitimate institution that used underhanded tactics to gain power. The commentaries allege that the CCP \"destroyed traditional Chinese culture\" and call the CCP an \"evil cult\".<ref>{{Cite web|author=The Epoch Times Dec 26, 2004 |url=https://www.theepochtimes.com/commentary-8-on-how-the-chinese-communist-party-is-an-evil-cult_3950.html |title=Part 8: On How the Chinese Communist Party Is an Evil Cult |work=The Epoch Times |date=December 26, 2004 |access-date=December 18, 2009}}</ref> According to China scholar David Ownby, the Nine Commentaries are a \"condemnation of communism and a direct indictment of the legitimacy of the Chinese Communist Party's rule in China\". While acknowledging the \"unnecessary violence\" the Chinese Communist Party has inflicted, Ownby finds that the lack of balance and nuance in tone and style makes the editorials resemble \"anti-Communist propaganda written in Taiwan in the 1950s.\"<ref name=\"DO2\" />\n\nThe Nine Commentaries have been translated into more than 30 other languages<ref name=9com /> and released as a DVD.<ref name=9comDVD>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=s8oaUepvc70 \"Nine Commentaries on the Communist Party\"] NTDTV youtube.com</ref>\n\n''The Epoch Times'' website hosts a \"CCP Renunciations\" service, encouraging Chinese people to quit the CCP and its related organizations. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://tuidang.epochtimes.com/|title=\u5927\u7eaa\u5143\u9000\u515a\u7f51\u7ad9|website=tuidang.epochtimes.com|access-date=2019-09-05}}</ref> The Chinese edition of the newspaper publishes the number of people who it claims have quit.\n\nUntil April 16, 2020, there were 354,283,182 people who quitted CCP and its subsidiaries as claimed on epochtimes website. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://tuidang.epochtimes.com/|title=\u5927\u7eaa\u5143\u9000\u515a\u7f51\u7ad9|website=tuidang.epochtimes.com|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n== Assessments ==\nAccording to Ming Xia, political science professor at the Graduate Center at the City University of New York, ''The Epoch Times'' represents part of Falun Gong's effort to expand to non-practitioners, and \"is part of the Falun Gong strategy to embed itself into the large civil society for influence and legitimacy\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.religionnewsblog.com/17386/epoch-times|title=Paper denies representing Falun Gong|date=February 5, 2007|publisher=Religionnewsblog.com|access-date=6 March 2014}}</ref> He described ''The Epoch Times'' staff as largely part-time and volunteer, and said they \"do not follow the protocols professional journalists abide by.\"<ref name=\":5\"/>\n\n''The Epoch Times'' has been criticized by some scholars for biases, particularly regarding the Chinese Communist Party and mainland China issues, as well as for being a \"mouthpiece\" of the [[Falun Gong]] movement.<ref name=\"Groot, Stafford 2012\" /><ref name=\"Thornton2008\" /><ref name=\"James Jiann Hua To, 2014\" /><ref name=\"Elwood2007\" /><ref name=\"Sun2009\" /><ref name=\"Denton2011\" /> James To<!-- Not the Hong Kong legislator -->, a New Zealand political scientist, described ''The Epoch Times'' as the \"primary mouthpiece\" of Falun Gong, writing that it \"lacks credibility\", despite the newspaper posing a \"viable threat to the CCP\" by publishing articles about the party's negative aspects.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=To|first=James|date=December 2012|title=Beijing's Policies for Managing Han and Ethnic-Minority Chinese Communities Abroad|journal=Journal of Current Chinese Affairs|volume=41|pages=183\u2013221|doi=10.1177/186810261204100407|number=4}}</ref> In his book ''Blocked on Weibo: What Gets Suppressed on China's Version of Twitter and Why,'' [[University of Toronto]] [[research fellow]] Jason Q. Ng referred to the paper's coverage of mainland China issues as \"heavily biased against the Communist Party\" and thus its reportage \"should be viewed skeptically.\"<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kHARBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA127|title=Blocked on Weibo: What Gets Suppressed on China's Version of Twitter (And Why)|last=Ng|first=Jason Q.|date=August 27, 2013|publisher=New Press|isbn=9781595588715|page=127}}</ref>\n\nSeth Hettna wrote in ''[[The New Republic]]'' that ''The Epoch Times'' \"has built a global propaganda machine, similar to Russia\u2019s [[Sputnik (news agency)|Sputnik]] or [[RT (TV network)|RT]], that pushes a mix of alternative facts and conspiracy theories that has won it far-right acolytes around the world.\"<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nJoan Donovan of the [[Shorenstein Center on Media, Politics and Public Policy]] at [[Harvard University]] called ''The Epoch Times'' \"a known [[disinformation]] operation\".<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/tech/social-media/wake-call-iowa-caucus-disinformation-serves-warning-about-2020-election-n1130111|title='Wake-up call': Iowa caucus disinformation serves as warning about 2020 election|website=NBC News|language=en|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref>\n\nBen Collins of [[NBC News]] called ''The Epoch Times'' a \"pro-Trump conspiracy website.\"<ref name=\":9\" />\n\nThe paper has also been lauded by some political commentators and media experts. [[Ethan Gutmann]] of the [[Foundation for Defense of Democracies]], a [[Neoconservatism|neoconservative]] think tank, has characterized ''The Epoch Times'' as a leader in political analysis of the Chinese regime, writing: \"With the \"Chinese Regime in Crisis\" series, ''Epoch Times'' has finally and indisputably arrived. Any China expert who wants to save face by pretending the paper doesn't exist can continue to do so\u2014for a little while anyway\u2014but they had better be reading it in secret.\"<ref>Ethan Gutman, Facebook. (23 Apr 2012) [https://www.facebook.com/ethan.gutmann/posts/10150841176268179 Now quoted by the paper]</ref>\n\nJames Bettinger, a professor of Communications at [[Stanford University]] and the director of the John S. Knight Journalism Fellowships, said \"Even if ''Epoch Times'' is not associated with Falun Gong, if they consistently write about Falun Gong in the same perspective, or if there are no articles examining Falun Gong, people would perceive it as being not credible.\"<ref name=\"waves2\">Eugenia Chien, [http://news.newamericamedia.org/news/view_article.html?article_id=6ce9872ebb88b3aaa3ff48b6c1ffc19a \"Falun Gong-Linked Media Venture Makes Waves, Raises Questions\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080306081937/http://news.newamericamedia.org/news/view_article.html?article_id=6ce9872ebb88b3aaa3ff48b6c1ffc19a|date=March 6, 2008}} ''New America Media'', News Analysis, May 16, 2006</ref> Orville Schell, dean of the Graduate School of Journalism at [[University of California, Berkeley]], said in 2005 that \"It's hard to vouch for their quality because it's difficult to corroborate, but it's not something to be dismissed as pure propaganda.\"<ref name=\"sfgate23\"/>\n\nIn his 2008 book on Falun Gong, David Ownby wrote that ''The Epoch Times'' articles are \"well written and interesting, if occasionally idiosyncratic in their coverage.\"<ref name=\"DO2\" /><ref name=\"morais\">Morais, Betsy. \"''The Epoch Times'' doesn't like to brag\", Capital Magazine, Jun. 23, 2010</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://berkleycenter.georgetown.edu/people/david-ownby|title=David Ownby|last=University|first=Berkley Center for Religion, Peace and World Affairs at Georgetown|website=berkleycenter.georgetown.edu|language=en|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> According to Ownby, the newspaper has been praised and also criticized for a perceived bias against the CCP, and support of Falun Gong practitioners and other dissidents such as Tibetans, Taiwanese independence advocates, democracy activists, Uyghurs and others. The paper, therefore, is often assessed in light of its connection to Falun Gong, rather than a thorough analysis of its editorial content.<ref>Ownby 2008, pp. ''vii''\u2013''viii'', 163, 221\u20133, 229.</ref>\n\n[[Jiao Guobiao]], a former Beijing University journalism professor who was dismissed after criticizing the [[Publicity Department of the Communist Party of China|Propaganda Department]], proposed that even if ''The Epoch Times'' published only negative information highly critical of the CCP, the weight of their attacks could never begin to counterbalance the positive propaganda the party publishes about itself. In addressing media balance, Jiao noted that the Chinese public lacked negative, critical information regarding their country. As such, he noted for a need of media balance based on the principles of freedom, equality, and legality, and that media balance \"is the result of the collective imbalances of all\".<ref name=\"Thornton2008\" />\n\nIn 2010, ''The Epoch Times'' successfully defended its reporting in the Canadian court system,<ref name=\"Canada2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.scc-csc.ca/case-dossier/info/sum-som-eng.aspx?cas=34781|title=Supreme Court of Canada - SCC Case Information - Summary - 34781|last=Canada|first=Supreme Court of|date=2001-01-01|website=www.scc-csc.ca|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref><ref>[http://www.facts.org.cn/reports/world/200805/t80351.htm Facts.org] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111005152705/http://www.facts.org.cn/reports/world/200805/t80351.htm|date=October 5, 2011}}, quoting from Xinhua, March 23, 2006 (Retrieved July 23, 2011)</ref> when a publisher it had reported on, Crescent Chau of ''[[Les Presses Chinoises]]'', sued for libel.<ref name=\"straightgood2\">Miller, John Gordon (31 May 2010) [http://www.straightgoods.ca/2010/ViewArticle.cfm?Ref=554 \"Judge rules that Falun Gong newspaper acted in the public interest\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100903024152/http://www.straightgoods.ca/2010/ViewArticle.cfm?Ref=554|date=September 3, 2010}} Straight Goods</ref> The Supreme Court of Canada ruled that ''The Epoch Times'' article expressed \"legitimate concerns and constitute an opinion which is drawn from a factual premise.\"<ref name=\"Canada2\" /> In examining the case, John Gordon Miller, a Canadian journalist and media professor, noted that articles in question \"appear to be thoroughly and professionally reported\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thejournalismdoctor.ca/Blog.php/33|title=Blog: Good journalism|last=Ubertor.com|first=John Miller, The Journalism Doctor, Bewdley, Real Estate Website by|website=thejournalismdoctor.ca|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref><ref name=\"straightgood2\" />\n\nHayes Brown of ''[[BuzzFeed News|Buzzfeed News]]'' called ''The Epoch Times'' \"one of the staunchest defenders of [[Donald Trump|Donald Trump's]] presidency.\"<ref name=\":22\" />\n\nU.S. Representative [[Paul Gosar]], Republican of Arizona, called ''The Epoch Times'' \u201cour favorite paper.\u201d<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/05/technology/epoch-times-youtube.html|title=Epoch Times, Punished by Facebook, Gets a New Megaphone on YouTube|last=Roose|first=Kevin|date=2020-02-05|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-06|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nHaifeng Huang, a professor of political science, said, \"I'm not exactly clear why they have become such a major pro-Trump voice\" but \"part of it is perhaps because they regard President Trump as tough on the Chinese government and therefore a natural ally for them\".<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nThe web-only, German edition of the paper, ''Epoch Times Deutschland'', has been criticized by media analysts<ref>Notably such media analysts include Bethany Allen-Ebrahimian of ''[[Foreign Policy]]'' magazine and Stefan Winterbauer of Germany's [[:de:Meedia|Meedia]].</ref> for its favorable coverage of far right populist groups such as the [[Alternative for Germany]] and [[Pegida]], both of which proclaim anti-immigrant views, and promotion of skepticism towards mainstream German media and politicians.<ref name=\"Allen-Ebrahimian\" /> A German media report described the outlet, along with [[Sputnik (news agency)|Sputnik News]] and Kopp Report, as a \"favorite\" of Pegida supporters, and found that its articles critical of immigration have been shared almost daily.<ref name=\":12\" />\n\nA report by the [[Institute for Strategic Dialogue]], a London-based think tank, said the German edition of ''The Epoch Times'' \"primarily runs anti-West, anti-American and pro-Kremlin content \u2013 a high proportion of this content is based on unverified information.\"<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.isdglobal.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/Make-Germany-Great-Again-ENG-061217.pdf|title=Make Germany Great Again: Kremlin, Alt-Right and International Influences in the 2017 German Elections|last=|first=|date=2017|website=Institute for Strategic Dialogue|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\n*'''2012 Queen Elizabeth II Diamond Jubilee Medal'''&nbsp;\u2014 Canadian publisher Cindy Gu of ''The Epoch Times'' was one of about 60,000 recipients awarded this commemorative medal, which honors \"significant contributions and achievements by Canadians.\"<ref>[https://www.gg.ca/en/honours/canadian-honours/directory-honours/queen-elizabeth-ii-diamond-jubilee-medal Queen Elizabeth II Diamond Jubilee Medal] The Governor General of Canada. Retrieved 28 Apr 2013</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.gg.ca/en/honours/recipients?filter_name=Cindy+Gu |title=Find a Recipient |publisher=The Governor General of Canada|date=June 11, 2018 }}</ref> She was nominated for the medal by the Canadian Centre for Abuse Awareness for raising awareness of human rights abuses in China and the organ harvesting of Falun Gong practitioners.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ausepochmedia.com/2016/10/25/epoch-times-publisher-awarded-diamond-jubilee-medal/|title=Epoch Times Publisher Awarded Diamond Jubilee Medal|date=2016-10-25|website=Chinese Newspaper - Perth Epoch Times|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-06}}</ref>\n*'''2012 National Ethnic Press and Media Council Award'''&nbsp;\u2014The Chinese edition of ''The Epoch Times'' was one of nine newspapers given an award for \"excellence in editorial/free expression, best concept and visual presentation.\"<ref>[https://www.sources.com/Releases/NR1780.htm \"National Ethnic Press and Media Council of Canada Award Recipients 2012\"] sources.com 7 November 2012</ref><ref>''The Epoch Times'' (13 November 2012) [https://www.theepochtimes.com/n2/canada/epoch-times-wins-ethnic-press-media-award-in-canada-314136.html ''The Epoch Times'' Wins Ethnic Press Media Award] Retrieved 28 Apr 2013</ref>\n*'''2012 New York Press Association Award'''&nbsp;\u2014 ''The Epoch Times'' won first place in the category \"Best Special Section&nbsp;\u2014 Advertising, Division 2\" for a special section produced for ''Asia Week'' New York in March 2012. \"A great special section has five strong components: a great cover, appealing design, good art, strong content, and well-designed complementary advertising. This section has all five\", said the NYPA judges. \"In all, this is one of the nicest sections I have ever seen produced by a newspaper.\"<ref>[http://www.freeinews.com Free-i-News.] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130421130806/http://www.freeinews.com/ |date=April 21, 2013}} (8 April 2013) [http://www.freeinews.com/global/epoch-times-wins-newspaper-excellence-award \"''The Epoch Times'' Wins Newspaper Excellence Award\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102140506/http://www.freeinews.com/global/epoch-times-wins-newspaper-excellence-award |date=November 2, 2013}} Retrieved 28 Apr 2013</ref>\n*'''2012 [[Society of Professional Journalists]]' [[Sigma Delta Chi Award]]'''&nbsp;\u2014 ''The Epoch Times'' China reporter Matthew Robertson won this award in the category of Non-Deadline Reporting in newspapers with a circulation of less than 50,000 per day, for a series of articles he wrote on forced, live organ harvesting in China.<ref name=\"SPJ22\">[https://www.spj.org/sdxa12.asp \"2012 Sigma Delta Chi Award Honorees\"], The Society of Professional Journalists, spj.org Accessed 8 Dec. 2014</ref>\n*'''2013 Newswomen's Club Award'''&nbsp;\u2014 ''The Epoch Times'' New York reporter Genevieve Belmaker won a Front Page Award from the Newswomen's Club of New York for reporting on the effects of [[Hurricane Sandy]], in the category of newspapers with a circulation of less than 100,000 per day.<ref>Newswomen's Club of New York [https://www.newswomensclubnewyork.com/2013-front-page-awards/ \"2013 Front Page Award Winners\"] {{Webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150124095018/http://www.newswomensclubnewyork.com/2013-fpa-winners |date=January 24, 2015}} newswomensclubnewyork.com</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*Falun Gong-related groups:\n:*[[New Tang Dynasty Television]]\n:*[[Shen Yun]] Performing Arts\n:*[[Sound of Hope]]\n*''[[World Journal]]''\n\n== Footnotes ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Epoch Times}}\n*[https://www.theepochtimes.com/ ''Epoch Times''] {{in lang|en}}\n*[https://epochtimes.com ''Epoch Times''] {{in lang|zh}}\n*[https://www.epochtimes.org.au/ ''Epoch Times''] Australia\n*[https://www.ninecommentaries.com/ \"Nine Commentaries on the Communist Party\"]\n\n{{Falun Gong}}\n{{Portal bar|Journalism}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Epoch Times, The}}\n[[Category:2000 establishments in New York City]]\n[[Category:Publications established in 2000]]\n[[Category:Anti-communism in the United States]]\n[[Category:Chinese-American culture in New York City]]\n[[Category:Chinese-language newspapers (Traditional Chinese)]]\n[[Category:Chinese-language newspapers published in Canada]]\n[[Category:Chinese-language newspapers published in Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Chinese-language newspapers published in the United States]]\n[[Category:Criticism of journalism]]\n[[Category:Falun Gong]]\n[[Category:Free daily newspapers]]\n[[Category:French-language newspapers published in the United States]]\n[[Category:German-language newspapers published in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Internet-related controversies]]\n[[Category:Media bias controversies]]\n[[Category:Media-related controversies]]\n[[Category:Newspapers published in New York City]]\n[[Category:Non-English-language newspapers published in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language newspapers]]\n[[Category:Conservative media in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-pc|small=yes}}\n{{Short description|Newspaper focused on China, based in New York City}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox newspaper\n| name              = The Epoch Times\n| image             = Epochtimescover.png\n| caption           = Front page of ''The Epoch Times'' New York edition for March 18, 2016\n| type              = International newspaper\n| format            = [[Broadsheet]]\n| owners            = Epoch Media Group\n| founder           = John Tang\n| publisher         = Epoch Media Group\n| foundation        = {{start date and age|2000|5|20}}\n| political         = [[Conservatism]], [[anti-Communism]], [[anti-Socialism]], [[Right-wing populism]]\n| language          = Multiple, mainly Chinese and English\n| headquarters      = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| circulation       = 1,314,375 (2012, unaudited)<ref name=WWdistribution>[http://ads.epochtimes.com/pages/distribution-pricing-newspapers-distribution.htm \"The Epoch Times \u2013 Worldwide distribution\"]. {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080817010655/http://ads.epochtimes.com/pages/distribution-pricing-newspapers-distribution.htm|date=17 August 2008}} Retrieved 6 March 2014.</ref>\n| sister newspapers =\n| website           = {{URL|https://www.theepochtimes.com/}}\n}}\n'''''The Epoch Times''''' is a multi-language newspaper.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/states/new-york/city-hall/story/2010/06/the-epoch-times-doesnt-like-to-brag-067223|title=The Epoch Times doesn't like to brag|last=Morais|first=Betsy|publisher=[[Politico]]|date=June 23, 2010}}</ref> It was founded in 2000 by John Tang and a group of [[Chinese Americans]] associated with the [[Falun Gong]] spiritual movement.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Lawrence|first=Susan V.|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB108190438992282143 |title=Falun Gong Fields Media Weapons |newspaper=Wall Street Journal |date=14 April 2004}}</ref> Though the newspaper is known for general interest topics with a focus on news about China and its [[human rights in China|human rights issues]], it has become known for its support of [[Donald Trump|U.S. President Donald Trump]] and favorable coverage of far-right politicians in Europe; a 2019 report showed it to be the second-largest funder of pro-Trump Facebook advertising after the Trump campaign.<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite news|last=Brown|first=Hayes|url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/hayesbrown/epoch-times-trump-administration-falun-gong|title=A Newspaper Banned In China Is Now One Of Trump's Biggest Defenders|work=BuzzFeed News|date=October 23, 2018|access-date=December 20, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":32\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theepochtimes.com/a-letter-to-our-readers-regarding-buzzfeeds-reporting-about-the-epoch-times_2697534.html|title=A Letter to Our Readers Regarding BuzzFeed's Reporting About The Epoch Times|date=2018-10-23|website=The Epoch Times|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-26}}</ref><ref name=\":42\">{{Cite web|url=https://popular.info/p/the-epoch-of-social-media|title=The Epoch of Social Media|website=popular.info|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref><ref name=\"NBCNews\"/><ref name=\"Zadrozny-bans-CNBC\" /><ref name=\"Allen-Ebrahimian\">{{Cite magazine|url=http://www.chinafile.com/reporting-opinion/media/german-edition-of-falun-gong-affiliated-epoch-times-aligns-far-right |title=The German Edition of Falun Gong's 'Epoch Times' Aligns with the Far Right |first=Bethany |last=Allen-Ebrahimian |publisher=Center on U.S.-China Relations at Asia Society |magazine=China File |date=23 September 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171028135010/http://www.chinafile.com/reporting-opinion/media/german-edition-of-falun-gong-affiliated-epoch-times-aligns-far-right |archive-date=28 October 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"BI-facebook\">{{Cite news |title=Aside from the Trump campaign itself, the biggest spender on pro-Trump Facebook ads is reportedly a secretive New York-based newspaper |last=Gilbert |first=Ben |date=August 21, 2019 |newspaper=Business Insider |publisher=Insider Inc. |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/epoch-times-pro-trump-facebook-ads-2019-8 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190821030349/https://www.businessinsider.com/epoch-times-pro-trump-facebook-ads-2019-8 |archive-date=21 August 2019 |url-status=live |df=dmy}}</ref><ref name=\":3\"/> The newspaper is part of the '''Epoch Media Group''', which also operates [[New Tang Dynasty Television]] (NTD).<ref name=\"NBCNews\"/> The group's news sites and [[YouTube]] channels have spread [[Conspiracy theory|conspiracy theories]] such as [[QAnon]] and [[Vaccine hesitancy|anti-vaccination]] propaganda.<ref name=\"NBCNews\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/23/technology/facebook-ads-epoch-times.html|title=Facebook Bans Ads From The Epoch Times|last=Alba|first=Davey|date=2019-08-23|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-12-16|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/8/23/20830229/epoch-times-facebook-ban-buying-ads-violating-policies-trump-propaganda|title=Epoch Times banned from advertising after sneaking pro-Trump propaganda onto Facebook|last=Gartenberg|first=Chaim|date=2019-08-23|website=The Verge|language=en|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref> \n\nFor its articles, the publication draws from a network within China, as well as staff living in the West.<ref name=\"Congressional Research Service2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.usembassy.it/pdf/other/RL33437.pdf|title=China and Falun Gong|author=Thomas Lum|date=August 11, 2006|publisher=Congressional Research Service|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120205064042/http://www.usembassy.it/pdf/other/RL33437.pdf|archivedate=February 5, 2012|df=mdy-all}} <!-- page CRS-8, list of Falun Gong-affiliated media --></ref><ref name=\"sfgate23\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.sfgate.com/news/article/CULTURE-AND-RELIGION-Dissident-media-linked-to-2587555.php|title=Dissident media linked to Falun Gong / Chinese-language print, broadcast outlets in U.S. are making waves|last=Hua|first=Vanessa|date=December 18, 2005|work=San Francisco Chronicle|access-date=December 9, 2006}}</ref><ref name=\"Schworm_Boston_Globe_12_03_20072\">{{Cite news|url=http://archive.boston.com/news/world/asia/articles/2007/12/03/chinese_american_activists_decry_chinas_communism/|title=Chinese-American activists decry China's communism|first=Peter|last=Schworm|date=December 3, 2007|work=The Boston Globe}}</ref> ''The Epoch Times'' has print editions in English, Chinese, and six other languages.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theepochtimes.com/about-us|title=The Epoch Times - About Us|website=www.theepochtimes.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-28}}</ref> Fifteen additional languages are published online only. The English edition of ''The Epoch Times'' is sold in broadsheet format Monday to Friday in New York City and Washington, D.C., and weekly across the United States and Canada.<ref name=\":0\" /> A typical issue includes news sections, including Nation, World, Business, Opinion, and Commentary, and lifestyle sections, including Travel, Life & Tradition, Mind & Body, Food, and Puzzles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://printarchive.epochtimes.com/a1/en/region.php?dir=us/nyc|title=Epoch Times: Print Archive: United States: New York City|website=epoch Times|access-date=2019-08-28}}</ref>\n\n''The Epoch Times'' has been publishing in Chinese since May 2000. It is either sold or distributed free-of-charge in 35 countries, including various international regional editions. ''The Epoch Times'' websites are blocked in mainland China.<ref>{{Cite web |url= https://www.aim.org/media-monitor/independent-chinese-newspaper-bucks-communists/|title= Independent Chinese Newspaper Bucks Communists|last1= Gossett|first1= Sherrie|date= 15 June 2005|website= aim.org|publisher= Accuracy in Media|access-date= 19 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n''The Epoch Times'' was founded in 2000 by John Tang and other [[Chinese Americans]] associated with the spiritual practice [[Falun Gong]].<ref>|title=\"The Epoch Times\", Falun Gong, and Me|https://www.williamgairdner.ca/the-epoch-times-falun-gong-and-me/</ref> The founders said they were responding to censorship inside China and a lack of international understanding about the Chinese government's repression of Falun Gong.<ref name=\"Congressional Research Service\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.usembassy.it/pdf/other/RL33437.pdf|title=China and Falun Gong|author=Thomas Lum|date=August 11, 2006|publisher=Congressional Research Service|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120205064042/http://www.usembassy.it/pdf/other/RL33437.pdf|archivedate=February 5, 2012|df=mdy-all}}<!-- page CRS-8, list of Falun Gong-affiliated media --></ref><ref>Ownby 2008, p. 223.</ref> In May 2000, the paper was first published in the [[Chinese language]] in New York, with the web launch in August 2000.<ref name=About_Us>[https://www.theepochtimes.com/n3/about-us \"''The Epoch Times'' \u2013 About Us\"] {{Webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161106083455/https://www.theepochtimes.com/n3/about-us |date=November 6, 2016}} theepochtimes.com access-date 6 March 2014</ref>\n\nBy 2003, ''The Epoch Times'' website and group of newspapers had grown into one of the largest Chinese-language news sites and newspaper groups outside China, with local editions in the U.S., Canada, Australia, New Zealand, Japan, Indonesia, Taiwan, Hong Kong, and major Western European countries.<ref name=zhao /> The first English edition launched online in 2003, followed by the New York print edition in 2004.<ref name=About_Us />\n\nIn 2000, ten of ''The Epoch Times'' correspondents were imprisoned in China, but current staff of the Chinese-language edition work in Hong Kong.<ref name=Tenth>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theepochtimes.com/n2/canada/epoch-times-marks-10-years-in-canada-53136.html |title=Epoch Times Marks 10 Years in Canada|work=Epoch Times|date=March 17, 2011|access-date=July 25, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[NBC News]], \"little is publicly known about the precise ownership, origins or influences of ''The Epoch Times'',\" and it is loosely organized into several regional [[Nonprofit organization|tax free non-profits]], under the umbrella of the Epoch Media Group, together with [[New Tang Dynasty Television]].<ref name=\"NBCNews\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/tech/tech-news/trump-qanon-impending-judgment-day-behind-facebook-fueled-rise-epoch-n1044121|title=Trump, QAnon and an impending judgment day: Behind the Facebook-fueled rise of The Epoch Times|author=Brandy Zadrozny and Ben Collins|date=August 20, 2019|publisher=NBC News}}</ref> Its revenue in 2017 was [[United States dollar|US$]]8.1 million, and reported a spending of US$7.2 million.\n\n== Distribution ==\n[[File:Epoch Times Montreal.jpg|thumb|''\u00c9poqueTimes'' headquarters in [[Montreal]]'s [[Chinatown, Montreal|Chinatown]] in 2015]]\nAs of February 2012, 67 ''The Epoch Times'' newspaper editions{{Citation needed|date=January 2020}} are published, in print in 11 languages, online in 21 languages.{{citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\nIn April 2019, videos and ads from the Epoch Media Group including ''The Epoch Times'' and New Tang Dynasty (NTD) totaled 3 billion views on Facebook, YouTube and Twitter, according to the analytics company Tubular. That ranked it 11th among all video creators, and ahead of any other traditional news publisher, according to NBC News.<ref name=\"NBCNews\" />\n\n== Relationship to Falun Gong ==\n[[Associated Press]] reporter [[Nahal Toosi]] wrote that it is \"technically inaccurate\" to say that the Falun Gong organization owns ''The Epoch Times,'' but many of the newspaper's staffers are Falun Gong practitioners. Toosi noted \"many observers\" have said Falun Gong uses the newspaper for its public relations campaigns,<ref name=\"thepost\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/02/05/AR2007020500185_pf.html|title=Paper denies representing Falun Gong|newspaper=Washington Post|access-date=4 December 2015}}</ref> and the paper is connected with the group and carries sympathetic coverage of it.<ref name=\"thepost\" /><ref name=\"Groot, Stafford 2012\" /><ref name=Elwood2007>{{Cite book |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=34vGv_HDGG8C&pg=PA217 |page=217 |title=World Religions in America |editor=Jacob Neusner |publisher=Westminster John Knox Press |year=2007 |last=Ellwood |first=Robert S. |last2=Csikszentmihalyi |first2=Mark A. |chapter=East Asian Religions |isbn=9781611640472 |quote=... the ''Epoch Times'', an anticommunist newspaper connected with Falun Gong organization...}}</ref><ref name=Sun2009>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HAsB54UlQE8C&pg=PR11 |page=xi |last=Sun |first=Wanning |title=Media and the Chinese Diaspora: Community, Communications and Commerce |publisher=Routledge |year=2009 |isbn=9781134263592 |quote=...the ''Epoch Times''&nbsp;\u2013 a globally circulated pro-Falun Gong, anti-Communist Chinese-language newspaper...}}</ref><ref name=Denton2011>{{Cite book |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ul89eeKHLGEC&pg=PA268 |page=268 |title=Places of Memory in Modern China: History, Politics, and Identity |editor=Marc Andre Matten |last=Denton |first=Kirk A. |chapter=Yan'an as a Site of Memory |publisher=Brill |year=2011 |isbn=9789004219014 |series=Leiden Series in Comparative Historiography |volume=5 |quote=An article in the anti-Communist, Falun Gong ''Epoch Times'' claims, without citing any sources, that Zhang's death was the result of an accident involving opium use.}}</ref>\n\nThe English ''Epoch Times'' chair Stephen Gregory said in 2007: \"It's not a Falun Gong newspaper. Falun Gong is a question of an individual's belief. The paper's not owned by Falun Gong, it doesn't speak for Falun Gong, it doesn't represent Falun Gong. It does cover the persecution of Falun Gong in China.\"<ref name=\"thepost\" /> In 2003 sociologist [[Yuezhi Zhao]] wrote that the paper \"displays an indisputable ideological and organizational affinity with Falun Gong\" and that it strongly emphasizes negative portrayals of the Chinese government and positive portrayals of Falun Gong. Per Zhao, ''Epoch'' portrays itself as neutral, independent, and public-interest oriented.<ref name=\"zhao\" />  \n\nCanadian scholar Clement Tong wrote<ref name=\"Groot, Stafford 2012\">{{Cite book |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Lm2tdagEnL4C&pg=PA103 |page=103 |title=The Engaging State: South Australia's Engagement with the Asia-Pacific Region |editor=John Spoehr |editor2=Purnendra Jain |chapter=China and South Australia |publisher=Wakefield Press |year=2012 |isbn=9781743051573 |last=Groot |first=Gerry |last2=Stafford |first2=Glen |quote=In related vein, another paper with wide distribution but published elsewhere is ''The Epoch Times'' (Dajiyuan shibao), the qigong meditation religious group Falun gong mouth-piece, which runs a strong anti-communist line.}}</ref><ref name=\"Thornton2008\">{{Cite book |title=Popular Protest in China |last=Thornton |first=Patricia M. |editor=Kevin J. O'Brien |pages=199\u2013200 |chapter=Manufacturing Dissent in Transnational China |publisher=Harvard University Press |isbn=9780674041585 |year=2008 |series=Harvard Contemporary China |volume=15}}</ref><ref name=\"Tong2015\">{{Cite book |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kpHvCgAAQBAJ&pg=RA2-PA71 |page=71 |editor=Jean-Guy A. Goulet |editor2=Liam D. Murphy |editor3=Anastasia Panagakos |last=Tong |first=Clement |title=Religious Diversity Today: Experiencing Religion in the Contemporary World |chapter=Western Apocalyptic Narratives in the International Arena |publisher=ABC-CLIO |year=2015 |isbn=9781440833328 |volume=3}}</ref><ref name=\"James Jiann Hua To, 2014\">{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KGe7AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA197 |page=97 |title=Qiaowu: Extra-Territorial Policies for the Overseas Chinese |author=James Jiann Hua To |publisher=Brill |year=2014 |isbn=9789004272286}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Noakes |first=Stephen |title=Falun Gong, Ten Years On |date=June 2010 |journal=Pacific Affairs |volume=83 |number=2 |pages=349\u201357 |quote=The Epoch Times newspaper also serves as a mouthpiece for Falun Gong internationally...|doi= 10.5509/2010832349}}</ref> ''The Epoch Times'' \"operates as a mouthpiece for\" Falun Gong without an official statement of affiliation with the movement.<ref name=\"Tong2015\" /> In 2008, David Ownby, director of the Center for East Asian Studies at the [[Universit\u00e9 de Montr\u00e9al]] and the author of ''Falun Gong and the Future of China'', said the newspaper is set up by Falun Gong practitioners with their own money.<ref name=\"Ownby 2008 p.223\" /> He describes ''The Epoch Times'' as wishing to be taken seriously as a global newspaper rather than being judged on the basis of its strong association with Falun Gong.<ref name=\"Ownby 2008 p.223\">{{Cite book |last=Ownby |first=David |title=Falun Gong and the Future of China |year=2008 |url=https://archive.org/details/falungongfutureo2008ownb |url-access=registration |page=[https://archive.org/details/falungongfutureo2008ownb/page/223 223] |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=9780199716371}}</ref><ref name=\"Ownby 2008 p.8\">{{Cite book |last=Ownby |first=David |title=Falun Gong and the Future of China |year=2008 |url=https://archive.org/details/falungongfutureo2008ownb |url-access=registration |page=[https://archive.org/details/falungongfutureo2008ownb/page/8 8] |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=9780199716371}}</ref> He wrote: \"''Epoch Times'' is a newspaper with a mission, that of reporting on issues bearing on human rights throughout the world, which allows for considerable focus on China and Falun Gong.\"<ref name=\"DO2\">Ownby 2008, p. 221.</ref> The paper's reporting on Chinese affairs often highlights negative news about the Chinese government, and covers Falun Gong in a sympathetic light. The paper is seen to articulate Falun Gong's views on a range of issues, and may be part of a ''de facto'' media alliance with democracy activists in exile.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Couldry|first=Nick|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yRVtAAAAQBAJ|title=Contesting Media Power: Alternative Media in a Networked World|last2=Curran|first2=James|date=2003-09-22|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield Publishers|isbn=9780742575202}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, [[Li Hongzhi]], the founder of Falun Gong, appeared at the newspaper's office in New York City and called for the expansion of ''The Epoch Times'' to \"become regular media\". Former employees also noted the involvement of Falun Gong practitioners in the management and editorial process.<ref name=\"NBCNews\" /> Three anonymous former employees said ''Epoch Times'' workers were encouraged to attend weekly \"Fa study\" sessions outside work hours to study the teachings of Li Hongzhi.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n''The Epoch Times'' runs frequent promotional stories about the [[Shen Yun]] dance troupe that is affiliated with Falun Gong. ''The New Yorker'''s review of Shen Yun called ''The Epoch Times'' \"the world\u2019s foremost purveyor of Shen Yun content.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/culture/culture-desk/stepping-into-the-uncanny-unsettling-world-of-shen-yun|title=Stepping Into the Uncanny, Unsettling World of Shen Yun|last=Tolentino|first=Jia|date=2019-03-19|access-date=2019-08-24|language=en|issn=0028-792X}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, an [[NBC News]] investigative report suggested ''The Epoch Times's'' political coverage may be affected by Falun Gong believers' anticipation of a judgment day in which communists are sent to hell, and Falun Gong's allies are spared. Former ''Epoch Times''' employees told NBC News that President Donald Trump is viewed as a key anti-communist ally,<ref name=\"NBCNews\" /> allegedly \"hastening judgement day and the delivery of communists to hell.\"<ref name=\"Zadrozny-bans-CNBC\">{{cite news |last1=Zadrozny |first1=Brandy |last2=Collins |first2=Ben |title=Facebook bans ads from The Epoch Times after huge pro-Trump buy |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/08/23/facebook-bans-ads-from-the-epoch-times-after-huge-pro-trump-buy.html |accessdate=7 October 2019 |agency=CNBC |date=23 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Notable coverage ==\n=== Organ harvesting in China ===\n{{Further|Persecution of Falun Gong#Organ harvesting |Organ harvesting from Falun Gong practitioners in China}}\nIn March 2006, ''The Epoch Times'' published the allegations of three Chinese individuals who said that thousands of [[Falun Gong]] practitioners had been killed to supply China's organ transplant industry,<ref>[https://www.theepochtimes.com/worse-than-any-nightmarejournalist-quits-china-to-expose-concentration-camp-horrors-and-bird-flu-coverup_1732938.html \"Worse Than Any Nightmare\u2014Journalist Quits China to Expose Concentration Camp Horrors and Bird Flu Coverup\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090207185741/http://en.epochtimes.com/news/6-3-10/39111.html |date=February 7, 2009}}, Epoch Times, 10 March 2006</ref><ref>[https://www.theepochtimes.com/news/6-3-17/39405.html \"New Witness Confirms Existence of Chinese Concentration Camp, Says Organs Removed from Live Victims\"] ''The Epoch Times'', 17 March 2006</ref><ref name=36cc /> including a doctor, who said there were 36 concentration camps all over China.<ref name=36cc>[https://www.theepochtimes.com/news/6-3-31/39910.html \"Source Reveals Other Chinese Concentration Camps\"] ''The Epoch Times'', 31 March 2006</ref> The [[Kilgour\u2013Matas report]]<ref name=orgharv>[[David Kilgour]], [[David Matas]] (6 July 2006, revised 31 January 2007) [http://organharvestinvestigation.net \"An Independent Investigation into Allegations of Organ Harvesting of Falun Gong Practitioners in China\"] (in 22 languages) organharvestinvestigation.net</ref> stated that \"the source of 41,500 transplants for the six year period 2000 to 2005 is unexplained\" and \"we believe that there has been and continues today to be large scale organ seizures from unwilling [[Falun Gong]] practitioners\".<ref name=orgharv /> Appendix 16 of the revised report refuted [[Harry Wu]]'s negative comments.<ref name=orgharv />\n\nIn 2008, two United Nations Special Rapporteurs reiterated their requests for \"the Chinese government to fully explain the allegation of taking vital organs from Falun Gong practitioners and the source of organs for the sudden increase in organ transplants that has been going on in China since the year 2000\".<ref>[http://www.theinformationdaily.com/2008/05/09/united-nations-human-rights-special-rapporteurs-reiterate-findings-on-chinas-organ-harvesting-from-falun-gong-practitioners \"United Nations Human Rights Special Rapporteurs Reiterate Findings on China's Organ Harvesting from Falun Gong Practitioners\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150512183828/http://www.theinformationdaily.com/2008/05/09/united-nations-human-rights-special-rapporteurs-reiterate-findings-on-chinas-organ-harvesting-from-falun-gong-practitioners |date=May 12, 2015}}, The Information Daily.com, 9 May 2008</ref> The Chinese government has consistently denied the allegations. The Foreign Affairs Subcommittee of the [[United States House of Representatives]] has adopted resolutions condemning alleged organ harvesting from Falun Gong prisoners of conscience.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/114th-congress/house-resolution/343/text |title=H.Res.343 \u2013 Expressing concern regarding persistent and credible reports of systematic, state-sanctioned organ harvesting from non-consenting prisoners of conscience in the People's Republic of China, including from large numbers of Falun Gong practitioners and members of other religious and ethnic minority groups. |author=Ileana Ros-Lehtinen |date=25 June 2015 |publisher=Library of Congress |access-date=20 December 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161122222318/https://www.congress.gov/bill/114th-congress/house-resolution/343/text |archivedate=November 22, 2016 |url-status=live |website=congress.gov |df=mdy}}</ref>\n\n=== Other reports ===\nDuring the 2009 [[New York City Comptroller]] elections, ''The Epoch Times'' alleged that [[Taiwan]]-born [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nominee [[John Liu]] is part of a \"United Front\" by the [[Communist Party of China|Chinese Communist Party]] (CCP) to infiltrate the United States and subvert its government, democracy, and human rights in general.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theepochtimes.com/n2/content/view/22317/ |title=Chinese Communist Party Subverts Democracies and Rights Abroad |work=The Epoch Times |date=September 10, 2009 |access-date=December 18, 2009}}</ref> The newspaper alleged that \"the CCP works tenaciously and systematically to place its people [...] in key positions in corporations, academia, and government in the United States and other countries.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theepochtimes.com/n2/content/view/22292/|title=Editor's Note on Coverage of John Liu: Uncovering a hidden threat|date=September 10, 2009}}</ref> ''The Epoch Times'' also published an 8-page \"special edition\", and also featured on its website a section focused on coverage of Liu's reported ties with CCP officials.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theepochtimes.com/n2/component/option,com_ettopic/topicid,57/ |title=John Liu and the United Front |work=The Epoch Times |access-date=December 18, 2009}}</ref>\n\nDuring [[Hu Jintao]]'s visit to Canada in June 2010, the ''[[Toronto Star]]'' noted that ''The Epoch Times'' had published several \"hard-hitting\" critical stories on Hu's visit, such as allegations of the local Chinese embassy's orchestration of welcome parades, as well as an alleged recording of a speech by the first secretary of education Liu Shaohua, in which Liu stated that embassy would provide accommodation and transport for over 3,000 participants in the welcome parade.<ref name=star>Susan Delacourt, [https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/torontog20summit/article/827903--harper-helps-hu-keep-critics-away \"Harper helps Hu keep critics away\"], thestar.com 25 Jun 2010</ref>\n\nCanadian media reported that the parliamentary press office made deliberate arrangements in relation to Hu's public appearances limiting ''The Epoch Times''{{'}} access to the [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China]], even though the newspaper is an accredited member of the Canadian Parliamentary Press Gallery.<ref name=star /> The paper carried an exclusive interview with outspoken Canadian Member of Parliament [[Rob Anders]], wherein Anders alleged that the Chinese government used gifts and business deals in attempts to influence Canadian political decisions.<ref name='Secrecy'>{{Cite news |first=Norma |last=Greenaway |title=Liberals decry secrecy around CSIS report |date=August 3, 2010 |url=https://vancouversun.com/news/Liberals+decry+secrecy+around+CSIS+report/3355144/story.html |work=Vancouver Sun |access-date=2012-05-25 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100805081220/http://www.vancouversun.com/news/Liberals+decry+secrecy+around+CSIS+report/3355144/story.html |archivedate=2010-08-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vancourier.com/Chinese+Canadian+leader+laments+agency+allegations/3337835/story.html |title=Chinese-Canadian leader laments spy agency allegations |publisher=[[Vancouver Courier]] |date=July 29, 2010 |access-date=2012-05-25}}</ref>\n\nA story in ''The Epoch Times'' on February 17, 2020 shared a map from the internet that falsely alleged massive sulfur dioxide releases from crematoriums during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]] in China, speculating that 14,000 bodies may have been burned.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://factcheck.afp.com/map-forecast-based-past-data-not-real-time-satellite-readings|title=This map is a forecast based on past data, not real-time satellite readings|date=2020-02-20|website=AFP Fact Check|language=en|access-date=2020-02-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.epochtimes.com/b5/20/2/17/n11875579.htm|title=\u6b66\u6f22\u4e8c\u6c27\u5316\u786b\u7206\u8868 \u53f0\u5b78\u8005\uff1a\u71d2\u5c4d\u9ad4\u662f\u5408\u7406\u63a8\u65b7 - \u5927\u7d00\u5143|date=2020-02-17|website=\u5927\u7d00\u5143 www.epochtimes.com|language=zh-TW|access-date=2020-02-23}}</ref> A fact check by [[Agence France-Presse|AFP]] reported that the map was a NASA forecast taken out of context.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\n== Editorial stance ==\nThe editorial stance of ''The Epoch Times'' is generally considered [[anti-communism|anti-communist]], specifically opposing the [[Communist Party of China]].<ref name=\"Thornton2008\" />\n\nIn recent years, the newspaper has also been noted for favorable coverage of the [[Presidency of Donald Trump|Trump administration]], [[far-right politics in Germany|the German far right]], and the [[History of far-right movements in France|French far right]].<ref name=\"Allen-Ebrahimian\" /><ref name=\":12\">[https://meedia.de/2016/03/18/kopp-sputnik-epoch-times-co-nachrichten-aus-einem-rechten-paralleluniversum/ Kopp, Sputnik, Epoch Times & Co: Nachrichten aus einem rechten Paralleluniversum] Stefan Winterbauer, Meedia. March 13, 2016</ref><ref name=\":22\" /><ref name=\":32\" /><ref name=\"NBCNews\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/155076/obscure-newspaper-fueling-far-right-europe|title=The Obscure Newspaper Fueling the Far-Right in Europe|last=Hettena|first=Seth|date=2019-09-17|work=The New Republic|access-date=2019-12-16|issn=0028-6583}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a report by NBC News, ''The Epoch Times'' \"generally stayed out of U.S. politics\" before 2016, \"unless they dovetailed with Chinese interests.\" Ben Hurley, a former ''Epoch Times'' employee until 2013, told NBC News that the newspaper was critical toward abortion and LGBT, and that Falun Gong practitioners \"saw communism everywhere\" including in internationalist figures like [[Hillary Clinton]] and [[Kofi Annan]], \"but there was more room for disagreements in the early days.\" Since 2016, according to NBC News, ''The Epoch Times'' has promoted favorable coverage of [[Donald Trump|Donald Trump's]] campaign and presidency, and emphasized issues such as [[Islamic terrorism]] and [[illegal immigration to the United States]]. It has also emphasized \"what the publication claims is a labyrinthian, global conspiracy led by [Hillary] Clinton and former President Barack Obama to tear down Trump.\"<ref name=\"NBCNews\" />\n\nThe newspaper counters what it considers to be Chinese Communist Party propaganda through its own opinion pieces and reporting. It covers causes and groups opposed to the CCP, including Falun Gong, dissidents, activists, and supporters of the [[Central Tibetan Administration|Tibetan government-in-exile]]. The paper also reports on Falun Gong-related news, including the group's attempt to sue former [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China|Communist Party general secretary]] [[Jiang Zemin]] under civil legislation for \"[[genocide]]\", not covered by most other overseas Chinese-language newspapers.<ref name=\"sfgate2\">{{Cite news|url= https://www.sfgate.com/news/article/CULTURE-AND-RELIGION-Dissident-media-linked-to-2587555.php|title= Dissident media linked to Falun Gong / Chinese-language print, broadcast outlets in U.S. are making waves|work= San Francisco Chronicle|date= December 18, 2005|access-date= December 9, 2006|first= Vanessa|last= Hua}}</ref>\n\nThe newspaper is also at odds with the [[Taiwanese people|Taiwanese]]-owned newspaper ''[[World Journal]]'', accusing it of being a \"megaphone for the evil Chinese Communist Party\".<ref name= \"HPheartsandmind\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/chinese-press-abroad_n_4729474|title=The Chinese Press Battles For Hearts And Minds Abroad|date=February 13, 2014|website=HuffPost Canada}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.epochtimes.com/gb/14/1/24/n4067175.htm|title=\u65e7\u91d1\u5c71\u6cd5\u8f6e\u529f\u5b66\u5458\u81f4\u4e16\u754c\u65e5\u62a5\u7684\u516c\u5f00\u4fe1 - \u5927\u7eaa\u5143|date=January 24, 2014|website=\u5927\u7eaa\u5143 www.epochtimes.com}}</ref>\n\n''The Epoch Times'' is known for alleging [[conspiracy|conspiracies]] against former [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China|Communist Party general secretary]] [[Jiang Zemin]],<ref name= \"HPheartsandmind\" /> under whose administration Falun Gong was suppressed in China.\n\nIn 2005, the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' reported that \"three new U.S.-based, Chinese-language media outlets that provide provocative reporting about the Communist Party, government oppression and social unrest in China [namely ''The Epoch Times'', Sound of Hope, and NTDTV] have ties to the Falun Gong spiritual movement.\" When interviewed, executives at each outlet claimed they did not represent the Falun Gong movement as a whole.<ref name=\"sfgate2\" />\n\n''The Epoch Times'' also picks up mainstream [[News agency|newswire]] stories and in some places can resemble a community newspaper.<ref name=\"waves\">Eugenia Chien, [http://news.newamericamedia.org/news/view_article.html?article_id=6ce9872ebb88b3aaa3ff48b6c1ffc19a \"Falun Gong-Linked Media Venture Makes Waves, Raises Questions\"] {{Webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080306081937/http://news.newamericamedia.org/news/view_article.html?article_id=6ce9872ebb88b3aaa3ff48b6c1ffc19a |date=March 6, 2008}} ''New America Media'', News Analysis, May 16, 2006</ref> According to sociologist [[Yuezhi Zhao|Zhao Yuezhi]], \"While mainstream newspaper typically treat Web versions as an extension of the already-existing print version, ''The Epoch Times'' website serves as the master for all its worldwide papers.\"<ref name=\"zhao\">Zhao, Yuezhi, \"Falun Gong, Identity, and the Struggle over Meaning Inside and Outside China\", pp 209\u2013223 in ''Contesting Media Power: Alternative Media in a Networked World'', edited by Nick Couldry and James Curran (Rowman & Littlefield, 2003)</ref>\n\nIn some cases ''The Epoch Times'' operates in a hostile overseas environment, in which \"overseas Chinese media companies choosing to remain independent or publish non-approved content become the targets of an aggressive campaign of elimination or control.\" In one instance Chinese diplomatic officials made threats against media for reporting Falun Gong-related content; in other cases, advertisers have been regularly threatened not to support ''The Epoch Times'' in any way. Communist Party authorities have been accused of resorting to \"militant methods\" against the newspaper and its staff, including attacking staff and destroying computer equipment.<ref>{{Cite book|title= Qiaowu: Extra-Territorial Policies for the Overseas Chinese|last= To|first= James Jiann Hua|publisher= BRILL|year= 2014|isbn= 9789004272286|location= |pages= 180}}</ref>\n\nThe newspaper reported that in 2005 the Communist Party \"exerted hard and soft pressure\" on printing houses in Hong Kong, forcing the paper to stop printing, after it reported on Tibet, human rights, Falun Gong, and was the first media to break the story on [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS]].<ref>{{Cite book|title= Taiwan: The Threatened Democracy|last= Herschensohn|first= Bruce|publisher= WND Books|year= 2006|isbn= 9780977898428|location= |pages= 99}}</ref> The newspaper was also briefly banned from Malaysia after coming under reported pressure by the Chinese Communist Party.<ref name=Sun2009 />\n\nIn 2016, the newspaper was removed from the pharmacy of [[Australian National University]], after the president of the [[Chinese Students and Scholars Association]] confronted the pharmacist and threw out the papers. The incident drew national media coverage over questions of Chinese government sponsored overseas student organizations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/education/the-patriotic-education-of-chinese-students-at-australian-universities-20161003-gru13j.html|title=The 'patriotic education' of Chinese students at Australian universities|last=Wen|first=Alexander Joske and Philip|date=2016-10-07|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2019-08-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afr.com/world/asia/canberra-pharmacy-at-front-line-of-chinas-push-for-global-influence-20160901-gr65xy|title=Canberra pharmacy at front line of China's push for global influence|date=2016-09-01|website=Australian Financial Review|language=en|access-date=2019-08-20}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, The German edition of the newspaper, ''The Epoch Times Deutschland'', which became Web-only in 2012, was accused by online magazine ''The China File'' of being aligned with the German far-right, and attractive to supporters of the [[Alternative for Germany]] (AfD) party and the anti-immigrant group [[Pegida]].<ref name=\"Allen-Ebrahimian\" />  Stefanie Albrecht, a reporter for the German broadcaster RTL who spent several days inside the Berlin office of ''The Epoch Times'' while investigating the far right, said that ''The Epoch Times'' staffers she met had no journalistic training and didn't check facts, trusting instead in the alternative sources they consulted.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nIn [[France]], ''The Epoch TImes'' gives \"an unfettered platform to [[Jean-Marie Le Pen]], the patriarch of the French far right, and his daughter, [[Marine Le Pen|Marine]], who leads the nationalist party her father founded,\" according to ''[[The New Republic]]''.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Trump administration ==\nAccording to ''[[BuzzFeed News]]'', ''The Epoch Times'' is known as \"one of the staunchest defenders of [[Presidency of Donald Trump|Donald Trump's presidency]].\"<ref name=\":22\" /> The paper has championed Trump's [[Spygate (conspiracy theory)|Spygate conspiracy theory]] in its news coverage and advertising, and the Epoch Media Group's ''Edge of Wonder'' videos on YouTube have spread the right-wing, pro-Trump [[QAnon|QAnon conspiracy theory]].<ref name=\"NBCNews\" />\n\nThe ''Edge of Wonder'' hosts, according to ''[[The Daily Dot]]'', \"embrace QAnon completely\" even though \"almost nothing QAnon has foretold has actually taken place.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailydot.com/layer8/edge-wonder-qanon-youtube/|title=This massive YouTube channel is normalizing QAnon|date=2019-08-27|website=The Daily Dot|language=en|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref> An NBC News report found that the ''Edge of Wonder'' hosts have been creative director and chief photo editor at ''The Epoch Times,'' and the newspaper promoted ''Edge of Wonder'' videos in dozens of Facebook posts through 2019.<ref name=\"NBCNews\" /> The hosts and the newspaper's publisher deny that they are currently affiliated.<ref name=\"NBCNews\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theepochtimes.com/our-response-to-nbc-news-inappropriate-questions_2971493.html|title=Our Response to NBC News' Inappropriate Questions|last=|first=|date=|work=The Epoch Times|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://edgeofwonder.tv/about|title=Edge of Wonder|website=edgeofwonder.tv|access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref>\n\nIn a response to a ''BuzzFeed'' report about ''The Epoch Times''' coverage of Trump, ''The Epoch Times'' editor-in-chief Jasper Fakkert wrote in a letter to readers: \"We see the Trump administration's efforts to change socialist policies in America, as well as set policies to counter infiltration and subversion by China, as remarkable reversals from past policies, and sincere efforts that, if fully realized, will benefit America and the world as a whole.\"<ref name=\":22\" /><ref name=\":32\" />\n\nIn April 2018, ''The Epoch Times'' publisher Stephen Gregory and editor-in-chief Jasper Fakkert reported a third-hand claim that [[Donald Trump]] reads ''The Epoch Times'' every day and \"it's the one newspaper that he believes to be a truthful and correct paper.\"<ref name=\":22\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theepochtimes.com/trump-said-to-describe-the-epoch-times-as-most-credible-newspaper_2495714.html|title=Trump Said to Describe The Epoch Times as 'Most Credible Newspaper'|date=2018-04-16|website=The Epoch Times|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-26}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2018, ''The Epoch Times'' photographer Samira Bouaou broke White House protocol and handed Trump a folder during an official event.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/white-house-reviews-incident-involving-epoch-times-photographer-handing-a-folder-to-trump/2018/09/18/e9d8b8ba-bac5-11e8-bdc0-90f81cc58c5d_story.html|title=White House reviews incident involving ''The Epoch Times'' photographer handing a folder to Trump|last=Nakamura|first=David|date=September 18, 2018|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180919014513/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/white-house-reviews-incident-involving-epoch-times-photographer-handing-a-folder-to-trump/2018/09/18/e9d8b8ba-bac5-11e8-bdc0-90f81cc58c5d_story.html?tid=pm_politics_pop|archive-date=September 19, 2018|last2=Shih|first2=Gerry|quote=The photographer, identified by other photojournalists as Samira Bouaou, passed the purple-colored folder to Trump as he was walking out of the East Room on Sept. 12 after delivering remarks at a reception for the Congressional Medal of Honor Society.}}</ref>\n\nDuring the February 2020 [[2020 Iowa Democratic caucuses|Iowa Democratic Caucuses]], ''The Epoch Times'' shared viral [[disinformation]] from the conservative group [[Judicial Watch]] that falsely alleged inflated voter rolls.<ref name=\":8\" /> The claim, which went viral on Facebook, was debunked by fact checkers and the Iowa secretary of state.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/live-blog/iowa-caucuses-live-updates-2020-democrats-make-their-final-pitches-n1128596/ncrd1128966|title=Debunked claims about Iowa voter fraud pushed by conservative activists|last=Brandy Zadrozny26d ago / 8:32 PM UTC|website=NBC News|language=en|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/story/iowa-misinformation-spreads-online-despite-new-policies/|title=Iowa Misinformation Spreads Online, Despite New Policies|work=Wired|access-date=2020-02-29|language=en|issn=1059-1028}}</ref> A Harvard media expert quoted by NBC News said ''The Epoch Times'' employed a \"classic disinformation tactic\" known as \"trading up the chain,\" in which false stories are repackaged and shared.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\n=== Advertising controversies ===\n\n==== Ad ban on Facebook ====\nDuring a six month period in 2019, ''The Epoch Times'' spent more than $1.5 million on about 11,000 Facebook ads that NBC News said were \"pro-Trump advertisements\". NBC said the amount spent was more than any group except the Trump campaign itself.<ref name=\"NBCNews\" /><ref name=\"BI-facebook\" /> Political ad spending on Facebook in April 2019 through an account called \"Coverage of the Trump Presidency by The Epoch Times\" exceeded any politician's spending except Trump and Democrat [[Joe Biden]].<ref name=\":42\" /><ref name=\"FWIW: Where are they now\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.anotheracronym.org/newsletter/where-are-they-now/|title=FWIW: Where are they now?|website=ACRONYM|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> Journalist [[Judd Legum]] wrote in May 2019 that ''The Epoch Times'' ads were \"boosting Donald Trump and floating conspiracy theories about Joe Biden\".<ref name=\":42\" /><ref name=\"FWIW: Where are they now\" />\n\nIn August 2019, [[Facebook]] banned ''The Epoch Times'' from advertising on its platform, after finding that the newspaper broke Facebook's political transparency rules by publishing pro-Trump subscription ads through [[Sockpuppet (Internet)|sockpuppet]] pages such as \u201cHonest Paper\u201d and \u201cPure American Journalism.\"<ref name=\"Zadrozny-bans-CNBC\" /><ref name=\":4\" /> A Facebook representative told NBC: \"Over the past year we removed accounts associated with ''The Epoch Times'' for violating our ad policies, including trying to get around our review systems.\" <ref name=\"Zadrozny-bans-CNBC\" />\n\n''The Epoch Times'' publisher, Stephen Gregory, wrote in response that the paper didn't intend to violate Facebook's rules. The video ads, he wrote, \"are overtly ''Epoch Times'' advertisements for our subscriptions,\u201d and \"discuss ''The Epoch Times''\u2019 editorial and feature content and encourage people to subscribe to our print newspaper.\"<ref name=\"Zadrozny-bans-CNBC\" /> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theepochtimes.com/epoch-times-statement-in-response-to-nbc-facebook-stories_3053492.html|title=Epoch Times Statement in Response to NBC Facebook Stories|date=2019-08-23|website=www.theepochtimes.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-24}}</ref>\n\n==== Removal of ''The BL'' on Facebook ====\nIn October 2019, the fact-checking website [[Snopes]] reported that ''The Epoch Times'' is closely linked to a large network of Facebook pages and groups called ''The BL'' (''The Beauty of Life'') that shares pro-Trump views and conspiracy theories such as [[QAnon]]. ''The BL'' has spent at least $510,698 on Facebook advertising. Hundreds of the ads were removed for violations of Facebook's advertising rules. The ''BL'' network of pages has 28 million followers on Facebook in total, according to ''Snopes''. The editor-in-chief of ''The BL'' recently worked as editor-in-chief of ''The Epoch Times,'' and several other ''BL'' employees are listed as current or former employees of ''The Epoch Times''. ''The BL'' is registered in [[Middletown, Orange County, New York|Middletown]], [[New York (state)|New York]], to an address that also is registered to Falun Gong's ''Sound of Hope Radio Network'' and is associated with the YouTube series ''Beyond Science,'' but Snopes found \"the outlet as a whole is literally the English-language edition of ''Epoch Times'' Vietnam.\"<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.snopes.com/news/2019/10/11/pro-trump-outlet-linked-epoch-times/|title=EXCLUSIVE: Expanding Pro-Trump Outlet 'The BL' Is Closely Linked to The Epoch Times|website=Snopes.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-12}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.snopes.com/news/2019/12/13/facebook-bl-cib/|title=If Facebook Is Dealing with Deceptive 'BL' Network, It's Not Working|website=Snopes.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-15}}</ref> Snopes found that''The BL'' uses more than 300 fake Facebook profiles based in Vietnam and other countries, using names, stock photos and celebrity photos in their profiles to emulate Americans, to administer more than 150 pro-Trump Facebook groups amplifying its content.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.snopes.com/news/2019/11/12/bl-fake-profiles/|title=How a Pro-Trump Network Is Building a Fake Empire on Facebook and Getting Away with It|website=Snopes.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-15}}</ref>\n\nAn unnamed representative of ''The BL'' wrote to ''Snopes'' that \u201cThe BL has NO connection with ''The Epoch Times'',\" and a \"few of our staff has job experience \u2026 working in ''The Epoch Times'', but now they are working full time in The BL.\u201d ''The Epoch Times''\u2019 publisher, Stephen Gregory, said \u201c''The Epoch Times'' is not affiliated with the BL.\u201d <ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn December 2019, Facebook announced it removed a large network of accounts, pages, and groups linked to The BL and Epoch Media Group for coordinated inauthentic behavior on behalf of a foreign actor. The network had 55 million followers on Facebook and Instagram, and $9.5 million had been spent on Facebook ads through its accounts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://about.fb.com/news/2019/12/removing-coordinated-inauthentic-behavior-from-georgia-vietnam-and-the-us/|title=Removing Coordinated Inauthentic Behavior From Georgia, Vietnam and the US|date=2019-12-20|website=About Facebook|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-20}}</ref>\n\nOn December 20, 2019, ''The New York Times'' reported, in \"Facebook Discovers Fakes That Show Evolution of [[Fake news|Disinformation]]\", that Facebook had deleted \"hundreds of accounts with ties to the Epoch Media Group, parent company of the Falun Gong-related publication and conservative news outlet ''The Epoch Times''\" using fake profile photos that had been generated using [[artificial intelligence]]. The [[Atlantic Council#The Digital Forensic Research Lab (DFRLab)|Atlantic Council Digital Forensic Research Lab]] (DFRLab) director Graham Brookie stated that the coordinated network of fake accounts demonstrated \"an eerie, tech-enabled future of disinformation\". Facebook's head of security policy, Nathaniel Gleicher, said, \"What\u2019s new here is that this is purportedly a U.S.-based media company leveraging foreign actors posing as Americans to push political content. We\u2019ve seen it a lot with state actors in the past.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/20/business/facebook-ai-generated-profiles.html?ribbon-ad-idx=2&rref=business|title=Facebook Discovers Fakes That Show Evolution of Disinformation|website=The New York Times|language=en|date=2019-12-20|access-date=2019-01-03}}</ref><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/tech/tech-news/facebook-says-pro-trump-media-outlet-used-artificial-intelligence-create-n1105951|title=Facebook says a pro-Trump media outlet used artificial intelligence to create fake people and push conspiracies|website=NBC News|language=en|access-date=2019-12-23}}</ref>\n\n==== YouTube ads ====\nAs Facebook banned ''The Epoch Times'' from advertising, the newspaper shifted its spending to [[YouTube]]. ''The Epoch Times'' has spent more than $1 million on YouTube ads, some promoting conspiracy theories,''The New York Times'' reported in February 2020.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n== Editorials ==\n=== Nine commentaries on the Communist Party ===\nIn November 2004, the Chinese version of ''The Epoch Times'' published a series of editorials titled \"Nine Commentaries on the Communist Party\"<ref name=9com>[http://www.ninecommentaries.com/english \"Nine Commentaries on the Communist Party\"] ninecommentaries.com/english</ref> ({{Lang-zh|t=\u4e5d\u8a55\u5171\u7522\u9ee8|s=\u4e5d\u8bc4\u5171\u4ea7\u515a|first=t|links=no}}). The editorials detail what ''The Epoch Times'' characterizes as the CCP's violent political campaigns throughout its history, from its ascent to power under [[Mao Zedong]] to its present-day form. The CCP is criticized as an illegitimate institution that used underhanded tactics to gain power. The commentaries allege that the CCP \"destroyed traditional Chinese culture\" and call the CCP an \"evil cult\".<ref>{{Cite web|author=The Epoch Times Dec 26, 2004 |url=https://www.theepochtimes.com/commentary-8-on-how-the-chinese-communist-party-is-an-evil-cult_3950.html |title=Part 8: On How the Chinese Communist Party Is an Evil Cult |work=The Epoch Times |date=December 26, 2004 |access-date=December 18, 2009}}</ref> According to China scholar David Ownby, the Nine Commentaries are a \"condemnation of communism and a direct indictment of the legitimacy of the Chinese Communist Party's rule in China\". While acknowledging the \"unnecessary violence\" the Chinese Communist Party has inflicted, Ownby finds that the lack of balance and nuance in tone and style makes the editorials resemble \"anti-Communist propaganda written in Taiwan in the 1950s.\"<ref name=\"DO2\" />\n\nThe Nine Commentaries have been translated into more than 30 other languages<ref name=9com /> and released as a DVD.<ref name=9comDVD>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=s8oaUepvc70 \"Nine Commentaries on the Communist Party\"] NTDTV youtube.com</ref>\n\n''The Epoch Times'' website hosts a \"CCP Renunciations\" service, encouraging Chinese people to quit the CCP and its related organizations. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://tuidang.epochtimes.com/|title=\u5927\u7eaa\u5143\u9000\u515a\u7f51\u7ad9|website=tuidang.epochtimes.com|access-date=2019-09-05}}</ref> The Chinese edition of the newspaper publishes the number of people who it claims have quit.\n\n== Assessments ==\nAccording to Ming Xia, political science professor at the Graduate Center at the City University of New York, ''The Epoch Times'' represents part of Falun Gong's effort to expand to non-practitioners, and \"is part of the Falun Gong strategy to embed itself into the large civil society for influence and legitimacy\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.religionnewsblog.com/17386/epoch-times|title=Paper denies representing Falun Gong|date=February 5, 2007|publisher=Religionnewsblog.com|access-date=6 March 2014}}</ref> He described ''The Epoch Times'' staff as largely part-time and volunteer, and said they \"do not follow the protocols professional journalists abide by.\"<ref name=\":5\"/>\n\n''The Epoch Times'' has been criticized by some scholars for biases, particularly regarding the Chinese Communist Party and mainland China issues, as well as for being a \"mouthpiece\" of the [[Falun Gong]] movement.<ref name=\"Groot, Stafford 2012\" /><ref name=\"Thornton2008\" /><ref name=\"James Jiann Hua To, 2014\" /><ref name=\"Elwood2007\" /><ref name=\"Sun2009\" /><ref name=\"Denton2011\" /> James To<!-- Not the Hong Kong legislator -->, a New Zealand political scientist, described ''The Epoch Times'' as the \"primary mouthpiece\" of Falun Gong, writing that it \"lacks credibility\", despite the newspaper posing a \"viable threat to the CCP\" by publishing articles about the party's negative aspects.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=To|first=James|date=December 2012|title=Beijing's Policies for Managing Han and Ethnic-Minority Chinese Communities Abroad|journal=Journal of Current Chinese Affairs|volume=41|pages=183\u2013221|doi=10.1177/186810261204100407|number=4}}</ref> In his book ''Blocked on Weibo: What Gets Suppressed on China's Version of Twitter and Why,'' [[University of Toronto]] [[research fellow]] Jason Q. Ng referred to the paper's coverage of mainland China issues as \"heavily biased against the Communist Party\" and thus its reportage \"should be viewed skeptically.\"<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kHARBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA127|title=Blocked on Weibo: What Gets Suppressed on China's Version of Twitter (And Why)|last=Ng|first=Jason Q.|date=August 27, 2013|publisher=New Press|isbn=9781595588715|page=127}}</ref>\n\nSeth Hettna wrote in ''[[The New Republic]]'' that ''The Epoch Times'' \"has built a global propaganda machine, similar to Russia\u2019s [[Sputnik (news agency)|Sputnik]] or [[RT (TV network)|RT]], that pushes a mix of alternative facts and conspiracy theories that has won it far-right acolytes around the world.\"<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nJoan Donovan of the [[Shorenstein Center on Media, Politics and Public Policy]] at [[Harvard University]] called ''The Epoch Times'' \"a known [[disinformation]] operation\".<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/tech/social-media/wake-call-iowa-caucus-disinformation-serves-warning-about-2020-election-n1130111|title='Wake-up call': Iowa caucus disinformation serves as warning about 2020 election|website=NBC News|language=en|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref>\n\nBen Collins of [[NBC News]] called ''The Epoch Times'' a \"pro-Trump conspiracy website.\"<ref name=\":9\" />\n\nThe paper has also been lauded by some political commentators and media experts. [[Ethan Gutmann]] of the [[Foundation for Defense of Democracies]], a [[Neoconservatism|neoconservative]] think tank, has characterized ''The Epoch Times'' as a leader in political analysis of the Chinese regime, writing: \"With the \"Chinese Regime in Crisis\" series, ''Epoch Times'' has finally and indisputably arrived. Any China expert who wants to save face by pretending the paper doesn't exist can continue to do so\u2014for a little while anyway\u2014but they had better be reading it in secret.\"<ref>Ethan Gutman, Facebook. (23 Apr 2012) [https://www.facebook.com/ethan.gutmann/posts/10150841176268179 Now quoted by the paper]</ref>\n\nJames Bettinger, a professor of Communications at [[Stanford University]] and the director of the John S. Knight Journalism Fellowships, said \"Even if ''Epoch Times'' is not associated with Falun Gong, if they consistently write about Falun Gong in the same perspective, or if there are no articles examining Falun Gong, people would perceive it as being not credible.\"<ref name=\"waves2\">Eugenia Chien, [http://news.newamericamedia.org/news/view_article.html?article_id=6ce9872ebb88b3aaa3ff48b6c1ffc19a \"Falun Gong-Linked Media Venture Makes Waves, Raises Questions\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080306081937/http://news.newamericamedia.org/news/view_article.html?article_id=6ce9872ebb88b3aaa3ff48b6c1ffc19a|date=March 6, 2008}} ''New America Media'', News Analysis, May 16, 2006</ref> Orville Schell, dean of the Graduate School of Journalism at [[University of California, Berkeley]], said in 2005 that \"It's hard to vouch for their quality because it's difficult to corroborate, but it's not something to be dismissed as pure propaganda.\"<ref name=\"sfgate23\"/>\n\nIn his 2008 book on Falun Gong, David Ownby wrote that ''The Epoch Times'' articles are \"well written and interesting, if occasionally idiosyncratic in their coverage.\"<ref name=\"DO2\" /><ref name=\"morais\">Morais, Betsy. \"''The Epoch Times'' doesn't like to brag\", Capital Magazine, Jun. 23, 2010</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://berkleycenter.georgetown.edu/people/david-ownby|title=David Ownby|last=University|first=Berkley Center for Religion, Peace and World Affairs at Georgetown|website=berkleycenter.georgetown.edu|language=en|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> According to Ownby, the newspaper has been praised and also criticized for a perceived bias against the CCP, and support of Falun Gong practitioners and other dissidents such as Tibetans, Taiwanese independence advocates, democracy activists, Uyghurs and others. The paper, therefore, is often assessed in light of its connection to Falun Gong, rather than a thorough analysis of its editorial content.<ref>Ownby 2008, pp. ''vii''\u2013''viii'', 163, 221\u20133, 229.</ref>\n\n[[Jiao Guobiao]], a former Beijing University journalism professor who was dismissed after criticizing the [[Publicity Department of the Communist Party of China|Propaganda Department]], proposed that even if ''The Epoch Times'' published only negative information highly critical of the CCP, the weight of their attacks could never begin to counterbalance the positive propaganda the party publishes about itself. In addressing media balance, Jiao noted that the Chinese public lacked negative, critical information regarding their country. As such, he noted for a need of media balance based on the principles of freedom, equality, and legality, and that media balance \"is the result of the collective imbalances of all\".<ref name=\"Thornton2008\" />\n\nIn 2010, ''The Epoch Times'' successfully defended its reporting in the Canadian court system,<ref name=\"Canada2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.scc-csc.ca/case-dossier/info/sum-som-eng.aspx?cas=34781|title=Supreme Court of Canada - SCC Case Information - Summary - 34781|last=Canada|first=Supreme Court of|date=2001-01-01|website=www.scc-csc.ca|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref><ref>[http://www.facts.org.cn/reports/world/200805/t80351.htm Facts.org] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111005152705/http://www.facts.org.cn/reports/world/200805/t80351.htm|date=October 5, 2011}}, quoting from Xinhua, March 23, 2006 (Retrieved July 23, 2011)</ref> when a publisher it had reported on, Crescent Chau of ''[[Les Presses Chinoises]]'', sued for libel.<ref name=\"straightgood2\">Miller, John Gordon (31 May 2010) [http://www.straightgoods.ca/2010/ViewArticle.cfm?Ref=554 \"Judge rules that Falun Gong newspaper acted in the public interest\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100903024152/http://www.straightgoods.ca/2010/ViewArticle.cfm?Ref=554|date=September 3, 2010}} Straight Goods</ref> The Supreme Court of Canada ruled that ''The Epoch Times'' article expressed \"legitimate concerns and constitute an opinion which is drawn from a factual premise.\"<ref name=\"Canada2\" /> In examining the case, John Gordon Miller, a Canadian journalist and media professor, noted that articles in question \"appear to be thoroughly and professionally reported\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thejournalismdoctor.ca/Blog.php/33|title=Blog: Good journalism|last=Ubertor.com|first=John Miller, The Journalism Doctor, Bewdley, Real Estate Website by|website=thejournalismdoctor.ca|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref><ref name=\"straightgood2\" />\n\nHayes Brown of ''[[BuzzFeed News|Buzzfeed News]]'' called ''The Epoch Times'' \"one of the staunchest defenders of [[Donald Trump|Donald Trump's]] presidency.\"<ref name=\":22\" />\n\nU.S. Representative [[Paul Gosar]], Republican of Arizona, called ''The Epoch Times'' \u201cour favorite paper.\u201d<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/05/technology/epoch-times-youtube.html|title=Epoch Times, Punished by Facebook, Gets a New Megaphone on YouTube|last=Roose|first=Kevin|date=2020-02-05|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-06|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nHaifeng Huang, a professor of political science, said, \"I'm not exactly clear why they have become such a major pro-Trump voice\" but \"part of it is perhaps because they regard President Trump as tough on the Chinese government and therefore a natural ally for them\".<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nThe web-only, German edition of the paper, ''Epoch Times Deutschland'', has been criticized by media analysts<ref>Notably such media analysts include Bethany Allen-Ebrahimian of ''[[Foreign Policy]]'' magazine and Stefan Winterbauer of Germany's [[:de:Meedia|Meedia]].</ref> for its favorable coverage of far right populist groups such as the [[Alternative for Germany]] and [[Pegida]], both of which proclaim anti-immigrant views, and promotion of skepticism towards mainstream German media and politicians.<ref name=\"Allen-Ebrahimian\" /> A German media report described the outlet, along with [[Sputnik (news agency)|Sputnik News]] and Kopp Report, as a \"favorite\" of Pegida supporters, and found that its articles critical of immigration have been shared almost daily.<ref name=\":12\" />\n\nA report by the [[Institute for Strategic Dialogue]], a London-based think tank, said the German edition of ''The Epoch Times'' \"primarily runs anti-West, anti-American and pro-Kremlin content \u2013 a high proportion of this content is based on unverified information.\"<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.isdglobal.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/Make-Germany-Great-Again-ENG-061217.pdf|title=Make Germany Great Again: Kremlin, Alt-Right and International Influences in the 2017 German Elections|last=|first=|date=2017|website=Institute for Strategic Dialogue|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\n*'''2012 Queen Elizabeth II Diamond Jubilee Medal'''&nbsp;\u2014 Canadian publisher Cindy Gu of ''The Epoch Times'' was one of about 60,000 recipients awarded this commemorative medal, which honors \"significant contributions and achievements by Canadians.\"<ref>[https://www.gg.ca/en/honours/canadian-honours/directory-honours/queen-elizabeth-ii-diamond-jubilee-medal Queen Elizabeth II Diamond Jubilee Medal] The Governor General of Canada. Retrieved 28 Apr 2013</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.gg.ca/en/honours/recipients?filter_name=Cindy+Gu |title=Find a Recipient |publisher=The Governor General of Canada|date=June 11, 2018 }}</ref> She was nominated for the medal by the Canadian Centre for Abuse Awareness for raising awareness of human rights abuses in China and the organ harvesting of Falun Gong practitioners.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ausepochmedia.com/2016/10/25/epoch-times-publisher-awarded-diamond-jubilee-medal/|title=Epoch Times Publisher Awarded Diamond Jubilee Medal|date=2016-10-25|website=Chinese Newspaper - Perth Epoch Times|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-06}}</ref>\n*'''2012 National Ethnic Press and Media Council Award'''&nbsp;\u2014The Chinese edition of ''The Epoch Times'' was one of nine newspapers given an award for \"excellence in editorial/free expression, best concept and visual presentation.\"<ref>[https://www.sources.com/Releases/NR1780.htm \"National Ethnic Press and Media Council of Canada Award Recipients 2012\"] sources.com 7 November 2012</ref><ref>''The Epoch Times'' (13 November 2012) [https://www.theepochtimes.com/n2/canada/epoch-times-wins-ethnic-press-media-award-in-canada-314136.html ''The Epoch Times'' Wins Ethnic Press Media Award] Retrieved 28 Apr 2013</ref>\n*'''2012 New York Press Association Award'''&nbsp;\u2014 ''The Epoch Times'' won first place in the category \"Best Special Section&nbsp;\u2014 Advertising, Division 2\" for a special section produced for ''Asia Week'' New York in March 2012. \"A great special section has five strong components: a great cover, appealing design, good art, strong content, and well-designed complementary advertising. This section has all five\", said the NYPA judges. \"In all, this is one of the nicest sections I have ever seen produced by a newspaper.\"<ref>[http://www.freeinews.com Free-i-News.] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130421130806/http://www.freeinews.com/ |date=April 21, 2013}} (8 April 2013) [http://www.freeinews.com/global/epoch-times-wins-newspaper-excellence-award \"''The Epoch Times'' Wins Newspaper Excellence Award\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102140506/http://www.freeinews.com/global/epoch-times-wins-newspaper-excellence-award |date=November 2, 2013}} Retrieved 28 Apr 2013</ref>\n*'''2012 [[Society of Professional Journalists]]' [[Sigma Delta Chi Award]]'''&nbsp;\u2014 ''The Epoch Times'' China reporter Matthew Robertson won this award in the category of Non-Deadline Reporting in newspapers with a circulation of less than 50,000 per day, for a series of articles he wrote on forced, live organ harvesting in China.<ref name=\"SPJ22\">[https://www.spj.org/sdxa12.asp \"2012 Sigma Delta Chi Award Honorees\"], The Society of Professional Journalists, spj.org Accessed 8 Dec. 2014</ref>\n*'''2013 Newswomen's Club Award'''&nbsp;\u2014 ''The Epoch Times'' New York reporter Genevieve Belmaker won a Front Page Award from the Newswomen's Club of New York for reporting on the effects of [[Hurricane Sandy]], in the category of newspapers with a circulation of less than 100,000 per day.<ref>Newswomen's Club of New York [https://www.newswomensclubnewyork.com/2013-front-page-awards/ \"2013 Front Page Award Winners\"] {{Webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150124095018/http://www.newswomensclubnewyork.com/2013-fpa-winners |date=January 24, 2015}} newswomensclubnewyork.com</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*Falun Gong-related groups:\n:*[[New Tang Dynasty Television]]\n:*[[Shen Yun]] Performing Arts\n:*[[Sound of Hope]]\n*''[[World Journal]]''\n\n== Footnotes ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Epoch Times}}\n*[https://www.theepochtimes.com/ ''Epoch Times''] {{in lang|en}}\n*[https://epochtimes.com ''Epoch Times''] {{in lang|zh}}\n*[https://www.epochtimes.org.au/ ''Epoch Times''] Australia\n*[https://www.ninecommentaries.com/ \"Nine Commentaries on the Communist Party\"]\n\n{{Falun Gong}}\n{{Portal bar|Journalism}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Epoch Times, The}}\n[[Category:2000 establishments in New York City]]\n[[Category:Publications established in 2000]]\n[[Category:Anti-communism in the United States]]\n[[Category:Chinese-American culture in New York City]]\n[[Category:Chinese-language newspapers (Traditional Chinese)]]\n[[Category:Chinese-language newspapers published in Canada]]\n[[Category:Chinese-language newspapers published in Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Chinese-language newspapers published in the United States]]\n[[Category:Criticism of journalism]]\n[[Category:Falun Gong]]\n[[Category:Free daily newspapers]]\n[[Category:French-language newspapers published in the United States]]\n[[Category:German-language newspapers published in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Internet-related controversies]]\n[[Category:Media bias controversies]]\n[[Category:Media-related controversies]]\n[[Category:Newspapers published in New York City]]\n[[Category:Non-English-language newspapers published in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language newspapers]]\n[[Category:Conservative media in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "TorLiu", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNine commentaries on the Communist Party", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Epoch_Times"}
{"title_page": "Sully Bonnelly", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{autobiography|date=June 2012}}\n{{BLP sources|date=June 2012}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox fashion designer\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| name               = Sully Bonnelly\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1956|12|24}}\n| birth_place        = [[Santo Domingo]], [[Dominican Republic]]\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| citizenship        = [[United States]], [[Dominican Republic]]\n| education          = \n| label_name         = \n| spouse             = [[Robert R. Littman]]\n| awards             = Golden Coast Award ([[Chicago]] 1999)\n| website            = http://www.sullybonnelly.com\n}}\n'''Sully Bonnelly''', in full '''Sully Osvaldo Bonnelly Cana\u00e1n''' (born December 24, 1956), is a [[Dominican Republic|Dominican]] fashion designer of women's clothing. He is the Creative Director for Sully Bonnelly.\n\n==Early years==\nBonnelly was born into a family of both [[Corsican people|Corsican]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Falleci\u00f3 el padre del dise\u00f1ador Sully Bonelly|url=http://www.listindiario.com/la-republica/2008/12/7/83743/Fallecio-el-padre-del-disenador-Sully-Bonelly|publisher=[[List\u00edn Diario]]|accessdate=24 April 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140424004243/http://www.listindiario.com/la-republica/2008/12/7/83743/Fallecio-el-padre-del-disenador-Sully-Bonelly|archivedate=24 April 2014|location=Santo Domingo|language=Spanish|date=7 December 2008|quote=Dedic\u00f3 a\u00f1os investigando todo lo referente al apellido Bonnelly y sus or\u00edgenes hist\u00f3ricos. Fue quien organiz\u00f3 exitosamente los dos encuentros de las distintas ramas de esta gran familia, realizados hace varios a\u00f1os. Viaj\u00f3 a C\u00f3rcega tierra de origen del primer Bonnelly que se asent\u00f3 en la Rep\u00fablica Dominicana, e hizo un levantamiento de sus ancestros. Interesado en la unidad familiar de los Bonnelly estaba escribiendo un libro para dejarlo como legado. Sus restos mortales ser\u00e1n tra\u00eddos en los pr\u00f3ximos d\u00edas a la ciudad de Santo Domingo, Rep\u00fablica Dominicana.}}</ref> and [[French people|French]] descent.<ref>{{cite web|author=Ivonna Ginebra|title=Segundo Encuentro de la Familia Bonnelly|url=http://www.idg.org.do/ensayos/1995/bonnelly.pdf |accessdate=24 April 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140424003550/http://www.idg.org.do/ensayos/1995/bonnelly.pdf |archivedate=24 April 2014 |publisher=Instituto Dominicano de Genealog\u00eda |year=1995}}</ref> An uncle of him, [[Rafael Filiberto Bonnelly|Rafael Bonnelly-Fondeur]], became [[president of the Dominican Republic]] from 1962 to 1963.\n\nBonnelly studied architecture at [[Universidad Aut\u00f3noma de Santo Domingo]] and later moved to New York, where he studied at [[Parsons School of Design]] and began his career in fashion as [[Oscar de la Renta]]\u2019s assistant. He also worked as a designer for the houses of [[Bill Blass]] and Eli Tahari before starting his own collection in 1998, retailing at [[Saks Fifth Avenue]], [[Neiman Marcus]], [[Bergdorf Goodman]] and other stores around the globe. Later in his career, he returned to Oscar de la Renta as creative director for the O Oscar Collection.\n\n=== Ancestors ===\n{{ahnentafel\n|collapsed=yes |align=center\n|boxstyle_1=background-color: #fcc;\n|boxstyle_2=background-color: #fb9;\n|boxstyle_3=background-color: #ffc;\n|boxstyle_4=background-color: #bfc;\n|boxstyle_5=background-color: #9fe;\n| 1=  1. '''Sully Osvaldo Bonnelly Cana\u00e1n'''\n| 2=  2. Carlos Sully Rafael Jos\u00e9 Bonnelly Castellanos (Santiago, 1929\u2013[[Miami]], 2008)\n| 3=  3. Josefina Esmirna Cana\u00e1n D\u00edaz (La Vega, ''circa'' 1940\u2013)\n| 4=  4. Carlos Sully Rafael Bonnelly Fondeur (Santiago, 1893\u2013?, 1969; brother of President [[Rafael Filiberto Bonnelly]])\n| 5=  5. Sof\u00eda Noem\u00ed Castellanos Ortega\n| 6=  6. Jovino Cana\u00e1n Abud (\u2020 ''circa'' 1955)\n| 7=  7. Lilliam A. D\u00edaz Fern\u00e1ndez\n| 8=  8. Carlos Sully Bonnelly Arnaud (Puerto Plata, 1858\u2013Santiago, 1923)\n| 9=  9. Mar\u00eda Luisa Fondeur Fern\u00e1ndez (Santiago, 1863\u2013''ibidem'', 1949)\n|10= 10. Jos\u00e9 Furcy Castellanos Fondeur\n|11= 11. Ana Luisa Ortega Pichardo ([[San Francisco de Macor\u00eds]], 1871\u2013?)\n|12=\n|13= 13. Amelia Abud (Lebanon, ?\u2013?)\n|14= 14. Norberto D\u00edaz (Puerto Rico, ?\u2013?)\n|15= 15. Elena Herminda Fern\u00e1ndez M\u00e1rmol (''circa'' 1910\u2013 ?; sister of Vice President Manuel Antonio Fern\u00e1ndez M\u00e1rmol)\n|16= 16. Francisco Ulises Bonnelly Coutin ([[Charlotte Amalie, U.S. Virgin Islands|Charlotte Amalie]], 1825\u2013Santiago, 1923)\n|17= 17. Buenaventura Carmen Arnaud (Santiago, 1830\u2013Puerto Plata, 1877)\n|18= 18. [[Furcy Fondeur|Furcy Fondeur Lajeunesse]] (Paris, 1814\u2013Santiago, 1892)\n|19= 19. Mar\u00eda Luisa Fern\u00e1ndez Fern\u00e1ndez ([[Pu\u00f1al]], 1837\u2013Santiago, 1895)\n|20= 20. Jos\u00e9 Castellanos de Pe\u00f1a\n|21= 21. Gerardina Fondeur Castro (daughter of #18)\n|22= 22. Francisco Armando Ortega Soto ([[Ug\u00edjar]], ?\u2013San Francisco de Macor\u00eds, 1883)\n|23= 23. Mar\u00eda Teresa Pichardo Betancourt ([[Coamo, Puerto Rico|Coamo]], 1864\u2013?)\n|footnotes='''Source:''' Instituto Dominicano de Genealog\u00eda\n}}\n\n== Career ==\nBonnelly, a native of Santo Domingo in the Dominican Republic, grew up with fashion being an intrinsic part of his identity. He studied architecture at UASD before moving to New York where he graduated from Parsons School of Design and began his career in fashion as Oscar de la Renta\u2019s assistant. He then worked as a designer for the houses of Bill Blass and Eli Tahari before starting his namesake collection in 1998, retailing at Saks Fifth Avenue, Neiman Marcus, Bergdorf Goodman and other better stores around the world. He later returned to Oscar de la Renta as creative director for the O Oscar Collection. In 2000 Sully Bonnelly Accents was launched, an exclusive collection for Home Shopping Network (HSN) and HSN en Espanol, making him the first Latin American designer featured on a shopping network. In 2001 Bonnelly served as Creative Director for Citrine, a contemporary sportswear collection. Two years later the Sully Bonnelly Bridal collection was launched. In 1999 he received the Golden Coast Award, a prestigious fashion award in Chicago. In 2001 was elected member to the Council of Fashion Designers of America (CFDA) joining an important community of over 300 American fashion and accessory designers. Additionally, he has been honored by several Dominican organizations for his outstanding work in fashion. New York Governor George Pataki honored him in 2005 in celebration of Dominican Heritage Month. Most recently Bonnelly received the Orden al Merito Ciudadano, a recognition given to Dominicans all over the world who have distinguished themselves in their chosen careers and done honor to their homeland. Past honorees include: the authors Junot Diaz and Julia Alvarez, the musician Michael Camilo and fashion designer Oscar de la Renta. Today, Sully Bonnelly is Creative Director for Isaac Mizrahi  Sportswear, Eveningwear and Dresses. Memories of his travels around the world infuse all his designs, forming his imaginary scrapbook of colors, textures, rhythms and fragrances. These inspirations materialize into exciting designs that instill in women who wear them a feeling of well being and self-confidence.\n\n=== Other notable accomplishments ===\nIn 2001, Bonnelly held the position as Creative Director for Citrine.<ref>{{cite web|title=Puerto Rico Moda |url=http://www.puertoricomoda.com/REVISTA_PR_MODA_Rev6%5B1%5D.pdf |publisher=Puerto Rica Moda |accessdate=18 April 2012 }}{{dead link|date=September 2016|bot=medic}}</ref> In 2002, he designed<ref>{{cite web|title=Museo Celia Cruz|url=http://www.megalatina.fm/eventos/museo-celia-cruz/|publisher=Mega Latina|accessdate=20 April 2012}}</ref> [[Celia Cruz]]'s dress for the [[Latin Grammy Awards]]. In 2003, the Bonnelly Bridal collection was launched.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sully Bonnelly- Spring 2005 Bridal Collection}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Spring 2005 Bridal Collection|url=http://secure.secure.runwaytalk.com/shopping/guides/weddings/brides/gowns/04/bridalweek/sullybonelly/index.htm|publisher=New York Magazine|access-date=17 April 2012|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150417044646/http://secure.secure.runwaytalk.com/shopping/guides/weddings/brides/gowns/04/bridalweek/sullybonelly/index.htm|archive-date=17 April 2015|df=}}</ref> In 2008, Bonnelly became the Creative Director for Muse,<ref>{{cite news|last=Ramirez|first=Sonia|title=Sully Bonnelly: \"Lo que m\u00e1s me atrae de los textiles en Latinoam\u00e9rica es la riqueza en el trabajo manual\"|url=http://iconos.aollatino.com/2011/10/03/sully-bonnelly-entrevista|accessdate=19 April 2012|newspaper=AOL Latino|date=3 October 2011}}</ref> a contemporary women's clothing division of Maggy London in New York and Anthracite by Muse.\n\n== Recognition ==\n\nIn 1999, Bonnelly was a recipient of the Golden Coast Award, a prestigious fashion award in Chicago. In 2001, he was elected member to the [[Council of Fashion Designers of America]], an important community of over 300 American fashion and accessory designers.<ref>{{cite news|title=Council of Fashion Designers of America|url=http://www.cfda.com/members?member_id=562&tab=a#!sully-bonnelly|accessdate=8 June 2012|date=8 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nHe has also been acknowledged by several Dominican organizations for his outstanding work in fashion. Former New York Governor [[George Pataki]] acknowledged Bonnelly as a distinguished fashion designer in 2005 during Dominican Heritage Month.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sully Bonnelly|url=http://www.puertoricomoda.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=93:sully-bonnely&catid=35:disenadores&Itemid=56|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110123172918/http://www.puertoricomoda.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=93:sully-bonnely&catid=35:disenadores&Itemid=56|url-status=dead|archive-date=23 January 2011|publisher=Puerto Rico Moda|access-date=10 April 2012|df=}}</ref> Bonnelly received the Orden al Merito Ciudadano,<ref>{{cite news|title=Consul Eduardo Selman destaca progreso de dominicanos en Estados Unidos|url=http://www.ayudatotal.com/index2.php?option=com_content&do_pdf=1&id=134|accessdate=18 April 2012|newspaper=Ayuda Total|date=24 February 2009}}</ref> an award given to Dominicans all over the world who have distinguished themselves through their careers and represented honor to their homeland.\n\nBonnelly's house was featured in Rima Suqi's book Fashion Designers At Home.<ref>{{cite web|title=Assouline |url=http://www.assouline.com/9782759404711.html |access-date=20 April 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120427130211/http://www.assouline.com/9782759404711.html |archive-date=April 27, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn January 2012, Sully Bonnelly married Robert Littman, president of the Vergel Foundation, which manages a collection of modern and contemporary Mexican Art in New York and [[Cuernavaca, Mexico]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Sully Bonnelly and Robert Littman|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/01/15/fashion/weddings/sully-bonnelly-robert-littman-weddings.html?_r=1|accessdate=15 April 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=15 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.sullybonnelly.com/ Official Website]\n* [http://moda.laverdad.es/pasarelas/primavera-verano/2010/semana-de-la-moda-de-la-republica-dominicana-2010/sully-bonnelly/foto3.html Collecion Primavera-Verano 2010]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120802030327/http://www.hola.com/moda/modistos/dominicanamoda-2010/bonnelly/1/ DominicanaModa-2010]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bonnelly, Sully}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Dominican Republic fashion designers]]\n[[Category:Dominican Republic people of Corsican descent]]\n[[Category:Dominican Republic people of French descent]]\n[[Category:Dominican Republic people of Lebanese descent]]\n[[Category:Dominican Republic people of Spanish descent]]\n[[Category:Dominican Republic people of Puerto Rican descent]]\n[[Category:Dominican Republic people of Virgin Islands descent]]\n[[Category:Universidad Aut\u00f3noma de Santo Domingo alumni]]\n[[Category:LGBT fashion designers]]\n[[Category:People from Santo Domingo]]\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues|\n{{autobiography|date=June 2012}}\n{{BLP sources|date=June 2012}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox fashion designer\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| name               = Sully Bonnelly\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1956|12|24}}\n| birth_place        = [[Santo Domingo]], [[Dominican Republic]]\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| citizenship        = [[United States]], [[Dominican Republic]]\n| education          = \n| label_name         = \n| awards             = Golden Coast Award ([[Chicago]] 1999)\n| website            = http://www.sullybonnelly.com\n}}\n'''Sully Bonnelly''', in full '''Sully Osvaldo Bonnelly Cana\u00e1n''' (born December 24, 1956), is a [[Dominican Republic|Dominican]] fashion designer of women's clothing. He is the Creative Director for Sully Bonnelly.\n\n==Early years==\nBonnelly was born into a family of both [[Corsican people|Corsican]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Falleci\u00f3 el padre del dise\u00f1ador Sully Bonelly|url=http://www.listindiario.com/la-republica/2008/12/7/83743/Fallecio-el-padre-del-disenador-Sully-Bonelly|publisher=[[List\u00edn Diario]]|accessdate=24 April 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140424004243/http://www.listindiario.com/la-republica/2008/12/7/83743/Fallecio-el-padre-del-disenador-Sully-Bonelly|archivedate=24 April 2014|location=Santo Domingo|language=Spanish|date=7 December 2008|quote=Dedic\u00f3 a\u00f1os investigando todo lo referente al apellido Bonnelly y sus or\u00edgenes hist\u00f3ricos. Fue quien organiz\u00f3 exitosamente los dos encuentros de las distintas ramas de esta gran familia, realizados hace varios a\u00f1os. Viaj\u00f3 a C\u00f3rcega tierra de origen del primer Bonnelly que se asent\u00f3 en la Rep\u00fablica Dominicana, e hizo un levantamiento de sus ancestros. Interesado en la unidad familiar de los Bonnelly estaba escribiendo un libro para dejarlo como legado. Sus restos mortales ser\u00e1n tra\u00eddos en los pr\u00f3ximos d\u00edas a la ciudad de Santo Domingo, Rep\u00fablica Dominicana.}}</ref> and [[French people|French]] descent.<ref>{{cite web|author=Ivonna Ginebra|title=Segundo Encuentro de la Familia Bonnelly|url=http://www.idg.org.do/ensayos/1995/bonnelly.pdf |accessdate=24 April 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140424003550/http://www.idg.org.do/ensayos/1995/bonnelly.pdf |archivedate=24 April 2014 |publisher=Instituto Dominicano de Genealog\u00eda |year=1995}}</ref> An uncle of him, [[Rafael Filiberto Bonnelly|Rafael Bonnelly-Fondeur]], became [[president of the Dominican Republic]] from 1962 to 1963.\n\nBonnelly studied architecture at [[Universidad Aut\u00f3noma de Santo Domingo]] and later moved to New York, where he studied at [[Parsons School of Design]] and began his career in fashion as [[Oscar de la Renta]]\u2019s assistant. He also worked as a designer for the houses of [[Bill Blass]] and Eli Tahari before starting his own collection in 1998, retailing at [[Saks Fifth Avenue]], [[Neiman Marcus]], [[Bergdorf Goodman]] and other stores around the globe. Later in his career, he returned to Oscar de la Renta as creative director for the O Oscar Collection.\n\n=== Ancestors ===\n{{ahnentafel\n|collapsed=yes |align=center\n|boxstyle_1=background-color: #fcc;\n|boxstyle_2=background-color: #fb9;\n|boxstyle_3=background-color: #ffc;\n|boxstyle_4=background-color: #bfc;\n|boxstyle_5=background-color: #9fe;\n| 1=  1. '''Sully Osvaldo Bonnelly Cana\u00e1n'''\n| 2=  2. Carlos Sully Rafael Jos\u00e9 Bonnelly Castellanos (Santiago, 1929\u2013[[Miami]], 2008)\n| 3=  3. Josefina Esmirna Cana\u00e1n D\u00edaz (La Vega, ''circa'' 1940\u2013)\n| 4=  4. Carlos Sully Rafael Bonnelly Fondeur (Santiago, 1893\u2013?, 1969; brother of President [[Rafael Filiberto Bonnelly]])\n| 5=  5. Sof\u00eda Noem\u00ed Castellanos Ortega\n| 6=  6. Jovino Cana\u00e1n Abud (\u2020 ''circa'' 1955)\n| 7=  7. Lilliam A. D\u00edaz Fern\u00e1ndez\n| 8=  8. Carlos Sully Bonnelly Arnaud (Puerto Plata, 1858\u2013Santiago, 1923)\n| 9=  9. Mar\u00eda Luisa Fondeur Fern\u00e1ndez (Santiago, 1863\u2013''ibidem'', 1949)\n|10= 10. Jos\u00e9 Furcy Castellanos Fondeur\n|11= 11. Ana Luisa Ortega Pichardo ([[San Francisco de Macor\u00eds]], 1871\u2013?)\n|12=\n|13= 13. Amelia Abud (Lebanon, ?\u2013?)\n|14= 14. Norberto D\u00edaz (Puerto Rico, ?\u2013?)\n|15= 15. Elena Herminda Fern\u00e1ndez M\u00e1rmol (''circa'' 1910\u2013 ?; sister of Vice President Manuel Antonio Fern\u00e1ndez M\u00e1rmol)\n|16= 16. Francisco Ulises Bonnelly Coutin ([[Charlotte Amalie, U.S. Virgin Islands|Charlotte Amalie]], 1825\u2013Santiago, 1923)\n|17= 17. Buenaventura Carmen Arnaud (Santiago, 1830\u2013Puerto Plata, 1877)\n|18= 18. [[Furcy Fondeur|Furcy Fondeur Lajeunesse]] (Paris, 1814\u2013Santiago, 1892)\n|19= 19. Mar\u00eda Luisa Fern\u00e1ndez Fern\u00e1ndez ([[Pu\u00f1al]], 1837\u2013Santiago, 1895)\n|20= 20. Jos\u00e9 Castellanos de Pe\u00f1a\n|21= 21. Gerardina Fondeur Castro (daughter of #18)\n|22= 22. Francisco Armando Ortega Soto ([[Ug\u00edjar]], ?\u2013San Francisco de Macor\u00eds, 1883)\n|23= 23. Mar\u00eda Teresa Pichardo Betancourt ([[Coamo, Puerto Rico|Coamo]], 1864\u2013?)\n|footnotes='''Source:''' Instituto Dominicano de Genealog\u00eda\n}}\n\n== Career ==\nBonnelly, a native of Santo Domingo in the Dominican Republic, grew up with fashion being an intrinsic part of his identity. He studied architecture at UASD before moving to New York where he graduated from Parsons School of Design and began his career in fashion as Oscar de la Renta\u2019s assistant. He then worked as a designer for the houses of Bill Blass and Eli Tahari before starting his namesake collection in 1998, retailing at Saks Fifth Avenue, Neiman Marcus, Bergdorf Goodman and other better stores around the world. He later returned to Oscar de la Renta as creative director for the O Oscar Collection. In 2000 Sully Bonnelly Accents was launched, an exclusive collection for Home Shopping Network (HSN) and HSN en Espanol, making him the first Latin American designer featured on a shopping network. In 2001 Bonnelly served as Creative Director for Citrine, a contemporary sportswear collection. Two years later the Sully Bonnelly Bridal collection was launched. In 1999 he received the Golden Coast Award, a prestigious fashion award in Chicago. In 2001 was elected member to the Council of Fashion Designers of America (CFDA) joining an important community of over 300 American fashion and accessory designers. Additionally, he has been honored by several Dominican organizations for his outstanding work in fashion. New York Governor George Pataki honored him in 2005 in celebration of Dominican Heritage Month. Most recently Bonnelly received the Orden al Merito Ciudadano, a recognition given to Dominicans all over the world who have distinguished themselves in their chosen careers and done honor to their homeland. Past honorees include: the authors Junot Diaz and Julia Alvarez, the musician Michael Camilo and fashion designer Oscar de la Renta. Today, Sully Bonnelly is Creative Director for Isaac Mizrahi  Sportswear, Eveningwear and Dresses. Memories of his travels around the world infuse all his designs, forming his imaginary scrapbook of colors, textures, rhythms and fragrances. These inspirations materialize into exciting designs that instill in women who wear them a feeling of well being and self-confidence.\n\n=== Other notable accomplishments ===\nIn 2001, Bonnelly held the position as Creative Director for Citrine.<ref>{{cite web|title=Puerto Rico Moda |url=http://www.puertoricomoda.com/REVISTA_PR_MODA_Rev6%5B1%5D.pdf |publisher=Puerto Rica Moda |accessdate=18 April 2012 }}{{dead link|date=September 2016|bot=medic}}</ref> In 2002, he designed<ref>{{cite web|title=Museo Celia Cruz|url=http://www.megalatina.fm/eventos/museo-celia-cruz/|publisher=Mega Latina|accessdate=20 April 2012}}</ref> [[Celia Cruz]]'s dress for the [[Latin Grammy Awards]]. In 2003, the Bonnelly Bridal collection was launched.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sully Bonnelly- Spring 2005 Bridal Collection}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Spring 2005 Bridal Collection|url=http://secure.secure.runwaytalk.com/shopping/guides/weddings/brides/gowns/04/bridalweek/sullybonelly/index.htm|publisher=New York Magazine|access-date=17 April 2012|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150417044646/http://secure.secure.runwaytalk.com/shopping/guides/weddings/brides/gowns/04/bridalweek/sullybonelly/index.htm|archive-date=17 April 2015|df=}}</ref> In 2008, Bonnelly became the Creative Director for Muse,<ref>{{cite news|last=Ramirez|first=Sonia|title=Sully Bonnelly: \"Lo que m\u00e1s me atrae de los textiles en Latinoam\u00e9rica es la riqueza en el trabajo manual\"|url=http://iconos.aollatino.com/2011/10/03/sully-bonnelly-entrevista|accessdate=19 April 2012|newspaper=AOL Latino|date=3 October 2011}}</ref> a contemporary women's clothing division of Maggy London in New York and Anthracite by Muse.\n\n== Recognition ==\n\nIn 1999, Bonnelly was a recipient of the Golden Coast Award, a prestigious fashion award in Chicago. In 2001, he was elected member to the [[Council of Fashion Designers of America]], an important community of over 300 American fashion and accessory designers.<ref>{{cite news|title=Council of Fashion Designers of America|url=http://www.cfda.com/members?member_id=562&tab=a#!sully-bonnelly|accessdate=8 June 2012|date=8 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nHe has also been acknowledged by several Dominican organizations for his outstanding work in fashion. Former New York Governor [[George Pataki]] acknowledged Bonnelly as a distinguished fashion designer in 2005 during Dominican Heritage Month.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sully Bonnelly|url=http://www.puertoricomoda.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=93:sully-bonnely&catid=35:disenadores&Itemid=56|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110123172918/http://www.puertoricomoda.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=93:sully-bonnely&catid=35:disenadores&Itemid=56|url-status=dead|archive-date=23 January 2011|publisher=Puerto Rico Moda|access-date=10 April 2012|df=}}</ref> Bonnelly received the Orden al Merito Ciudadano,<ref>{{cite news|title=Consul Eduardo Selman destaca progreso de dominicanos en Estados Unidos|url=http://www.ayudatotal.com/index2.php?option=com_content&do_pdf=1&id=134|accessdate=18 April 2012|newspaper=Ayuda Total|date=24 February 2009}}</ref> an award given to Dominicans all over the world who have distinguished themselves through their careers and represented honor to their homeland.\n\nBonnelly's house was featured in Rima Suqi's book Fashion Designers At Home.<ref>{{cite web|title=Assouline |url=http://www.assouline.com/9782759404711.html |access-date=20 April 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120427130211/http://www.assouline.com/9782759404711.html |archive-date=April 27, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn January 2012, Sully Bonnelly married Robert Littman, president of the Vergel Foundation, which manages a collection of modern and contemporary Mexican Art in New York and [[Cuernavaca, Mexico]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Sully Bonnelly and Robert Littman|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/01/15/fashion/weddings/sully-bonnelly-robert-littman-weddings.html?_r=1|accessdate=15 April 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=15 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.sullybonnelly.com/ Official Website]\n* [http://moda.laverdad.es/pasarelas/primavera-verano/2010/semana-de-la-moda-de-la-republica-dominicana-2010/sully-bonnelly/foto3.html Collecion Primavera-Verano 2010]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120802030327/http://www.hola.com/moda/modistos/dominicanamoda-2010/bonnelly/1/ DominicanaModa-2010]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bonnelly, Sully}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Dominican Republic fashion designers]]\n[[Category:Dominican Republic people of Corsican descent]]\n[[Category:Dominican Republic people of French descent]]\n[[Category:Dominican Republic people of Lebanese descent]]\n[[Category:Dominican Republic people of Spanish descent]]\n[[Category:Dominican Republic people of Puerto Rican descent]]\n[[Category:Dominican Republic people of Virgin Islands descent]]\n[[Category:Universidad Aut\u00f3noma de Santo Domingo alumni]]\n[[Category:LGBT fashion designers]]\n[[Category:People from Santo Domingo]]\n", "name_user": "Jaa1986", "label": "safe", "comment": "added spouse name", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sully_Bonnelly"}
{"title_page": "DMC DeLorean", "text_new": "{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{short description|1980s automobile}}\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name = DMC DeLorean\n| image = Delorean DMC-12 side.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = 1983 DeLorean\n| manufacturer = [[DeLorean Motor Company]] (DMC)<br />[[Bloomfield_Hills,_Michigan|Bloomfield Hills]], Michigan, US\n| production = 9,080<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/cars/2015/12/19/delorean-book/77623204/|title=DeLoreans still ply the roads -- and memories|url-status=live}}</ref> (disputed)\n| model_years = 1981\u20131983\n| assembly = DeLorean Motor Cars, Ltd. (DMCL) [[Dunmurry]], [[Belfast]], Northern Ireland\n| designer = [[Giorgetto Giugiaro]] at [[Italdesign]]<ref>https://www.cnn.com/style/article/giorgetto-giugiaro-interview/index.html</ref>\n| class = Sports car\n| body_style = 2-door coup\u00e9\n| related = \n| layout = Rear-engine, rear-wheel-drive<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9|date= 2014 | pages = 15}}</ref>\n| engine = {{convert|2.85|L|cuin|0|abbr=on}} [[V6 PRV engine]] ''ZMJ-159''<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |date= 2014 |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9| pages = 15}}</ref>\n| powerout = {{convert|130|hp|PS kW|0|abbr=on}} and {{convert|207|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} of torque<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |date= 2014 |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9| pages = 15}}</ref>\n| transmission = 5-speed manual<br/>3-speed automatic<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9|date= 2014 | pages = 15}}</ref>\n| wheelbase = {{convert|2413|mm|1|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"autogenerated1946\">{{Cite book|title=Standard Catalog of American Cars 1946\u20131975|publisher= Krause|isbn=0-87341-027-0|editor-last=Gunnell |editor-first= John A.}}</ref>\n| length = {{convert|4267|mm|1|abbr=on}}<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9|date= 2014 | pages = 16}}</ref>\n| width = {{convert|1988|mm|1|abbr=on}}<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9|date= 2014 | pages = 16}}</ref>\n| height = {{convert|1140|mm|1|abbr=on}} doors closed<br/>{{convert|1962|mm|1|abbr=on}} doors open<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9|date = 2014| pages = 16}}</ref>\n| weight = {{convert|1233|kg|0|abbr=on}}<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9 |date= 2014 | pages = 16}}</ref>\n| sp = us\n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| doors = Gullwing doors\n}}\n\nThe '''DMC DeLorean''' (often referred to simply as the \"'''DeLorean'''\", as it was the only model ever produced by the company) is a sports car manufactured by [[John DeLorean]]'s [[DeLorean Motor Company]] (DMC) for the American market from 1981 to 1983. The car was designed by [[Giorgetto Giugiaro]] and stood out for its [[gull-wing door]]s and brushed stainless-steel outer body panels, as well as an innovative fiberglass body structure with a steel backbone chassis. It became widely known for its disappointing lack of power and performance, which did not match the expectations created by its looks and price tag, but it became iconic for its appearances as the [[DeLorean time machine|time machine]] in the [[Back to the Future (franchise)|''Back to the Future'' media franchise]] after 1985.\n\nThroughout production, the car was generally unchanged, although minor modifications were made to such parts as the hood and wheels. The first production car was completed on January 21, 1981. About 9,000 DeLoreans were made before production halted in late December 1982 shortly after DMC had filed for bankruptcy.\n\n==History==\n[[File:DeLorean DMC-12 (9979) (cropped).jpg|thumb|A DeLorean with the gull-wing doors closed]]\n[[File:DeLorean DMC-12 with doors open.jpg|thumb|A DeLorean from the front with the gull-wing doors open]]\nIn October 1976, the first prototype DeLorean was completed by American automotive chief engineer William T. Collins, formerly chief engineer at [[Pontiac]].  Originally, the car was intended to have a centrally-mounted [[Wankel engine|Wankel rotary engine]].  The engine selection was reconsidered when [[Comotor]] production ended, and the favored engine became the [[Ford Cologne V6 engine]].  Eventually the French/Swedish [[fuel injection|fuel-injected]] [[V6 PRV engine]] ([[Peugeot]]-[[Renault]]-[[Volvo]]) was selected.  Also the engine location moved from the mid-engined location in the prototype to a rear-engined installation in the production car.  The [[chassis]] was initially planned to be produced from a new and untested manufacturing technology known as elastic reservoir moulding (ERM), which would lighten the car while presumably lowering its production costs.  This new technology, for which DeLorean had purchased patent rights, was eventually found to be unsuitable.<ref>{{Cite book | title = Stainless Steel Illusion| author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |ISBN=0-9744141-0-7 |date= 2003| pages = 38\u201339}}</ref>\n\nThese and other changes to the original concept led to considerable schedule pressures.  The entire car was deemed to require almost complete re-engineering, which was turned over to engineer [[Colin Chapman]], founder of [[Lotus Cars]].  Chapman replaced most of the unproven material and manufacturing techniques with those then employed by Lotus, like the steel backbone chassis.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{Cite book | title = Stainless Steel Illusion| author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |ISBN=0-9744141-0-7|date= 2003| pages = 71\u201375}}</ref>\n\nThe first prototype appeared in October 1976 and was known as the DSV-1, or DeLorean Safety Vehicle.<ref>{{Cite book | title = Stainless Steel Illusion| author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |ISBN=0-9744141-0-7 |date= 2003| page = 23}}</ref> As development continued, the model was referred to as the DSV-12<ref>{{Cite book | title = Stainless Steel Illusion| author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |ISBN=0-9744141-0-7 |date= 2003| page = 28}}</ref> and later the DMC-12 since DMC was targeting a list price of US$12,000 ({{Inflation|US|12000|1976|fmt=eq|r=-3}}) at release.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.classic-car-history.com/delorean-car.htm |title=DeLorean DMC-12 |access-date=February 3, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190204065904/https://www.classic-car-history.com/delorean-car.htm |archive-date=February 4, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>[https://www.cnbc.com/2016/11/09/how-an-immigrant-mechanic-used-5-million-to-bring-deloreans-back-to-the-future.html How an immigrant mechanic used $5 million to bring DeLoreans back to the future] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190204014534/https://www.cnbc.com/2016/11/09/how-an-immigrant-mechanic-used-5-million-to-bring-deloreans-back-to-the-future.html |date=February 4, 2019 }} Zack Guzman. 3:52 PM ET Wed, November 9, 2016</ref>\n\nIn an interview with James Espey of the new incarnation of the DeLorean Motor Company of [[Texas]], a drawing surfaced showing that the car originally had the potential to be named \"Z Tavio\".  John DeLorean's middle name and his son's first name were both Zachary, while Tavio was his father's name and his son's middle name.  Due to only sporadic documentation, there is little more that is currently known about the Z Tavio name and why it was ultimately rejected in favor of the DeLorean.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.myride.com/content/shared/articles/templates/index.cfm/article_id_int/6244/page/page1/id/27821 |title=Interview with James Espy of DMCH |publisher=Myride.com |date= |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100908094456/http://www.myride.com/content/shared/articles/templates/index.cfm/article_id_int/6244/page/page1/id/27821 |archive-date=September 8, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAfter several delays and cost overruns, production finally began in late 1980. Around this time DMC officially dropped the name DMC-12 on its now US$25,000 ({{Inflation|US|25000|1981|fmt=eq|r=-3}}) car in favor of the model name DeLorean. The DeLorean sports car, as it was described in advertisements, began production in December 1980 with the first production car rolling off the assembly line on January 21, 1981.<ref>{{cite news |author=Lily Rothman |url=http://time.com/4180894/delorean-history/ |title=DeLorean Auto History: What Happened to the Company |publisher=Time |date=January 21, 2016 |accessdate=May 14, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190423164413/http://time.com/4180894/delorean-history/ |archive-date=April 23, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/almanac-the-delorean-car/ |title=Almanac: The DeLorean car |publisher=CBS News |date=January 21, 2018 |accessdate=May 14, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190515122627/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/almanac-the-delorean-car/ |archive-date=May 15, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe DeLorean Motor Company was placed into receivership in February 1982 and filed [[bankruptcy]] in October 1982<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/1982/10/26/business/delorean-motor-files-bankruptcy.html</ref>.  Approximately 100 partially assembled DeLoreans on the production line were completed by [[Big Lots|Consolidated International]].  About 9,000 cars were produced in total.  The remaining parts from the factory stock, the parts from the US Warranty Parts Center, as well as parts from the original suppliers that had not yet been delivered to the factory were all shipped to [[Columbus, Ohio]] in 1983\u201384.  A company called KAPAC sold these parts to retail and [[wholesaling|wholesale]] customers by mail order.  In 1997, DeLorean Motor Company of Texas acquired this inventory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.delorean.com/q&a.asp#whereparts |title=DeLorean Motor Company FAQ |publisher=Delorean.com |date=November 6, 2007 |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101121215155/http://delorean.com/q%26a.asp |archivedate=November 21, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n==Sales and production==\n===Sales===\nPrior to the release of the DeLorean, there was a waiting list of anxious buyers, many of whom paid over [[List_price#Automobiles/motorcars|MSRP]], however that exuberance subsided very quickly and production output soon far exceeded sales volume.  October 1981 was the highest month of sales for DMC with 720 vehicles sold but by December, the US was falling into recession and interest rates were rising which further negatively impacted sales.  Despite this, instead of reducing production, John DeLorean doubled production output, further adding to the backlog of unsold cars.   By the end of 1981, DMC had produced 7,500 cars but had only sold 3,000.  By this point, DMC was in a financial hardship and in February 1982, DMC was placed into receivership. <ref>{{Cite book | title = Stainless Steel Illusion| author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |ISBN=0-9744141-0-7 |date= 2003| pages = 130}}</ref>\n\nIn February 1982, unsold 1981 model year cars were \u201cpriced for immediate clearance\u201d in hopes to make room for the more expensive 1982 model year cars.  In March, telegrams were sent to all 343 dealerships requesting each buy six cars to help save the company;  none of the dealers responded with a sales order.  By this point, dealers were sitting on unsold inventory as were the quality assurance centers and hundreds more sitting on the  docks in [[Long Beach]], California.  By the end of May 1982, production at the factory was shut down.  Another attempt in July 1982 was made to revive sales by offering discounts to dealerships and offering a 5-year/{{convert|50000|mi|adj=on}} warranty with the first year or {{convert|12000|mi|adj=on}} portion secured by a major insurance carrier but this was not successful. \n\nBruce McWilliams, VP of Marketing for DMC and later acting President for DMC America, after resigning his position said, \u201cThe car could never be sold in the numbers John DeLorean predicted\u2026\u201d.<ref>{{Cite book | title = Stainless Steel Illusion| author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |ISBN=0-9744141-0-7 |date= 2003| pages = 133-141}}</ref>\n\n===Production===\nProduction information was lost or scattered upon the [[DeLorean Motor Company#Downturn and bankruptcy|shutdown of DMC]] and production figures for the DeLorean have never been verified based on official factory records.  Despite some unexplained VIN gaps, based upon VIN information, owners have been able to piece together the approximate quantity of DeLoreans produced.\n\nIn February 1982, DMC was placed into [[receivership]] and the factory continued to operate at a reduced production rate until the end of May.  When Consolidated International acquired the unsold and partially assembled cars in November 1982, it brought back workers to complete the cars remaining on the assembly line. It was decided to make the remaining completed 1982 model year cars into 1983 models. The remaining cars VINs were re-VINed into 1983 cars by taking the original VIN number and adding 5000 to it and changing the \"CD\" in the middle of the VIN to \"DD\" thus making a 1983 model.\n\nFor the 1981 model year, there were 6,700 DeLoreans produced (VIN 500-7199).  For the 1982 model year, there were 1,999 DeLoreans produced (VIN 10001-11999).  For the 1983 model year, there were 276 DeLoreans (VIN 17000-17170 and 20001-20105) bringing the total estimated production to 8,975 cars.<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |date= 2014 |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9| pages = 115-117}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2007, about 6,500 DeLorean cars were thought to still exist.<ref>{{cite news |first= Martin |last= Zimmerman |url= https://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-garage28jul28,0,7786124.story?coll=la-home-center |title= For the DeLorean, it's back to the present |accessdate= January 7, 2013 |work= Los Angeles Times |date= July 28, 2007 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20130228154343/http://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-garage28jul28,0,7786124.story?coll=la-home-center |archive-date= February 28, 2013 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\n==Construction==\nThe DeLorean features a number of unusual construction details, including gull-wing doors, unpainted [[stainless-steel]] body panels, and a rear-mounted engine.\n\n===Body===\n[[File:De Lorean DMC-12 at Wollaton Park, Nottingham, England.jpg|thumb|The gull-wing doors on the DeLorean were a distinctive feature.]]\nThe body design of the DeLorean was a product of [[Giorgetto Giugiaro]] of [[Italdesign Giugiaro|Ital Design]] and is panelled in brushed [[AISI steel grades#Stainless steel|SS304]] stainless steel. Except for three cars plated in 24-karat gold, all DeLoreans left the factory uncovered by paint or clearcoat.<ref>{{cite web |first= Knut |last= Grimsrud |url= http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/t_finish.htm |work= DeLorean FAQ |title= Body Finish and Composition from Owners Manual |publisher= Dmcnews.com |date=  |accessdate= December 4, 2010 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110228223225/http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/t_finish.htm |archive-date= February 28, 2011 |url-status= live }}</ref> Painted DeLoreans do exist, although these were all painted after the cars were purchased from the factory.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.aacamuseum.org/delorean-prototype/ |title=DeLorean Prototype & Production |publisher=AACA Museum |date= |accessdate=May 14, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180606022652/https://www.aacamuseum.org/delorean-prototype/ |archive-date=June 6, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> In order to train the workforce, a small number of DeLoreans were produced without the costly stainless steel panels and are referred to as \"black cars\" or [[Development_mule|mules]] in reference to their black fiberglass bodies. These cars were never intended to be sold.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://motor-car.net/delorean/item/10131-dmc-12-technical-1981-82 |title=DeLorean - DeLorean DMC-12 Technical (1981-1982) |publisher=Motor-car.net |date=June 7, 2013 |accessdate=May 14, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190425053807/https://motor-car.net/delorean/item/10131-dmc-12-technical-1981-82 |archive-date=April 25, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nSmall scratches in the stainless-steel body panels can be removed with a non-metallic scouring pad (since metal pads can leave iron particles embedded in the stainless steel, which can give the appearance of the stainless \"rusting\"), or even sandpaper.<ref>{{cite web |first= Knut |last= Grimsrud |url= http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/c_body.htm |work= DeLorean FAQ |title= Care & Feeding: Stainless Steel Body Maintenance |publisher= Dmcnews.com |date=  |accessdate= December 4, 2010 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110515142238/http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/c_body.htm |archive-date= May 15, 2011 |url-status= live }}</ref> The stainless-steel panels are fixed to a [[fiberglass]] underbody. The underbody is affixed to a steel double-Y frame chassis, inspired by the [[Lotus Esprit]] platform.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" />\n\nThe unpainted stainless body creates challenges during [[Automotive restoration|restoration]] of the cars. In traditional automotive body repair, the panel is repaired to be as original (\"straight\") as possible, and imperfections are sculpted back to form with polyester body filler like [[Bondo (putty)|Bondo]] or lead (body [[solder]]). This poses no problem (aside from originality) with most cars, as the filler will be hidden by the car's paint (for example, most new cars have filler hiding the seam where the roof meets the [[quarter panel]]). With an unpainted stainless body, the stainless steel must be reworked to exactly the original shape, contour, and grain, which is a tremendously difficult job on regular steel (a dented or bent panel is stretched, and a shrinking hammer or other techniques must be used to unstretch the metal) and even more difficult with stainless due to its tendency to [[Work hardening|work-harden]]. Furthermore, it is exceedingly difficult to paint stainless steel due to difficulties with paint adhesion. DeLorean envisioned that damaged panels would simply be replaced rather than repaired.\n\nAnother distinctive feature of the DeLorean is its [[gull-wing door]]s. The common problem of supporting the weight of gull-wing doors was solved by other manufacturers with lightweight doors in the [[Mercedes-Benz 300SL]] and a hydraulic pump in the [[Bricklin SV-1]], although these designs had structural or convenience disadvantages. The DeLorean features heavy doors supported by [[Cryogenics|cryogenically]] preset [[Torsion bar suspension|torsion bars]] and gas-charged [[strut]]s.<ref>{{US patent|4,378,658}}</ref> These torsion bars were developed by [[Grumman Aircraft Engineering Corporation|Grumman Aerospace]] (and built by Unbrako in the UK, a division of SPS Technologies of Jenkintown, Pennsylvania, US) to withstand the stresses of supporting the doors.<ref>{{cite web |first= Knut |last= Grimsrud |url= http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/t_tech1.htm |work= DeLorean FAQ |title= Exotic Technology |publisher= Dmcnews.com |date=  |accessdate= December 4, 2010 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110511091013/http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/t_tech1.htm |archive-date= May 11, 2011 |url-status= live }}</ref> Much like the [[scissor doors|doors]] fitted to the [[Lamborghini Countach]], the DeLorean doors featured small cutout windows, because full-sized windows would not be fully retractable within the short door panels. Additionally, the doors featured red and amber \"safety\" lights around the perimeter. These lights illuminated when the door was open and could be seen from the front, rear or side of the vehicle at night or in low-light situations.<ref>{{cite web |first= Knut |last= Grimsrud |url= http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/t_dims.htm |work= DeLorean FAQ |title= Vehicle Dimensions from Technical Manual, Workshop Manual |publisher= Dmcnews.com |date=  |accessdate= December 4, 2010 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20090401070948/http://dmcnews.com/faq/t_dims.htm |archive-date= April 1, 2009 |url-status= live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first= Knut |last= Grimsrud |url= http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/h_doors.htm |work= DeLorean FAQ |title= Historic Information: Door Design |publisher= Dmcnews.com |date=  |accessdate= December 4, 2010 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100914111250/http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/h_doors.htm |archive-date= September 14, 2010 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\n===Engine and drivetrain===\nThe [[engine]] is a [[Peugeot]]-[[Renault]]-[[Volvo]] ([[V6 PRV engine|PRV]]) {{cvt|2.85|L|cuin|0}} [[V6 engine|V6]], rated at {{convert|130|hp|PS kW|0|abbr=on}} @ 5500 rpm and [[torque]] of {{convert|153|lbft|Nm|0|abbr=on}} @ 2750 rpm.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.carfolio.com/specifications/models/car/?car=32725|website=carfolio.com|title=1981 De Lorean DMC-12 specifications|language=en-us|access-date=June 13, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180614071722/https://www.carfolio.com/specifications/models/car/?car=32725|archive-date=June 14, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.automobile-catalog.com/car/1982/587540/de_lorean_dmc-12.html|website=automobile-catalog.com|title=1982 De Lorean DMC-12 specs|language=en-us|access-date=June 13, 2018}}</ref> that was designed and built under special contract with the [[DeLorean Motor Company]]. These PRVs were a development of the 2.7-litre V6 in the [[Renault 30]] and were built in the PRV Factory in [[Douvrin]], Northern France. The 5-speed [[manual transmission]], also designed by PRV, was built at the [[Renault]] facility near [[Caen]] in [[Normandy]]. The engines and [[gearbox]]es were shipped weekly by sea from the PRV factories to the DMC factory.\n\n===Suspension===\nThe [[suspension (vehicle)|suspension]] is a four-wheel [[independent suspension]], [[coil spring]]s, and telescopic [[shock absorbers]]. The front suspension uses [[Double wishbone suspension|double wishbones]], while the rear is a [[Multi-link suspension|multi-link]] setup.\n\nWhen the DeLorean first arrived in the US, the car had a higher than expected wheel gap in the front suspension.  The nose-high appearance is the result of poor quality coil springs.  Despite having significantly less weight in the front, the front and rear springs had the same spring rate and also used lower quality steel which resulted in the nose-high look.<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9 |date= 2014 | pages = 83}}</ref>  Some people have erroneously cited a last minute change in US bumper height requirements led DMC to raise the vehicle just prior to delivery, however this is not true.  Design drawings clearly show that the design met [[National Highway Traffic Safety Administration|NHTSA]] minimum bumper and headlight heights of the time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nhtsa.gov/cars/problems/studies/Bumper/Index.html|title=Bumper Q&A's|publisher=National Highway Traffic and Safety Administration|accessdate=September 17, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111003151011/http://www.nhtsa.gov/cars/problems/studies/bumper/index.html|archive-date=October 3, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nhtsa.gov/cars/rules/rulings/glare.html|title=DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION National Highway Traffic Safety Administration, 49 CFR Part 571, [Docket No. 01-8885; Notice 01], RIN 2127-AH81, Glare from headlamps and other Front Mounted Lamps, Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standard No. 108; Lamps, Reflective Devices, and Associated Equipment|publisher=National Highway Traffic and Safety Administration|accessdate=September 17, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927155258/http://www.nhtsa.gov/cars/rules/rulings/glare.html|archive-date=September 27, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> Many owners have subsequently replaced or modified the front springs to return the front height to the original design specification.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://support.delorean.com/kb/a30/improving-handling-and-lowering-the-delorean.aspx|title=Improving handling and lowering the DeLorean - DeLorean Motor Company|author=|date=|website=support.delorean.com|access-date=June 21, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180621093431/http://support.delorean.com/kb/a30/improving-handling-and-lowering-the-delorean.aspx|archive-date=June 21, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSteering is [[rack and pinion]], with an overall [[steering ratio]] of 14.9:1, giving 2.65 turns lock-to-lock and a {{convert|35|ft|m|adj=on}} turning circle. DeLoreans are fitted with [[alloy|cast alloy]] wheels, measuring {{convert|14|in|mm}} in diameter by {{convert|6|in|mm}} wide on the front and {{convert|15|in|mm}} in diameter by {{convert|8|in|mm}} wide on the rear. These were fitted with [[Goodyear Tire and Rubber Company|Goodyear]] NCT steel-belted radial tires. The DeLorean is a [[Rear-engine, rear-wheel-drive layout|rear-engine vehicle]] with a 35%\u201365% front\u2013rear weight distribution.<ref>{{cite web|first= Knut |last= Grimsrud |url=http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/t_weight.htm |work=DeLorean FAQ |title= Weight and Balance from Technical manual |publisher=Dmcnews.com |date= |accessdate=December 4, 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe DeLorean features power-assisted [[disc brake]]s on all wheels, with {{convert|10|in|mm|adj=on}} rotors front and {{convert|10.5|in|mm|adj=on}} rear.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://oldcarbrochures.org/index.php/NA/DeLorean/1981_DeLorean/1981_Delorean_Brochure/1981-DeLorean-17|title=1981 DeLorean-17|author=|date=|website=oldcarbrochures.org|access-date=May 24, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180524222200/http://oldcarbrochures.org/index.php/NA/DeLorean/1981_DeLorean/1981_Delorean_Brochure/1981-DeLorean-17|archive-date=May 24, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nAt the time of release, the automotive press was generally complimentary towards the DeLorean.  [[Motor Trend]]<ref>{{Cite book | title = DeLorean Stainless Steel Illusion| author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |ISBN=0-9744141-0-7|date= 2003 | pages = 128\u2013129}}</ref>, [[Car and Driver]] <ref>https://www.caranddriver.com/reviews/comparison-test/a15144078/de-lorean-vs-chevy-corvette-datsun-280-zx-ferrari-308gts-porsche-911-comparison-test/</ref> and [[Road_%26_Track|Road & Track]]<ref>https://www.roadandtrack.com/car-culture/classic-cars/reviews/a27099/1982-delorean-dmc-12-road-test/</ref> had mostly positive remarks about the car.  All of them noted disappointing performance, especially those that performed comparative tests against other vehicles but were otherwise impressed with the car noting commendable gas mileage and most of them noting that the DeLorean is more of a [[grand tourer|GT]] car rather than a sports car or racecar.\n\nHowever, more recent reviews of the car have been much more harsh.  In 2017, [[Time Magazine]] included the DeLorean on its list of 50 worst cars of all time.<ref>https://time.com/4723114/50-worst-cars-of-all-time/</ref>  In his book ''Naff Motors: 101 Automotive Lemons'', Tony Davis described the build quality as \"woeful\".  ''Top Gear'' writer Richard Porter included it in his book ''Crap Cars'', calling it \"dismal\",<ref name = \"Porter\">{{cite book|last=Porter |first=Richard |title=Crap Cars |publisher=Bloomsbury |year=2005 |isbn= |page=}}</ref>\n\n==Performance==\nDMC's comparison literature noted that the DeLorean could achieve {{convert|0|\u2013|60|mph|}} in 8.8 seconds, when equipped with a manual transmission. When equipped with an automatic transmission, the DeLorean would accelerate from {{convert|0|to|60|mph|}} in 10.5 seconds as tested by ''Road & Track'' magazine. The car's top speed is {{convert|109|mph|0}}.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.roadandtrack.com/car-culture/classic-cars/reviews/a27099/1982-delorean-dmc-12-road-test/|title=1982 DeLorean DMC-12: The Vintage Road & Track Test|date=October 21, 2015|work=Road & Track|publisher=|access-date=July 23, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170803211950/http://www.roadandtrack.com/car-culture/classic-cars/reviews/a27099/1982-delorean-dmc-12-road-test/|archive-date=August 3, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Road and Track called the car: \".. not quick for a sports/GT car in this price category ..\".\n\n==Problems and issues==\nDeLoreans, early production models in particular, suffered from poor build quality as well as mechanical issues with the vehicle.  Early production cars needed as much as 140-200 hours of work at DMC Quality Assurance Centers prior to being shipped to dealerships for delivery. DMC eventually sent 30 factory workers to the quality centers in the US to learn about the issues and how to fix them.  Quality issues did improve over time and by 1982 many of the quality issues had been resolved.<ref>{{Cite book | title = DeLorean Stainless Steel Illusion| author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |ISBN=0-9744141-0-7|date= 2003 | pages = 83 - 84}}</ref>\n\nA total of four recalls were issued by the factory to correct issues such as a sticking throttle, front suspension issues and an inertia switch. <ref>{{Cite book | title = DeLorean Stainless Steel Illusion| author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |ISBN=0-9744141-0-7|date= 2003 | pages = 108\u2013109}}</ref>\n\nOther quality issues that plagued the car included other issues surrounding the front suspension, clutch pedal adjustment (or lack thereof), brake rotors, instruments; in particular the [[speedometer]], power door locks and weak alternators.  Many early DeLoreans were delivered with an incorrect alignment with the toe-in incorrectly set leading to premature tire wear. \n\nIn addition, many dealers were reluctant to perform warranty work on DeLoreans since DMC owed them money for past warranty claims that were still unpaid.  Some dealerships were not able to perform repair work properly as DMC never issued a proper service manual.  The lack of quality service at dealerships was a point of frustration for many DeLorean owners at the time, particularly those who paid over sticker price to purchase one of the first cars.<ref>{{Cite book | title = DeLorean Stainless Steel Illusion| author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |ISBN=0-9744141-0-7|date= 2003 | pages = 111\u2013112}}</ref>\n\n==Pricing and options==\n[[File:1982 De Lorean DMC12 coupe (8453073488).jpg|thumb|1982 DeLorean grey interior]]\n[[File:1981 DeLorean DMC 12 -- Virginia Museum of Transportation - 49374820477.jpg|thumb|1981 DeLorean with optional accent stripe]]\nUpon release in 1981, a DeLorean had a suggested retail price of US$25,000 ($650 more when equipped with an [[automatic transmission]]); this is equivalent to approximately US${{formatnum:{{inflation|US|25000|1981}}}} in {{inflation-year|US}}.{{inflation-fn|US}}. MSRP would increase in 1982 to $29,825<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nadaguides.com/Cars/1982/delorean/dmc-12-gullwing/2-door-sports-coupe/Values|title=1982 Delorean DMC-12 Gullwing 2 Door Sports Coupe Prices, Values & DMC-12 Gullwing 2 Door Sports Coupe Price Specs|author=|date=|website=NADAguides|access-date=June 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180616231331/https://www.nadaguides.com/Cars/1982/delorean/dmc-12-gullwing/2-door-sports-coupe/Values|archive-date=June 16, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and again in 1983 to $34,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nadaguides.com/Cars/1983/Delorean/DMC-12-Gullwing/2-Door-Sports-Coupe/Values|title=1983 Delorean DMC-12 Gullwing 2 Door Sports Coupe Prices, Values & DMC-12 Gullwing 2 Door Sports Coupe Price Specs|author=|date=|website=NADAguides|access-date=June 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180617015225/https://www.nadaguides.com/Cars/1983/Delorean/DMC-12-Gullwing/2-Door-Sports-Coupe/Values|archive-date=June 17, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> At the outset, there were extensive waiting lists of people willing to pay up to $10,000 above the list price; however, after the collapse of the DeLorean Motor Company, unsold cars could be purchased for less than the retail price.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/h_sales.htm |work=DeLorean FAQ |title= Historic Information: Sales and Dealer Experiences}}</ref>\n\nThe DeLorean was only available with two factory options; a no-cost [[manual transmission]] or automatic transmission and the choice of a grey or black interior (grey interior became available mid 1981 model year).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.deloreanmuseum.org/burgundy-delorean.html |title=one of one! factory burgundy interior delorean |access-date=September 5, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905044903/https://www.deloreanmuseum.org/burgundy-delorean.html |archive-date=September 5, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The standard feature list included stainless-steel body panels; gull-wing doors with cryogenically treated torsion bars; leather seats; [[air conditioning]]; an AM/FM [[Compact Cassette|cassette]] [[stereo system]]; [[power window]]s, [[power door locks|locks]] and [[Power side-view mirror|mirrors]]; a tilt and telescopic [[steering wheel]]; tinted glass; body side moldings; intermittent/constant windshield wipers; and an electric rear-window defogger. Several dealer options were available, including a car cover; [[Sheepskin seat cover|sheepskin]] seat covers; floor mats; car care cleaning kit; black textured accent stripes; grey scotch-cal accent stripes; a luggage rack and a ski-rack adapter.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/d_broc2.htm |work= DeLorean FAQ |title= Dealer Installed Accessories |date= June 20, 1981 |access-date= January 27, 2005 |archive-url= https://www.webcitation.org/6HxeVWMtL?url=http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/d_broc2.htm |archive-date= July 8, 2013 |url-status= live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.delorean-owners.org/legend/specs.html |title= DeLorean Owners Association: DeLorean specifications table |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19980214030500/http://delorean-owners.org/legend/specs.html |archivedate=February 14, 1998}}</ref>\n{{multiple image |align=left |direction=horizontal |total_width=390 | image1=DMC Sticker.jpg |width1=199 |height1=260 |alt1=1982 DMC-12 window sticker |image2=DMC12 clearance.jpg |width2=200 |height2=260 |alt2=DeLorean clearance advertisement |footer_align=center |footer=1982 window sticker & 1983 DeLorean clearance advertisement}}\n{{clear}}\n\n==Production changes==\nAlthough there were no typical yearly updates to the DeLorean, several changes were made to the DeLorean during production.<ref name=\"autogenerated1946\"/>  Instead of making changes at the end of the model year, DMC implemented changes mid-production. This resulted in no clear distinction between the 1981, 1982, and 1983 model years, but with subtle changes taking place almost continuously throughout the life cycle of the DeLorean.\n\n===Hood styles===\nThe original [[hood (vehicle)|hood]] of the DeLorean had [[Groove (machining)|grooves]] running down both sides. It included a tank flap to simplify [[Filling station|fuel filling]]. These cars typically had a locking cap to prevent fuel theft by [[siphon]]ing. In August 1981, the hood flap was removed from the hood of the cars (although the hood creases remained). This style was retained well into 1982.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://babbtechnology.com/thecar/Prod_changes/index.htm |title=The DeLorean |publisher=Babb Technology |date=April 8, 2008 |accessdate=November 6, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304035413/http://babbtechnology.com/thecar/Prod_changes/index.htm |archive-date=March 4, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> Based on production numbers for all three years, this hood style is probably the most common. After the supply of locking caps was exhausted, the company switched to a non-locking version (resulting in at least 500 cars with no flap, but with locking caps). The final styling for the hood included the addition of a DeLorean name badge and the removal of the grooves, resulting in a completely flat hood. According to senior personnel who worked at the Dunmurry factory, initial elimination of flapped hoods has a simple if unglamorous explanation; Chuck Benington, managing director, did not like the design.<ref>{{cite web|title=Nick Sutton, Purchasing Manager, Dunmurry factory|url=http://dmctalk.org/showthread.php?1412-How-DeLoreans-Were-Originally-Built-Stainless-Panel-Discussion&p=20354&viewfull=1#post20354|accessdate=September 17, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402132250/http://dmctalk.org/showthread.php?1412-How-DeLoreans-Were-Originally-Built-Stainless-Panel-Discussion&p=20354&viewfull=1#post20354|archive-date=April 2, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>{{multiple image |align=left |direction=horizontal |total_width=600 |image1=Early 1981 De Lorean hood.jpg |width1=387 |height1=142 |alt1=Early 1981 hood |image2=1983 De Lorean hood.jpg |width2=414 |height2=162 |alt2=1983 hood |footer_align=center |footer=Side-by-side comparison of an early 1981 hood (left) vs. a later model 1983 hood (right)}}\n{{clear}}\n\n===Other changes===\nJohn DeLorean was {{height|ft=6|in=4}} tall, and he designed the car to comfortably fit someone of his stature.<ref>{{Cite news|url= http://www.businessweek.com/articles/2012-04-19/the-deloreans-time-leap|title= The DeLorean's Time Leap|author= Claire Suddath|publisher= [[Bloomberg Businessweek]]|date= April 19, 2012|access-date= July 14, 2014|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140706011419/http://www.businessweek.com/articles/2012-04-19/the-deloreans-time-leap|archive-date= July 6, 2014|url-status= live}}</ref> For shorter people, the addition of a pull strap made closing the doors much easier from the inside. These attach to the existing door handle. Late-model 1981 cars, and all cars from 1982 and 1983, have doors with integrated pull straps.<ref name=\"babbtechnology.com\">{{cite web|url=http://babbtechnology.com/thecar/Prod_changes/index.htm|title=DeLorean \u2013 The Car: Production Changes|work=babbtechnology.com|access-date=August 10, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304035413/http://babbtechnology.com/thecar/Prod_changes/index.htm|archive-date=March 4, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe side [[bolster]]ing in the DeLorean was originally separate from the main interior pieces. In cars with this construction, is a tendency to place pressure on this piece when entering and exiting the vehicle, which eventually causes the bolstering to separate from the trim panel. To solve this problem, cars built in and after late 1981 have one solid trim piece with the bolster permanently attached.<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9|date= 2014 | pages = 38\u201339}}</ref>\n\nAs an addition to later cars, a foot rest, or [[dead pedal]], was added to help prevent [[fatigue (physical)|fatigue]] while driving. This is one of the few changes that is directly tied to a model year. These were built into only a few of the late-1981 vehicles and were added to all cars starting with 1982 production.<ref name=\"babbtechnology.com\"/>\n\nAlthough the styling of the DeLorean's wheels remained unchanged, the wheels of early-model 1981 vehicles were painted grey. These wheels sported matching grey centre caps with an embossed DMC logo. Early into the 1981 production run, these were changed to a polished silver look, with a contrasting black center cap. The embossed logo on the center caps was painted silver to add contrast.<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9|date= 2014 | pages = 25\u201326}}</ref>\n\nIn 1981, the DeLorean came with an AM/FM stereo radio with cassette made by Craig. Since the Craig radio did not have a built-in clock, one was installed in front of the [[gear shift]] on the console. DeLorean switched to an ASI stereo in the middle of the 1982 production run. Since the ASI radio featured an on-board clock, the clock on the console was removed at the same time.<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9|date= 2014 | pages = 44\u201345}}</ref>\n\nThe first 2,200 cars produced used a windshield-embedded [[antenna (radio)|antenna]]. This type of antenna proved to be unsuitable with poor radio reception. Oftentimes the radio would continually \"seek\", attempting to find a signal. A standard whip antenna, which was later changed to a manually retractable antenna, was added to the outside of the front right fender. While improving radio reception, this resulted in a hole in the stainless steel, and an unsightly antenna. As a result, the antenna was again moved. The final antenna was an automatic retractable version installed under the rear induction grill behind the rear driver's-side window.<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9|date= 2014 | pages = 28\u201329}}</ref>\n\nThe small [[visor|sun visors]] on the DeLorean have [[Polyvinyl chloride|vinyl]] on one side and headliner [[Textile|fabric]] on the other side. Originally these were installed such that the headliner side would be on the bottom when not in use. Later on in 1981, they were reversed so that the vinyl side would be on the bottom.<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |date= 2014 |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9| pages = 40}}</ref>\n\nThe original 80 amp Ducellier [[Alternator (auto)|alternator]] supplied with the early-production DeLoreans could not provide enough [[electric current|current]] to supply the car when all lights and electrical options were on; as a result, the [[battery (electricity)|battery]] would gradually discharge, leaving the driver stranded on the road. Beginning with cars built in late 1981, DeLoreans were fitted from the factory with a 90 amp [[Motorola]] alternator, which solved this problem. Additional battery drainage problems were caused by faulty or improperly adjusted door jamb switches. This switch activated the \"safety\" lights located around the door perimeter when it was open. When the door was closed, the door seals prevented the light from being seen. Due to the faulty switches the lights remained on, draining the battery. This happened to DeLorean owner [[Johnny Carson]] shortly after he was presented with the vehicle.\n\n<gallery>\n|align=\n\nFile:De Lorean add-on Pull strap.jpg|Early pull strap\nFile:Delorean dmc-12 later style side bolster.jpg|Later-style one-piece bolster\nFile:mid 1981 De Lorean silver wheel.JPG|Mid-1981 silver wheel\n</gallery>\n\n==Notable and unique DeLoreans==\n===Wooden Mock-up===\n[[File:Ulster Transport Museum, Cultra, DMC-12 Coupe clay model of Italdesign, Moncalieri, Turin for the De Lorean Company, 1975 04.jpg|thumb|DMC-12 Coupe Mock-up]]\nIn March 1975, DMC entered into a contract with Ital Design to have Giorgetto Giugiaro design the DeLorean Sports Car.  John DeLorean and Bill Collins approved one of the many designs and subsequently the styling mock-up that was made from \u201cepo-wood\u201d was scheduled to be shipped to the DMC office in Michigan on July 31, 1975.  This mockup would serve as the platform in which the prototype was developed.\n\nThe original full-size epowood DeLorean styling model which was modified in the first quarter of 1979 to reflect the refreshed design used in production, was donated to the [[Ulster Folk and Transport Museum]], in [[Cultra]], [[Northern Ireland]] where it is now on display.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nmni.com/uftm/Collections/Transport-(1)/|title=Ulster Folk and Transport Museum - Online Collections|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Prototypes and pilot cars===\nOnly one of two DeLorean prototypes still exists.<ref>{{cite web |author=PJ Grady Europe |url=http://www.pjgrady.co.uk/GenericContent.aspx?PageType=Delorean_Repairs&ShowContent=Prototype_Restoration.html |publisher=DeLorean PJ Grady Europe |title=Delorean Repairs |accessdate=January 13, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140421053458/http://www.pjgrady.co.uk/GenericContent.aspx?PageType=Delorean_Repairs&ShowContent=Prototype_Restoration.html |archivedate=April 21, 2014  }}</ref> Prototype 1 sold at the bankruptcy auction in 1984 for $37,000.<ref name=\"upi.com\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1984/11/25/DeLorean-prototype-cars-sell-at-auction-for-total-58000/3565470206800/ |title=DeLorean prototype cars sell at auction for total $58,000 |access-date=June 2, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190602233213/https://www.upi.com/Archives/1984/11/25/DeLorean-prototype-cars-sell-at-auction-for-total-58000/3565470206800/ |archive-date=June 2, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>  The car remained in a private collection until 2005 when it was sold to the owner of DeLorean Motor Company of Florida (DMCFL) where it received a complete restoration.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.liveauctioneers.com/item/4041986_1587-1976-delorean-dmc-12-original-prototype |title=1587: 1976 DeLorean DMC-12 Original Prototype |access-date=June 2, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190602234250/https://www.liveauctioneers.com/item/4041986_1587-1976-delorean-dmc-12-original-prototype |archive-date=June 2, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Proto 1 is now on display at DMCFL. Proto 2 was sent to [[Lotus Cars]] for development and evaluation in 1978. It was reported to have been destroyed in the 1990s.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Car |url=http://www.deloreanmuseum.org/car.html |website=The Delorean Museum |publisher=The Delorean Museum |accessdate=October 7, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151006112343/http://www.deloreanmuseum.org/car.html |archivedate=October 6, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nAn estimated 28 pilot cars were built by DMC. The pilot cars are best identified by the subtly different interiors and sliding side windows. These cars, used for evaluation and regulatory testing of the DeLorean, were previously thought to have been destroyed. Subsequently, several of the pilot cars were found to have survived.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dmctalk.org/showthread.php?1167-Earliest-known-Pilot-car-found-photographed |title=Earliest known Pilot car found/photographed |publisher=Dmctalk.org |date=November 5, 1955 |accessdate=January 13, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140114132601/http://dmctalk.org/showthread.php?1167-Earliest-known-Pilot-car-found-photographed |archive-date=January 14, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=PJ Grady Europe |url=http://www.pjgrady.co.uk/GenericContent.aspx?PageType=Pilot_Chronology&ShowContent=Pilot_Cars.html |title=Pilot Chronology |publisher=Pjgrady.co.uk |date=November 24, 1980 |accessdate=January 13, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140421051421/http://www.pjgrady.co.uk/GenericContent.aspx?PageType=Pilot_Chronology&ShowContent=Pilot_Cars.html |archivedate=April 21, 2014  }}</ref> Pilot car 25 which was featured on the front cover of [[Autocar (magazine)|Autocar]] in 1981 was found in 2003 in a barn in Northern Ireland.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pjgrady.co.uk/pilot-25 |title=pilot-25 |access-date=September 5, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905040305/https://www.pjgrady.co.uk/pilot-25 |archive-date=September 5, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Visioneering car===\nWith the 1980 [[National Automobile Dealers Association|NADA]] meeting approaching, DMC planned to show a final \u201cproduction\u201d version of the DeLorean, however there were no production cars ready at the time or even any production stainless steel panels.\n\nEarlier, in the summer of 1979, the revised Giugiaro styling mock-up was shipped to Visioneering, a [[Detroit]] based company, to create data needed to make the stamping dies for the stainless panels. This project would expand to create dies used to create a \u201cproduction\u201d car for the NADA show.\n\nUsing a prototype chassis supplied by Lotus in late 1979, Visioneering completed the assembly of this car at a cost of $750,000. The car was presented at the 1980 NADA show and was later used for engineering development and technical training as well as press photos. The Visioneering car would eventually be sold at the bankruptcy auction in late 1984 for $21,000.<ref name=\"upi.com\"/> Today, the car is in a private collection.<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage| ISBN = 978-0-9856578-1-9 |date= 2012 | page = 108}}</ref>\n\n===Legend turbo cars===\nIt was determined that the DeLorean needed additional power when automotive magazine road tests showed {{convert|0|\u2013|60|mph|abbr=on}} times for the DeLorean between 9.5 and 10.5 seconds, while its rivals were in the 7.5\u20138.5 second range. There had been interest in [[turbocharger|turbocharging]] the DeLorean early on, but the DMC engineering staff was busy with other projects, so DeLorean decided to go outside to develop a turbocharged version of the DeLorean.<ref name=\"Stainless Steel Illusion\">{{Cite book | title = Stainless Steel Illusion | isbn=0-9744141-0-7 | author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |date= 2003 | pages = 110\u2013111}}</ref>\n\nHaving had previous success with turbocharging [[Fiat 124 Sport Spider|Fiat Spiders]], DeLorean entered into a contract with Legend Industries, based in [[Hauppauge, New York|Hauppauge]], [[New York (state)|New York]]. DMC wanted to increase power without sacrificing fuel efficiency. DMC wanted a wide power band and did not want a surge of power similar to the [[Porsche 930]] Turbo. Legend used twin [[IHI Corporation|IHI]] RHB52 turbos along with twin [[intercooler]]s. The results were an engine capable of accelerating smoothly in fifth gear from 1,500&nbsp;rpm to full turbo boost at 2,500&nbsp;rpm, reaching {{convert|150|mph|abbr=on}} at 6,500&nbsp;rpm.<ref name=\"Stainless Steel Illusion\" />\n[[File:Legend engine.jpg|thumb|Legend Twin Turbo setup from VIN 530]]\n\nIn addition, Legend Industries developed a single turbocharged setup that was never finished.\nThe company converted a total of four DeLoreans and two Renault Alpines, which were the first development cars.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pjgrady.co.uk/#!vin-530/cjd7|title=Delorean Car Sales Europe UK. Canvey Island Essex SS8 OPQ|publisher=|access-date=February 18, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130513040331/http://www.pjgrady.co.uk/#!vin-530/cjd7|archive-date=May 13, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> [[VIN]] 530 was written in numerous press articles as the fastest production car of its era.\n\nIn a test run of VIN 530 at [[Bridgehampton Race Circuit|Bridgehampton Raceway]] in 1981, the twin-turbo DeLorean was quicker than a [[Ferrari 308 GTB/GTS|Ferrari 308]] and a [[Porsche 928]]. It has been a misconception for many years that VIN 502 was at Bridgehampton and used in testing; however, evidence from pictures, along with information from a Legend employee published by PJ Grady, indicates that 530 was used along with VIN 558.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pjgrady.co.uk/identifying-the-legend-cars |title=identifying-the-legend-cars |access-date=September 5, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905041236/https://www.pjgrady.co.uk/identifying-the-legend-cars |archive-date=September 5, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> By the time of Bridgehampton, Legend had perfected modular boosting, which the earlier prototypes did not have installed apart from one of the Alpine mules and VIN 530.<ref>{{cite web | title=DeLorean DMC-12 | website=Silodrome | date=March 3, 2018 | url=https://silodrome.com/delorean-dmc-12-buying-guide/ | access-date=September 5, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905042552/https://silodrome.com/delorean-dmc-12-buying-guide/ | archive-date=September 5, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nVIN 530 tested 0\u201360&nbsp;mph in 5.8 seconds and the [[Dragstrip|{{convert|1/4|mi|m|0}}]] in 14.7 seconds. John DeLorean was so impressed with the engine, he committed to ordering 5,000 engines from Legend Industries. DMC planned to offer a turbocharged engine as a $7,500 option in 1984 (presumably to compete with the newly redesigned [[Chevrolet Corvette (C4)|1984 Corvette]]). Before any of the 5,000 cars could be put into production, DMC had declared bankruptcy, which drove Legend Industries, as well as other suppliers, into bankruptcy.<ref name=\"DeLorean Gold Portfolio\">{{Cite book | title = DeLorean Gold Portfolio | author=R. M. Clarke| publisher = Brookland Books LTD. |ISBN=1-85520-331-6 |date= 1996 | pages = 137\u2013143}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" Style=\"text-align:center\"\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n|-\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n!\tVIN\t!!\tConfiguration\t!!\tLast known location\t!!\tComments\n|-\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n|\t502\t||\tTwin\t||\tNew Zealand\t||\tOriginal prototype\n|-\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n|\t528\t||\tSingle\t||\tNew York\t||\t\n|-\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n|\t530\t||\tTwin\t||\tUnited Kingdom\t||\tSister twin-turbo\n|-\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n|\t558\t||\tSingle\t||\tUnknown\t||\t\n|}\n\n===Gold-plated===\n[[File:gold-D.jpg|thumb|A gold-plated DeLorean in Reno, Nevada]]\nFor Christmas 1980, a DeLorean/[[American Express]] promotion planned to sell 100 [[Karat|24K]]-[[Gilding|gold-plated]] DeLoreans for US$85,000 each to its gold-card members, but only two were sold.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.caranddriver.com/in-1980-you-could-buy-an-85000-24k-gold-plated-delorean/|title=In 1980, You Could Buy an $85,000, 24K-Gold-Plated DeLorean|publisher=|access-date=September 4, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160920152935/http://blog.caranddriver.com/in-1980-you-could-buy-an-85000-24k-gold-plated-delorean/|archive-date=September 20, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> One of these was purchased by Roger Mize, president of Snyder National Bank in [[Snyder, Texas]]. VIN #4301 sat in the bank lobby for over 20 years before being loaned to the [[Petersen Automotive Museum]] in [[Los Angeles]]. It has a black interior and an automatic transmission.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigtexas.com/dmc/ |title=The 24-Karat Gold Plated DeLorean Car |publisher=Bigtexas.com |accessdate=January 22, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120224111825/http://www.bigtexas.com/dmc/ |archivedate=February 24, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nThe second gold-plated American Express DeLorean was purchased by Sherwood Marshall, an entrepreneur and former [[Royal Canadian Navy|Royal Canadian Naval]] Officer. Marshall donated his DeLorean to the [[William F. Harrah]] Foundation/[[National Automobile Museum]] in [[Reno, Nevada]]. This car, VIN #4300, is equipped with a manual transmission and a saddle-brown interior.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.automuseum.org |title=National Automobile Museum |publisher=National Automobile Museum |date= |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101207005657/http://www.automuseum.org/ |archive-date=December 7, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nA third gold-plated car exists that was assembled with spare parts that were required by American Express in case one of the other two that were built were damaged. All necessary gold-plated parts were on hand, with the exception of one door that was sourced later.<ref name=bigtexas>{{cite web|url=http://bigtexas.com/dmc/gold/ |title=Gold DeLorean for sale in LaVale, Maryland |publisher=Bigtexas.com |date= |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110812111029/http://bigtexas.com/dmc/gold/|archivedate=August 12, 2011 }}</ref> The car was first acquired by the winner of a [[Big Lots]] store raffle. Consolidated International, which owned the department store, had purchased 1374 DeLoreans during the DeLorean Motor Company's financial troubles, acquiring the remaining stock after the company went into receivership. It was listed for sale online at a price of US$250,000,<ref name=bigtexas/> but it is unclear whether it ever sold.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigtexas.com/dmc/gold/ |title=Delorean for sale in LaVale, Maryland |publisher=Archive.is |accessdate=January 13, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120524094241/http://bigtexas.com/dmc/gold/ |archivedate=May 24, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nA gold-plated DeLorean was reproduced privately by an enthusiast.<ref>{{cite web |author= |url=http://mycarquest.com/2013/02/gold-plated-deloreans-yes-there-were-four.html |title=Gold Plated DeLoreans? \u2013 Yes There Were Four |publisher=Mycarquest.com |date=February 21, 2013 |accessdate=January 13, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140421051720/http://mycarquest.com/2013/02/gold-plated-deloreans-yes-there-were-four.html |archive-date=April 21, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Right-hand-drive models===\nDeLoreans were primarily intended for the American market. All production models were therefore [[left-hand-drive]]. DeLorean Motor Company was aware as early as April 1981 of the need to produce a [[right-hand-drive]] (RHD) version to supply to world markets, specifically the United Kingdom.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pjgrady.co.uk/woller-hodec |title=woller-hodec |access-date=September 5, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905043041/https://www.pjgrady.co.uk/woller-hodec |archive-date=September 5, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe company faced the choice of building right-hand-drive models from scratch or performing a post-production conversion exercise. Given the cost of new body molds, tooling, and a host of specific parts that a factory-built right-hand-drive configuration would require, the company opted to investigate the idea of a post-production conversion using a UK company based in [[Hampshire]] called Wooler-Hodec Ltd.<ref>{{cite book | last=Narus | first=D. | title=Independent Sports Cars | publisher=Lulu.com | year=2017 | isbn=978-1-387-15601-6 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HolUDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA48 | access-date=August 30, 2019 | page=48}}</ref>{{self-published inline|date=February 2020}}\n\n[[File:De Lorean DMC12 - Flickr - foshie (1).jpg|thumb|RHD DeLorean]]\nOnly 16 right-hand-drive factory-authorized DeLoreans were ever produced.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deloreans.co.uk/rhd-euro/index.html |title=DeLorean: Euro Spec DeLoreans |publisher=Deloreans.co.uk |accessdate=May 4, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100617185502/http://www.deloreans.co.uk/rhd-euro/index.html |archivedate=June 17, 2010 }}</ref> These cars can be divided into two distinct groups:\n# The first batch, known by enthusiasts as the \"Wooler-Hodec cars\", were converted by the UK company of that name. Evidence still exists in the form of a DMC factory memo, which orders 20 cars to be converted to right-hand drive.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://docs.wixstatic.com/ugd/3d11d1_78b371c4af664be7ba130b81c1ddd557.pdf |title=DMC Inter-Office Memo: RHD Conversion Programme |access-date=September 5, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905045408/https://docs.wixstatic.com/ugd/3d11d1_78b371c4af664be7ba130b81c1ddd557.pdf |archive-date=September 5, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Due to the factory's closure, this order was never completed, and today a total of 13 cars survive, carrying the VINs 510, 12171\u201312181 and 12199.\n# The second batch were registered and used by the factory in Northern Ireland, with registration numbers (license plates), AXI 1697, AXI 1698, AXI 1699 and are referred to by enthusiasts as the \"AXI cars\". These three cars (VINs 5565, 5592 and 5638) differ from the first Wooler-Hodec cars in several ways. They all had roof-mounted radio antennas, indicator repeater lights, no side marker lights, white forward-facing door lights, fog-light switch, and textured body rubstrips on the stainless panels. No [[catalytic converters]] or [[Oxygen sensor|lambda equipment]] were fitted, as British legislation did not require them. \n\nOwners who bought these cars at auction in the early 1980s encountered difficulty in registering them as new vehicles in the UK. At this point a former DeLorean Motor Cars executive offered to modify and register the cars so that they could be used in the UK. These modifications included:\n* Different seat-belt units fitted.<ref name=\"foglight\">{{cite web|url=http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/fogswitch01.jpg |publisher=DeLorean Owners Club UK |title=Reference image illustrating modified seat belt unit in right-hand drive car |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724223213/http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/fogswitch01.jpg |archivedate=July 24, 2011 }}</ref>\n* The fitting of Rubbolite tail light clusters with a built-in fog light function.<ref name=\"rubberlight\">{{cite web|url=http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/rubberlight02.jpg |publisher=DeLorean Owners Club UK |title=Reference image illustrating so-called \"Euro-spec\" tail light unit |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724223141/http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/rubberlight02.jpg |archivedate=July 24, 2011 }}</ref>\n* The fitting of a fog light switch to one of the center-console dummy switches.<ref name=\"foglight\"/>\n* A custom-made tail light surround and number (license) plate bezel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/rubberlight01.jpg |publisher=DeLorean Owners Club UK |title=Reference image illustrating custom fabricated tail light and number (license) plate bezel fitted on an official right-hand drive car |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724223225/http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/rubberlight01.jpg |archivedate=July 24, 2011 }}</ref>\n* Swapping the front turn signal lenses for ones of a different, more rounded style.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/frontrepeater02.jpg |publisher=DeLorean Owners Club UK |title=Reference image illustrating rounded turn signal lens on an official right-hand drive car |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110712013912/http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/frontrepeater02.jpg |archivedate=July 12, 2011 }}</ref>\n* Swapping the rear side marker lenses for amber ones.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/rearmarker01.jpg |publisher=DeLorean Owners Club UK |title=Reference image illustrating amber rear side marker lens fitted on an official right-hand drive car |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724223301/http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/rearmarker01.jpg |archivedate=July 24, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nAll of the 13 Wooler-Hodec cars were modified to the OEM front turn-signal lens fixing method in order to make them fit flush with the front fascia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/frontrepeater01.jpg |publisher=DeLorean Owners Club UK |title=Reference image illustrating modified front turn signal lens |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110712013859/http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/frontrepeater01.jpg |archivedate=July 12, 2011 }}</ref> The cars' headlights were also changed for right-hand-drive spec lights that incorporate a UK sidelight feature. \n\n\nBy contrast, the three AXI cars had further modifications to the amber front door lights, which were exchanged for clear lenses of the same style.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/whitedoorlight01.jpg |publisher=DeLorean Owners Club UK |title=Reference image illustrating clear door light lens |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724223348/http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/whitedoorlight01.jpg |archivedate=July 24, 2011 }}</ref> Perhaps the most significant alteration on the AXI cars is the deletion of the front and rear side markers. These are replaced by a single small round European-style indicator side repeater, situated on the front wing (fender). The body rubstrips are also of a different configuration in order to cover the areas that would otherwise have had federal side marker lenses fitted.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/flasherrepeater02.jpg |publisher=DeLorean Owners Club UK |title=Reference image illustrating modified rubstrips and single round marker light |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724223415/http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/flasherrepeater02.jpg |archivedate=July 24, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n===''Back to the Future''===\n{{Main|DeLorean time machine}}\n[[File:'81-'82 DeLorean DMC-12.jpg|thumb|A DeLorean \"time machine\" from the ''Back to the Future'' trilogy exhibited at [[Universal Studios Florida]]]]\nSeveral special-edition DeLorean cars have been produced over the years, and the car is most notably featured as the time machine in the [[Back to the Future (franchise)|''Back to the Future'' film trilogy]]. Six DeLorean chassis were used during the production, along with one manufactured out of fiberglass for scenes where a full-size DeLorean was needed to \"fly\" on-screen; only three of the cars still exist, with one that was destroyed at the end of ''[[Back to the Future Part III]]'', two additional cars were abandoned, and the fiberglass replica was scrapped. Universal Studios owns two of the remaining cars, occasionally putting them on display or using them for other productions, and the last resides in a private collection after having been extensively restored.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bttf3delorean.com/Where_are_they.html |title=BTTF3 DeLorean: Where Are They? |date= |accessdate=January 1, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111005125859/http://bttf3delorean.com/Where_are_they.html |archive-date=October 5, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> The official ''[[Back to the Future]]'' DeLorean can be viewed at the [[Petersen Automotive Museum]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://petersen.org/backtothefuture/ |title=Petersen Automotive Museum |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160320133259/http://petersen.org/backtothefuture/ |archivedate=March 20, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nA number of production DeLoreans have been modified by the [[Automotive aftermarket|aftermarket]] into ''Back to the Future'' time machine replicas, whose bodies and interiors are modified to mirror the appearance and functions of the film cars.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bobspropshop.com/bttf.html|title=Bob's Prop Shop|work=bobspropshop.com|access-date=November 13, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141016005640/http://www.bobspropshop.com/bttf.html|archive-date=October 16, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==DMC Texas==\n[[File:\" 12 - ITALY (Milan) Electro Vehicles Europe ( EVE ) DeLorean DMC-12.JPG|thumb|[[Electric car|All-electric model]] DMCev in Milan (2012)]]\nIn 1995, Stephen Wynne from Liverpool created a separate company based in Texas using the [[DeLorean Motor Company (Texas)|DeLorean Motor Company]] name. Wynne acquired the trademark on the stylized DMC logo, along with the remaining parts inventory of the original DeLorean Motor Company. The company rebuilds cars at its [[Humble, Texas]], location using a combination of [[new old stock]] (NOS) parts, original equipment manufacturer (OEM), and reproduction parts on a made-to-order basis.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.delorean.com/index-5.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718103728/http://www.delorean.com/index-5.html|archivedate=July 18, 2011|title=New build cars|publisher=DeLorean Motor Company|accessdate=May 26, 2010}}</ref>\n\nDMC Texas (based in [[Humble, Texas]]) announced on July 30, 2007, that the car would be returning into very limited production (about 20 cars a year) in 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-garage28jul28,1,6560463.story |title=For the DeLorean, it's back to the present |work=LA Times |date=July 28, 2007 |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110310115947/http://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-garage28jul28,1,6560463.story |archive-date=March 10, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> They were subsequently sued by John DeLorean's widow for illegally licensing the family name. DMC Texas settled this lawsuit in September 2015 by paying his widow an undisclosed sum and in turn received rights to use the name, images, and trademark in the future.<ref>{{cite web|title = Lawyers Settle DeLorean Lawsuit Just in Time for 'Back to the Future' Day|url = https://blogs.wsj.com/law/2015/10/21/lawyers-settle-delorean-lawsuit-just-in-time-for-back-to-the-future-day/|website = WSJ Blogs \u2013 Law Blog|date = October 21, 2015|accessdate = December 26, 2015|first = Jacob|last = Gershman|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151222085854/http://blogs.wsj.com/law/2015/10/21/lawyers-settle-delorean-lawsuit-just-in-time-for-back-to-the-future-day/|archive-date = December 22, 2015|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nThe cars were announced to have a new stainless-steel frame; with optional extras such as GPS, an enhanced \"Stage 2\" engine, and possibly a new modern interior. Given that the cars were made with 80% old parts,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,293814,00.html |title=Texas Entrepreneur Set to Start Building DeLorean Cars |publisher=Fox News |date=August 21, 2007 |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130511132411/http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,293814,00.html |archive-date=May 11, 2013 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> the term \"return to production\" is something of a misnomer; the cars are constructed on DeLorean underbodies built by the original company in the 1980s and retaining their VINs. The cars' titles show the year of the underbody's manufacture. Therefore, they are not new DeLoreans, but complete rebuilds of the car from the underbody with enhancements. In 2009, the price of a refurbished DeLorean from DMC Texas started at US$57,500, and the project was featured in an episode of ''[[Modern Marvels]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.motorauthority.com/news/1040516_anything-but-rusty-reviewing-the-delorean-in-2009/page-2|title=Anything But Rusty: Reviewing The DeLorean In 2009|first=Ryan|last=McCaffrey|publisher=Motor Authority|date=December 20, 2009|accessdate=November 6, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222115538/http://www.motorauthority.com/news/1040516_anything-but-rusty-reviewing-the-delorean-in-2009/page-2|archive-date=December 22, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn October 18, 2011, it was announced that an all-electric model would be available for sale by 2013. It was said to have a {{Convert|200|hp|0|abbr=on|adj=on}} motor, accelerate from {{Convert|0|to|60|mph|abbr=on|km/h}} in 8 seconds, and sell for US$90,000.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.foxnews.com/leisure/2011/10/18/electric-delorean-coming-in-2013/ |title=Electric DeLorean Coming in 2013 |work=Fox News |date=October 18, 2011 |accessdate=October 28, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111029024300/http://www.foxnews.com/leisure/2011/10/18/electric-delorean-coming-in-2013/ |archivedate=October 29, 2011  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://automotivediscovery.com/the-new-2013-delorean-ev-gets-some-test-runs-by-enthusiasts/9210689/ |title=The New DeLorean EV Gets Some Test Runs by Enthusiasts |work=Automotive Discovery |date=October 26, 2011 |accessdate=October 28, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141026195129/http://automotivediscovery.com/the-new-2013-delorean-ev-gets-some-test-runs-by-enthusiasts/9210689/ |archive-date=October 26, 2014 |url-status=dead  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/eco-nomics/2011/10/19/back-to-the-future-all-electric-delorean-coming-in-2013/ |title=Back To The Future: All Electric DeLorean Coming in 2013 |work=Forbes |date=October 19, 2011 |accessdate=October 28, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111101212905/http://www.forbes.com/sites/eco-nomics/2011/10/19/back-to-the-future-all-electric-delorean-coming-in-2013/ |archive-date=November 1, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> Initial test drives revealed that the prototype had a range of {{Convert|70|mi|km}}, approaching the {{Convert|100|mi|km}} that was announced.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jalopnik.com/5850448/electric-delorean-first-drive|title=Electric DeLorean: First Drive|first=Kevin|last=McCauley|publisher=Jalopnik|date=October 17, 2011|accessdate=November 6, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151025045755/http://jalopnik.com/5850448/electric-delorean-first-drive|archive-date=October 25, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> However, 2014 saw criticism from fans who tried to buy the electric DeLorean only to learn that it was still unavailable.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cardebater.com/it-seems-delorean-has-gone-back-to-the-past-again/|title=It Seems DeLorean Has Gone Back To The Past Again|first=Wes|last=Lungwitz|publisher=Car Debater|date=February 14, 2014|accessdate=November 6, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106215825/http://www.cardebater.com/it-seems-delorean-has-gone-back-to-the-past-again/|archive-date=November 6, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDue to the passage of the [[Low Volume Motor Vehicle Manufacturers Act of 2015|Low Volume Vehicle Manufacturing Act]], DMC Texas announced that it would be producing replica DeLoreans with an expected release date in 2017. DMC anticipated building approximately 50 vehicles per year over six years with an estimated retail price of US$100,000.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://jalopnik.com/the-delorean-is-coming-back-thanks-to-this-new-law-1755528406 |title=The DeLorean Is Coming Back Thanks To This New Law, Will Have 300-400 HP |first=Jason |last=Torchinsky |publisher= |access-date=January 21, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190830195816/https://jalopnik.com/the-delorean-is-coming-back-thanks-to-this-new-law-1755528406 |archive-date=August 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.roadandtrack.com/car-culture/classic-cars/news/a28016/new-delorean-replicas-coming/ |title=Brand-New DeLorean Replicas Are on the Way |date=January 27, 2016 |publisher= |access-date=January 21, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190914085258/https://www.roadandtrack.com/car-culture/classic-cars/news/a28016/new-delorean-replicas-coming/ |archive-date=September 14, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In October 2016, DMC announced that it was expecting to build 12 units in the first production year with as many as 50 in the second year of production.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newdelorean.com/blog/ |title=DMC Blog - DeLorean - The New DMC DeLorean |publisher= |access-date=December 18, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160827145747/http://www.newdelorean.com/blog/ |archive-date=August 27, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>   In December 2019, the NHTSA issued guidelines for the Low Volume Vehicle Manufacturing Act<ref>https://www.nhtsa.gov/sites/nhtsa.dot.gov/files/documents/replica_vehicle_program_nprm_12172019.pdf</ref> and DMC Texas is now projecting they will begin production in 2021.<ref>https://www.autoblog.com/2020/01/24/delorean-motor-company-dmc-12-new-cars/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}<!-- Dead note \"production2\": [http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/img/news/n_vinrat.pdf DMC-12 Estimated Production Volumes by Month] (PDF) by Knut Grimsrud -->\n<!-- Dead note \"production3\": [http://www.delorean-owners.org/legend/index.html DMC - The legend - DeLorean: Stainless Style] -->\n<!-- Dead note \"production3\": [http://www.delorean.hu/ - Delorean Club Hungary- DeLorean: Stainless Style] -->\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book |first1= John Z. |last1= DeLorean |first2= Ted |last2= Schwarz |title= DeLorean |location= Grand Rapids, MI |publisher= Zondervan |year= 1985 |isbn= 0-310-37940-7 |url-access= registration |url= https://archive.org/details/delorean00delo }}\n* {{cite book |first= John |last= Lamm |title= DeLorean Stainless Steel Illusion |edition= 2nd |year= 2003 |location= Fort Jones, CA |publisher= Red Lion Press |isbn= 0-9744141-0-7}}\n* {{cite book |first= R. M. |last= Clarke |title= DeLorean: 1977\u20131995 Gold Portfolio |year= 1995 |location= Cobham |publisher= Brooklands |isbn= 1-85520-331-6}}\n* {{cite book |first= James |last= Espey |title= The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | edition= 2nd |year= 2014 |publisher= the DeLorean Garage |isbn= 978-0-9856578-1-9}}\n* {{cite book |first= Chris | last= Parnham |first2= Andrew | last2= Withers |title= DeLorean Celebrating the Impossible |year= 2015| location = | publisher= DeLorean Motor Cars (1978) Ltd.| isbn= 978-0-9928594-0-4}}\n* {{cite book |first= Chris |last= Williams|title= DeLorean DMC-12 [sic], The Essential Buyers Guide (2018) |year=2018 | location= |publisher= Veloce Publishing| isbn= 978-1-787112-32-2}}\n\n==External links==\n<!--======================== {{No more links}} ============================\n | PLEASE BE CAUTIOUS IN ADDING MORE LINKS TO THIS ARTICLE. Wikipedia |\n | is not a collection of links nor should it be used for advertising. |\n | |\n | Excessive or inappropriate links WILL BE DELETED. |\n | See [[Wikipedia:External links]] & [[Wikipedia:Spam]] for details. |\n | |\n | If there are already plentiful links, please propose additions or |\n | replacements on this article's discussion page, or submit your link |\n | to the relevant category at the Open Directory Project (dmoz.org) |\n | and link back to that category using the {{dmoz}} template. |\n==={{No more links}}=========-->\n\n{{Commons category|DeLorean DMC-12}}\n* [http://www.delorean.com/ DeLorean Motor Company]\n* {{curlie|Recreation/Autos/Makes_and_Models/DeLorean/|DeLorean}}\n* {{imcdb vehicle|make=De Lorean|model=DMC 12|DeLorean}}\n* [http://www.finecars.cc/en/detail/car/10075/ 1976 Concept DeLorean DMC 12]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_n_oBV2osAg ''The Car's the Star''] \u2013 TV biography of the DMC by former [[Top Gear (1977 TV series)|Top Gear]] host [[Quentin Willson]] (1999, UK)\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Lotus}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Cars|North America}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:DeLorean}}\n[[Category:Cars of Northern Ireland]]\n[[Category:Sports cars]]\n[[Category:Rear-engined vehicles]]\n[[Category:Back to the Future]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 1981]]\n[[Category:Automobiles with gull-wing doors]]\n[[Category:Rear-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:Coup\u00e9s]]\n[[Category:First car made by manufacturer]]\n[[Category:Automobiles with backbone chassis]]\n[[Category:Cars powered by rear-mounted 6-cylinder engines]]\n\n[[ja:\u30c7\u30ed\u30ea\u30a2\u30f3#DMC-12]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{short description|1980s automobile}}\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name = DMC DeLorean\n| image = Delorean DMC-12 side.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = 1983 DeLorean\n| manufacturer = [[DeLorean Motor Company]] (DMC)<br />[[Bloomfield_Hills,_Michigan|Bloomfield Hills]], Michigan, US\n| production = 9,080<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/cars/2015/12/19/delorean-book/77623204/|title=DeLoreans still ply the roads -- and memories|url-status=live}}</ref> (disputed)\n| model_years = 1981\u20131983\n| assembly = DeLorean Motor Cars, Ltd. (DMCL) [[Dunmurry]], [[Belfast]], Northern Ireland\n| designer = [[Giorgetto Giugiaro]] at [[Italdesign]]<ref>https://www.cnn.com/style/article/giorgetto-giugiaro-interview/index.html</ref>\n| class = Sports car\n| body_style = 2-door coup\u00e9\n| related = \n| layout = Rear-engine, rear-wheel-drive<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9|date= 2014 | pages = 15}}</ref>\n| engine = {{convert|2.85|L|cuin|0|abbr=on}} [[V6 PRV engine]] ''ZMJ-159''<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |date= 2014 |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9| pages = 15}}</ref>\n| powerout = {{convert|130|hp|PS kW|0|abbr=on}} and {{convert|207|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} of torque<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |date= 2014 |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9| pages = 15}}</ref>\n| transmission = 5-speed manual<br/>3-speed automatic<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9|date= 2014 | pages = 15}}</ref>\n| wheelbase = {{convert|2413|mm|1|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"autogenerated1946\">{{Cite book|title=Standard Catalog of American Cars 1946\u20131975|publisher= Krause|isbn=0-87341-027-0|editor-last=Gunnell |editor-first= John A.}}</ref>\n| length = {{convert|4267|mm|1|abbr=on}}<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9|date= 2014 | pages = 16}}</ref>\n| width = {{convert|1988|mm|1|abbr=on}}<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9|date= 2014 | pages = 16}}</ref>\n| height = {{convert|1140|mm|1|abbr=on}} doors closed<br/>{{convert|1962|mm|1|abbr=on}} doors open<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9|date = 2014| pages = 16}}</ref>\n| weight = {{convert|1233|kg|0|abbr=on}}<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9 |date= 2014 | pages = 16}}</ref>\n| sp = us\n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| doors = Gullwing doors\n}}\n\nThe '''DMC DeLorean''' (often referred to simply as the \"'''DeLorean'''\", as it was the only model ever produced by the company) is a sports car manufactured by [[John DeLorean]]'s [[DeLorean Motor Company]] (DMC) for the American market from 1981 to 1983. The car was designed by [[Giorgetto Giugiaro]] and stood out for its [[gull-wing door]]s and brushed stainless-steel outer body panels, as well as an innovative fiberglass body structure with a steel backbone chassis. It became widely known for its disappointing lack of power and performance, which did not match the expectations created by its looks and price tag, but it became iconic for its appearances as the [[DeLorean time machine|time machine]] in the [[Back to the Future (franchise)|''Back to the Future'' media franchise]] after 1985.\n\nThroughout production, the car was generally unchanged, although minor modifications were made to such parts as the hood and wheels. The first production car was completed on January 21, 1981. About 9,000 DeLoreans were made before production halted in late December 1982 shortly after DMC had filed for bankruptcy.\n\n==History==\n[[File:DeLorean DMC-12 (9979) (cropped).jpg|thumb|A DeLorean with the gull-wing doors closed]]\n[[File:DeLorean DMC-12 with doors open.jpg|thumb|A DeLorean from the front with the gull-wing doors open]]\nIn October 1976, the first prototype DeLorean was completed by American automotive chief engineer William T. Collins, formerly chief engineer at [[Pontiac]].  Originally, the car was intended to have a centrally-mounted [[Wankel engine|Wankel rotary engine]].  The engine selection was reconsidered when [[Comotor]] production ended, and the favored engine became the [[Ford Cologne V6 engine]].  Eventually the French/Swedish [[fuel injection|fuel-injected]] [[V6 PRV engine]] ([[Peugeot]]-[[Renault]]-[[Volvo]]) was selected.  Also the engine location moved from the mid-engined location in the prototype to a rear-engined installation in the production car.  The [[chassis]] was initially planned to be produced from a new and untested manufacturing technology known as elastic reservoir moulding (ERM), which would lighten the car while presumably lowering its production costs.  This new technology, for which DeLorean had purchased patent rights, was eventually found to be unsuitable.<ref>{{Cite book | title = Stainless Steel Illusion| author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |ISBN=0-9744141-0-7 |date= 2003| pages = 38\u201339}}</ref>\n\nThese and other changes to the original concept led to considerable schedule pressures.  The entire car was deemed to require almost complete re-engineering, which was turned over to engineer [[Colin Chapman]], founder of [[Lotus Cars]].  Chapman replaced most of the unproven material and manufacturing techniques with those then employed by Lotus, like the steel backbone chassis.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{Cite book | title = Stainless Steel Illusion| author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |ISBN=0-9744141-0-7|date= 2003| pages = 71\u201375}}</ref>\n\nThe first prototype appeared in October 1976 and was known as the DSV-1, or DeLorean Safety Vehicle.<ref>{{Cite book | title = Stainless Steel Illusion| author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |ISBN=0-9744141-0-7 |date= 2003| page = 23}}</ref> As development continued, the model was referred to as the DSV-12<ref>{{Cite book | title = Stainless Steel Illusion| author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |ISBN=0-9744141-0-7 |date= 2003| page = 28}}</ref> and later the DMC-12 since DMC was targeting a list price of US$12,000 ({{Inflation|US|12000|1976|fmt=eq|r=-3}}) at release.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.classic-car-history.com/delorean-car.htm |title=DeLorean DMC-12 |access-date=February 3, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190204065904/https://www.classic-car-history.com/delorean-car.htm |archive-date=February 4, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>[https://www.cnbc.com/2016/11/09/how-an-immigrant-mechanic-used-5-million-to-bring-deloreans-back-to-the-future.html How an immigrant mechanic used $5 million to bring DeLoreans back to the future] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190204014534/https://www.cnbc.com/2016/11/09/how-an-immigrant-mechanic-used-5-million-to-bring-deloreans-back-to-the-future.html |date=February 4, 2019 }} Zack Guzman. 3:52 PM ET Wed, November 9, 2016</ref>\n\nIn an interview with James Espey of the new incarnation of the DeLorean Motor Company of [[Texas]], a drawing surfaced showing that the car originally had the potential to be named \"Z Tavio\".  John DeLorean's middle name and his son's first name were both Zachary, while Tavio was his father's name and his son's middle name.  Due to only sporadic documentation, there is little more that is currently known about the Z Tavio name and why it was ultimately rejected in favor of the DeLorean.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.myride.com/content/shared/articles/templates/index.cfm/article_id_int/6244/page/page1/id/27821 |title=Interview with James Espy of DMCH |publisher=Myride.com |date= |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100908094456/http://www.myride.com/content/shared/articles/templates/index.cfm/article_id_int/6244/page/page1/id/27821 |archive-date=September 8, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAfter several delays and cost overruns, production finally began in late 1980. Around this time DMC officially dropped the name DMC-12 on its now US$25,000 ({{Inflation|US|25000|1981|fmt=eq|r=-3}}) car in favor of the model name DeLorean. The DeLorean sports car, as it was described in advertisements, began production in December 1980 with the first production car rolling off the assembly line on January 21, 1981.<ref>{{cite news |author=Lily Rothman |url=http://time.com/4180894/delorean-history/ |title=DeLorean Auto History: What Happened to the Company |publisher=Time |date=January 21, 2016 |accessdate=May 14, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190423164413/http://time.com/4180894/delorean-history/ |archive-date=April 23, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/almanac-the-delorean-car/ |title=Almanac: The DeLorean car |publisher=CBS News |date=January 21, 2018 |accessdate=May 14, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190515122627/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/almanac-the-delorean-car/ |archive-date=May 15, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe DeLorean Motor Company was placed into receivership in February 1982 and filed [[bankruptcy]] in October 1982<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/1982/10/26/business/delorean-motor-files-bankruptcy.html</ref>.  Approximately 100 partially assembled DeLoreans on the production line were completed by [[Big Lots|Consolidated International]].  About 9,000 cars were produced in total.  The remaining parts from the factory stock, the parts from the US Warranty Parts Center, as well as parts from the original suppliers that had not yet been delivered to the factory were all shipped to [[Columbus, Ohio]] in 1983\u201384.  A company called KAPAC sold these parts to retail and [[wholesaling|wholesale]] customers by mail order.  In 1997, DeLorean Motor Company of Texas acquired this inventory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.delorean.com/q&a.asp#whereparts |title=DeLorean Motor Company FAQ |publisher=Delorean.com |date=November 6, 2007 |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101121215155/http://delorean.com/q%26a.asp |archivedate=November 21, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n==Sales and production==\n===Sales===\nPrior to the release of the DeLorean, there was a waiting list of anxious buyers, many of whom paid over [[List_price#Automobiles/motorcars|MSRP]], however that exuberance subsided very quickly and production output soon far exceeded sales volume.  October 1981 was the highest month of sales for DMC with 720 vehicles sold but by December, the US was falling into recession and interest rates were rising which further negatively impacted sales.  Despite this, instead of reducing production, John DeLorean doubled production output, further adding to the backlog of unsold cars.   By the end of 1981, DMC had produced 7,500 cars but had only sold 3,000.  By this point, DMC was in a financial hardship and in February 1982, DMC was placed into receivership. <ref>{{Cite book | title = Stainless Steel Illusion| author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |ISBN=0-9744141-0-7 |date= 2003| pages = 130}}</ref>\n\nIn February 1982, unsold 1981 model year cars were \u201cpriced for immediate clearance\u201d in hopes to make room for the more expensive 1982 model year cars.  In March, telegrams were sent to all 343 dealerships requesting each buy six cars to help save the company;  none of the dealers responded with a sales order.  By this point, dealers were sitting on unsold inventory as were the quality assurance centers and hundreds more sitting on the  docks in [[Long Beach]], California.  By the end of May 1982, production at the factory was shut down.  Another attempt in July 1982 was made to revive sales by offering discounts to dealerships and offering a 5-year/{{convert|50000|mi|adj=on}} warranty with the first year or {{convert|12000|mi|adj=on}} portion secured by a major insurance carrier but this was not successful. \n\nBruce McWilliams, VP of Marketing for DMC and later acting President for DMC America, after resigning his position said, \u201cThe car could never be sold in the numbers John DeLorean predicted\u2026\u201d.<ref>{{Cite book | title = Stainless Steel Illusion| author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |ISBN=0-9744141-0-7 |date= 2003| pages = 133-141}}</ref>\n\n===Production===\nProduction information was lost or scattered upon the [[DeLorean Motor Company#Downturn and bankruptcy|shutdown of DMC]] and production figures for the DeLorean have never been verified based on official factory records.  Despite some unexplained VIN gaps, based upon VIN information, owners have been able to piece together the approximate quantity of DeLoreans produced.\n\nIn February 1982, DMC was placed into [[receivership]] and the factory continued to operate at a reduced production rate until the end of May.  When Consolidated International acquired the unsold and partially assembled cars in November 1982, it brought back workers to complete the cars remaining on the assembly line. It was decided to make the remaining completed 1982 model year cars into 1983 models. The remaining cars VINs were re-VINed into 1983 cars by taking the original VIN number and adding 5000 to it and changing the \"CD\" in the middle of the VIN to \"DD\" thus making a 1983 model.\n\nFor the 1981 model year, there were 6,700 DeLoreans produced (VIN 500-7199).  For the 1982 model year, there were 1,999 DeLoreans produced (VIN 10001-11999).  For the 1983 model year, there were 276 DeLoreans (VIN 17000-17170 and 20001-20105) bringing the total estimated production to 8,975 cars.<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |date= 2014 |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9| pages = 115-117}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2007, about 6,500 DeLorean cars were thought to still exist.<ref>{{cite news |first= Martin |last= Zimmerman |url= https://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-garage28jul28,0,7786124.story?coll=la-home-center |title= For the DeLorean, it's back to the present |accessdate= January 7, 2013 |work= Los Angeles Times |date= July 28, 2007 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20130228154343/http://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-garage28jul28,0,7786124.story?coll=la-home-center |archive-date= February 28, 2013 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\n==Construction==\nThe DeLorean features a number of unusual construction details, including gull-wing doors, unpainted [[stainless-steel]] body panels, and a rear-mounted engine.\n\n===Body===\n[[File:De Lorean DMC-12 at Wollaton Park, Nottingham, England.jpg|thumb|The gull-wing doors on the DeLorean were a distinctive feature.]]\nThe body design of the DeLorean was a product of [[Giorgetto Giugiaro]] of [[Italdesign Giugiaro|Ital Design]] and is panelled in brushed [[AISI steel grades#Stainless steel|SS304]] stainless steel. Except for three cars plated in 24-karat gold, all DeLoreans left the factory uncovered by paint or clearcoat.<ref>{{cite web |first= Knut |last= Grimsrud |url= http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/t_finish.htm |work= DeLorean FAQ |title= Body Finish and Composition from Owners Manual |publisher= Dmcnews.com |date=  |accessdate= December 4, 2010 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110228223225/http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/t_finish.htm |archive-date= February 28, 2011 |url-status= live }}</ref> Painted DeLoreans do exist, although these were all painted after the cars were purchased from the factory.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.aacamuseum.org/delorean-prototype/ |title=DeLorean Prototype & Production |publisher=AACA Museum |date= |accessdate=May 14, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180606022652/https://www.aacamuseum.org/delorean-prototype/ |archive-date=June 6, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> In order to train the workforce, a small number of DeLoreans were produced without the costly stainless steel panels and are referred to as \"black cars\" or [[Development_mule|mules]] in reference to their black fiberglass bodies. These cars were never intended to be sold.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://motor-car.net/delorean/item/10131-dmc-12-technical-1981-82 |title=DeLorean - DeLorean DMC-12 Technical (1981-1982) |publisher=Motor-car.net |date=June 7, 2013 |accessdate=May 14, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190425053807/https://motor-car.net/delorean/item/10131-dmc-12-technical-1981-82 |archive-date=April 25, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nSmall scratches in the stainless-steel body panels can be removed with a non-metallic scouring pad (since metal pads can leave iron particles embedded in the stainless steel, which can give the appearance of the stainless \"rusting\"), or even sandpaper.<ref>{{cite web |first= Knut |last= Grimsrud |url= http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/c_body.htm |work= DeLorean FAQ |title= Care & Feeding: Stainless Steel Body Maintenance |publisher= Dmcnews.com |date=  |accessdate= December 4, 2010 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110515142238/http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/c_body.htm |archive-date= May 15, 2011 |url-status= live }}</ref> The stainless-steel panels are fixed to a [[fiberglass]] underbody. The underbody is affixed to a steel double-Y frame chassis, inspired by the [[Lotus Esprit]] platform.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" />\n\nThe unpainted stainless body creates challenges during [[Automotive restoration|restoration]] of the cars. In traditional automotive body repair, the panel is repaired to be as original (\"straight\") as possible, and imperfections are sculpted back to form with polyester body filler like [[Bondo (putty)|Bondo]] or lead (body [[solder]]). This poses no problem (aside from originality) with most cars, as the filler will be hidden by the car's paint (for example, most new cars have filler hiding the seam where the roof meets the [[quarter panel]]). With an unpainted stainless body, the stainless steel must be reworked to exactly the original shape, contour, and grain, which is a tremendously difficult job on regular steel (a dented or bent panel is stretched, and a shrinking hammer or other techniques must be used to unstretch the metal) and even more difficult with stainless due to its tendency to [[Work hardening|work-harden]]. Furthermore, it is exceedingly difficult to paint stainless steel due to difficulties with paint adhesion. DeLorean envisioned that damaged panels would simply be replaced rather than repaired.\n\nAnother distinctive feature of the DeLorean is its [[gull-wing door]]s. The common problem of supporting the weight of gull-wing doors was solved by other manufacturers with lightweight doors in the [[Mercedes-Benz 300SL]] and a hydraulic pump in the [[Bricklin SV-1]], although these designs had structural or convenience disadvantages. The DeLorean features heavy doors supported by [[Cryogenics|cryogenically]] preset [[Torsion bar suspension|torsion bars]] and gas-charged [[strut]]s.<ref>{{US patent|4,378,658}}</ref> These torsion bars were developed by [[Grumman Aircraft Engineering Corporation|Grumman Aerospace]] (and built by Unbrako in the UK, a division of SPS Technologies of Jenkintown, Pennsylvania, US) to withstand the stresses of supporting the doors.<ref>{{cite web |first= Knut |last= Grimsrud |url= http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/t_tech1.htm |work= DeLorean FAQ |title= Exotic Technology |publisher= Dmcnews.com |date=  |accessdate= December 4, 2010 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110511091013/http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/t_tech1.htm |archive-date= May 11, 2011 |url-status= live }}</ref> Much like the [[scissor doors|doors]] fitted to the [[Lamborghini Countach]], the DeLorean doors featured small cutout windows, because full-sized windows would not be fully retractable within the short door panels. Additionally, the doors featured red and amber \"safety\" lights around the perimeter. These lights illuminated when the door was open and could be seen from the front, rear or side of the vehicle at night or in low-light situations.<ref>{{cite web |first= Knut |last= Grimsrud |url= http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/t_dims.htm |work= DeLorean FAQ |title= Vehicle Dimensions from Technical Manual, Workshop Manual |publisher= Dmcnews.com |date=  |accessdate= December 4, 2010 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20090401070948/http://dmcnews.com/faq/t_dims.htm |archive-date= April 1, 2009 |url-status= live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first= Knut |last= Grimsrud |url= http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/h_doors.htm |work= DeLorean FAQ |title= Historic Information: Door Design |publisher= Dmcnews.com |date=  |accessdate= December 4, 2010 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100914111250/http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/h_doors.htm |archive-date= September 14, 2010 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\n===Engine and drivetrain===\nThe [[engine]] is a [[Peugeot]]-[[Renault]]-[[Volvo]] ([[V6 PRV engine|PRV]]) {{cvt|2.85|L|cuin|0}} [[V6 engine|V6]], rated at {{convert|130|hp|PS kW|0|abbr=on}} @ 5500 rpm and [[torque]] of {{convert|153|lbft|Nm|0|abbr=on}} @ 2750 rpm.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.carfolio.com/specifications/models/car/?car=32725|website=carfolio.com|title=1981 De Lorean DMC-12 specifications|language=en-us|access-date=June 13, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180614071722/https://www.carfolio.com/specifications/models/car/?car=32725|archive-date=June 14, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.automobile-catalog.com/car/1982/587540/de_lorean_dmc-12.html|website=automobile-catalog.com|title=1982 De Lorean DMC-12 specs|language=en-us|access-date=June 13, 2018}}</ref> that was designed and built under special contract with the [[DeLorean Motor Company]]. These PRVs were a development of the 2.7-litre V6 in the [[Renault 30]] and were built in the PRV Factory in [[Douvrin]], Northern France. The 5-speed [[manual transmission]], also designed by PRV, was built at the [[Renault]] facility near [[Caen]] in [[Normandy]]. The engines and [[gearbox]]es were shipped weekly by sea from the PRV factories to the DMC factory.\n\n===Suspension===\nThe [[suspension (vehicle)|suspension]] is a four-wheel [[independent suspension]], [[coil spring]]s, and telescopic [[shock absorbers]]. The front suspension uses [[Double wishbone suspension|double wishbones]], while the rear is a [[Multi-link suspension|multi-link]] setup.\n\nWhen the DeLorean first arrived in the US, the car had a higher than expected wheel gap in the front suspension.  The nose-high appearance is the result of poor quality coil springs.  Despite having significantly less weight in the front, the front and rear springs had the same spring rate and also used lower quality steel which resulted in the nose-high look.<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9 |date= 2014 | pages = 83}}</ref>  Some people have erroneously cited a last minute change in US bumper height requirements led DMC to raise the vehicle just prior to delivery, however this is not true.  Design drawings clearly show that the design met [[National Highway Traffic Safety Administration|NHTSA]] minimum bumper and headlight heights of the time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nhtsa.gov/cars/problems/studies/Bumper/Index.html|title=Bumper Q&A's|publisher=National Highway Traffic and Safety Administration|accessdate=September 17, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111003151011/http://www.nhtsa.gov/cars/problems/studies/bumper/index.html|archive-date=October 3, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nhtsa.gov/cars/rules/rulings/glare.html|title=DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION National Highway Traffic Safety Administration, 49 CFR Part 571, [Docket No. 01-8885; Notice 01], RIN 2127-AH81, Glare from headlamps and other Front Mounted Lamps, Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standard No. 108; Lamps, Reflective Devices, and Associated Equipment|publisher=National Highway Traffic and Safety Administration|accessdate=September 17, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927155258/http://www.nhtsa.gov/cars/rules/rulings/glare.html|archive-date=September 27, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> Many owners have subsequently replaced or modified the front springs to return the front height to the original design specification.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://support.delorean.com/kb/a30/improving-handling-and-lowering-the-delorean.aspx|title=Improving handling and lowering the DeLorean - DeLorean Motor Company|author=|date=|website=support.delorean.com|access-date=June 21, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180621093431/http://support.delorean.com/kb/a30/improving-handling-and-lowering-the-delorean.aspx|archive-date=June 21, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSteering is [[rack and pinion]], with an overall [[steering ratio]] of 14.9:1, giving 2.65 turns lock-to-lock and a {{convert|35|ft|m|adj=on}} turning circle. DeLoreans are fitted with [[alloy|cast alloy]] wheels, measuring {{convert|14|in|mm}} in diameter by {{convert|6|in|mm}} wide on the front and {{convert|15|in|mm}} in diameter by {{convert|8|in|mm}} wide on the rear. These were fitted with [[Goodyear Tire and Rubber Company|Goodyear]] NCT steel-belted radial tires. The DeLorean is a [[Rear-engine, rear-wheel-drive layout|rear-engine vehicle]] with a 35%\u201365% front\u2013rear weight distribution.<ref>{{cite web|first= Knut |last= Grimsrud |url=http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/t_weight.htm |work=DeLorean FAQ |title= Weight and Balance from Technical manual |publisher=Dmcnews.com |date= |accessdate=December 4, 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe DeLorean features power-assisted [[disc brake]]s on all wheels, with {{convert|10|in|mm|adj=on}} rotors front and {{convert|10.5|in|mm|adj=on}} rear.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://oldcarbrochures.org/index.php/NA/DeLorean/1981_DeLorean/1981_Delorean_Brochure/1981-DeLorean-17|title=1981 DeLorean-17|author=|date=|website=oldcarbrochures.org|access-date=May 24, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180524222200/http://oldcarbrochures.org/index.php/NA/DeLorean/1981_DeLorean/1981_Delorean_Brochure/1981-DeLorean-17|archive-date=May 24, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nAt the time of release, the automotive press was generally complimentary towards the DeLorean.  [[Motor Trend]]<ref>{{Cite book | title = DeLorean Stainless Steel Illusion| author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |ISBN=0-9744141-0-7|date= 2003 | pages = 128\u2013129}}</ref>, [[Car and Driver]] <ref>https://www.caranddriver.com/reviews/comparison-test/a15144078/de-lorean-vs-chevy-corvette-datsun-280-zx-ferrari-308gts-porsche-911-comparison-test/</ref> and [[Road_%26_Track|Road & Track]]<ref>https://www.roadandtrack.com/car-culture/classic-cars/reviews/a27099/1982-delorean-dmc-12-road-test/</ref> had mostly positive remarks about the car.  All of them noted disappointing performance, especially those that performed comparative tests against other vehicles but were otherwise impressed with the car noting commendable gas mileage and most of them noting that the DeLorean is more of a [[grand tourer|GT]] car rather than a sports car or racecar.\n\nHowever, more recent reviews of the car have been much more harsh.  In 2017, [[Time Magazine]] included the DeLorean on its list of 50 worst cars of all time.<ref>https://time.com/4723114/50-worst-cars-of-all-time/</ref>  In his book ''Naff Motors: 101 Automotive Lemons'', Tony Davis described the build quality as \"woeful\".  ''Top Gear'' writer Richard Porter included it in his book ''Crap Cars'', calling it \"dismal\",<ref name = \"Porter\">{{cite book|last=Porter |first=Richard |title=Crap Cars |publisher=Bloomsbury |year=2005 |isbn= |page=}}</ref>\n\n==Performance==\nDMC's comparison literature noted that the DeLorean could achieve {{convert|0|\u2013|60|mph|}} in 8.8 seconds, when equipped with a manual transmission. When equipped with an automatic transmission, the DeLorean would accelerate from {{convert|0|to|60|mph|}} in 10.5 seconds as tested by ''Road & Track'' magazine. The car's top speed is {{convert|109|mph|0}}.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.roadandtrack.com/car-culture/classic-cars/reviews/a27099/1982-delorean-dmc-12-road-test/|title=1982 DeLorean DMC-12: The Vintage Road & Track Test|date=October 21, 2015|work=Road & Track|publisher=|access-date=July 23, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170803211950/http://www.roadandtrack.com/car-culture/classic-cars/reviews/a27099/1982-delorean-dmc-12-road-test/|archive-date=August 3, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Road and Track called the car: \".. not quick for a sports/GT car in this price category ..\".\n\n==Problems and issues==\nDeLoreans, early production models in particular, suffered from poor build quality as well as mechanical issues with the vehicle.  Early production cars needed as much as 140-200 hours of work at DMC Quality Assurance Centers prior to being shipped to dealerships for delivery. DMC eventually sent 30 factory workers to the quality centers in the US to learn about the issues and how to fix them.  Quality issues did improve over time and by 1982 many of the quality issues had been resolved.<ref>{{Cite book | title = DeLorean Stainless Steel Illusion| author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |ISBN=0-9744141-0-7|date= 2003 | pages = 83 - 84}}</ref>\n\nA total of four recalls were issued by the factory to correct issues such as a sticking throttle, front suspension issues and an inertia switch. <ref>{{Cite book | title = DeLorean Stainless Steel Illusion| author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |ISBN=0-9744141-0-7|date= 2003 | pages = 108\u2013109}}</ref>\n\nOther quality issues that plagued the car included other issues surrounding the front suspension, clutch pedal adjustment (or lack thereof), brake rotors, instruments; in particular the [[speedometer]], power door locks and weak alternators.  Many early DeLoreans were delivered with an incorrect alignment with the toe-in incorrectly set leading to premature tire wear. \n\nIn addition, many dealers were reluctant to perform warranty work on DeLoreans since DMC owed them money for past warranty claims that were still unpaid.  Some dealerships were not able to perform repair work properly as DMC never issued a proper service manual.  The lack of quality service at dealerships was a point of frustration for many DeLorean owners at the time, particularly those who paid over sticker price to purchase one of the first cars.<ref>{{Cite book | title = DeLorean Stainless Steel Illusion| author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |ISBN=0-9744141-0-7|date= 2003 | pages = 111\u2013112}}</ref>\n\n==Pricing and options==\n[[File:1982 De Lorean DMC12 coupe (8453073488).jpg|thumb|1982 DeLorean grey interior]]\n[[File:1981 DeLorean DMC 12 -- Virginia Museum of Transportation - 49374820477.jpg|thumb|1981 DeLorean with optional accent stripe]]\nUpon release in 1981, a DeLorean had a suggested retail price of US$25,000 ($650 more when equipped with an [[automatic transmission]]); this is equivalent to approximately US${{formatnum:{{inflation|US|25000|1981}}}} in {{inflation-year|US}}.{{inflation-fn|US}}. MSRP would increase in 1982 to $29,825<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nadaguides.com/Cars/1982/delorean/dmc-12-gullwing/2-door-sports-coupe/Values|title=1982 Delorean DMC-12 Gullwing 2 Door Sports Coupe Prices, Values & DMC-12 Gullwing 2 Door Sports Coupe Price Specs|author=|date=|website=NADAguides|access-date=June 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180616231331/https://www.nadaguides.com/Cars/1982/delorean/dmc-12-gullwing/2-door-sports-coupe/Values|archive-date=June 16, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and again in 1983 to $34,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nadaguides.com/Cars/1983/Delorean/DMC-12-Gullwing/2-Door-Sports-Coupe/Values|title=1983 Delorean DMC-12 Gullwing 2 Door Sports Coupe Prices, Values & DMC-12 Gullwing 2 Door Sports Coupe Price Specs|author=|date=|website=NADAguides|access-date=June 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180617015225/https://www.nadaguides.com/Cars/1983/Delorean/DMC-12-Gullwing/2-Door-Sports-Coupe/Values|archive-date=June 17, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> At the outset, there were extensive waiting lists of people willing to pay up to $10,000 above the list price; however, after the collapse of the DeLorean Motor Company, unsold cars could be purchased for less than the retail price.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/h_sales.htm |work=DeLorean FAQ |title= Historic Information: Sales and Dealer Experiences}}</ref>\n\nThe DeLorean was only available with two factory options; a no-cost [[manual transmission]] or automatic transmission and the choice of a grey or black interior (grey interior became available mid 1981 model year).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.deloreanmuseum.org/burgundy-delorean.html |title=one of one! factory burgundy interior delorean |access-date=September 5, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905044903/https://www.deloreanmuseum.org/burgundy-delorean.html |archive-date=September 5, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The standard feature list included stainless-steel body panels; gull-wing doors with cryogenically treated torsion bars; leather seats; [[air conditioning]]; an AM/FM [[Compact Cassette|cassette]] [[stereo system]]; [[power window]]s, [[power door locks|locks]] and [[Power side-view mirror|mirrors]]; a tilt and telescopic [[steering wheel]]; tinted glass; body side moldings; intermittent/constant windshield wipers; and an electric rear-window defogger. Several dealer options were available, including a car cover; [[Sheepskin seat cover|sheepskin]] seat covers; floor mats; car care cleaning kit; black textured accent stripes; grey scotch-cal accent stripes; a luggage rack and a ski-rack adapter.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/d_broc2.htm |work= DeLorean FAQ |title= Dealer Installed Accessories |date= June 20, 1981 |access-date= January 27, 2005 |archive-url= https://www.webcitation.org/6HxeVWMtL?url=http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/d_broc2.htm |archive-date= July 8, 2013 |url-status= live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.delorean-owners.org/legend/specs.html |title= DeLorean Owners Association: DeLorean specifications table |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19980214030500/http://delorean-owners.org/legend/specs.html |archivedate=February 14, 1998}}</ref>\n{{multiple image |align=left |direction=horizontal |total_width=390 | image1=DMC Sticker.jpg |width1=199 |height1=260 |alt1=1982 DMC-12 window sticker |image2=DMC12 clearance.jpg |width2=200 |height2=260 |alt2=DeLorean clearance advertisement |footer_align=center |footer=1982 window sticker & 1983 DeLorean clearance advertisement}}\n{{clear}}\n\n==Production changes==\nAlthough there were no typical yearly updates to the DeLorean, several changes were made to the DeLorean during production.<ref name=\"autogenerated1946\"/>  Instead of making changes at the end of the model year, DMC implemented changes mid-production. This resulted in no clear distinction between the 1981, 1982, and 1983 model years, but with subtle changes taking place almost continuously throughout the life cycle of the DeLorean.\n\n===Hood styles===\nThe original [[hood (vehicle)|hood]] of the DeLorean had [[Groove (machining)|grooves]] running down both sides. It included a tank flap to simplify [[Filling station|fuel filling]]. These cars typically had a locking cap to prevent fuel theft by [[siphon]]ing. In August 1981, the hood flap was removed from the hood of the cars (although the hood creases remained). This style was retained well into 1982.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://babbtechnology.com/thecar/Prod_changes/index.htm |title=The DeLorean |publisher=Babb Technology |date=April 8, 2008 |accessdate=November 6, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304035413/http://babbtechnology.com/thecar/Prod_changes/index.htm |archive-date=March 4, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> Based on production numbers for all three years, this hood style is probably the most common. After the supply of locking caps was exhausted, the company switched to a non-locking version (resulting in at least 500 cars with no flap, but with locking caps). The final styling for the hood included the addition of a DeLorean name badge and the removal of the grooves, resulting in a completely flat hood. According to senior personnel who worked at the Dunmurry factory, initial elimination of flapped hoods has a simple if unglamorous explanation; Chuck Benington, managing director, did not like the design.<ref>{{cite web|title=Nick Sutton, Purchasing Manager, Dunmurry factory|url=http://dmctalk.org/showthread.php?1412-How-DeLoreans-Were-Originally-Built-Stainless-Panel-Discussion&p=20354&viewfull=1#post20354|accessdate=September 17, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402132250/http://dmctalk.org/showthread.php?1412-How-DeLoreans-Were-Originally-Built-Stainless-Panel-Discussion&p=20354&viewfull=1#post20354|archive-date=April 2, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>{{multiple image |align=left |direction=horizontal |total_width=600 |image1=Early 1981 De Lorean hood.jpg |width1=387 |height1=142 |alt1=Early 1981 hood |image2=1983 De Lorean hood.jpg |width2=414 |height2=162 |alt2=1983 hood |footer_align=center |footer=Side-by-side comparison of an early 1981 hood (left) vs. a later model 1983 hood (right)}}\n{{clear}}\n\n===Other changes===\nJohn DeLorean was {{height|ft=6|in=4}} tall, and he designed the car to comfortably fit someone of his stature.<ref>{{Cite news|url= http://www.businessweek.com/articles/2012-04-19/the-deloreans-time-leap|title= The DeLorean's Time Leap|author= Claire Suddath|publisher= [[Bloomberg Businessweek]]|date= April 19, 2012|access-date= July 14, 2014|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140706011419/http://www.businessweek.com/articles/2012-04-19/the-deloreans-time-leap|archive-date= July 6, 2014|url-status= live}}</ref> For shorter people, the addition of a pull strap made closing the doors much easier from the inside. These attach to the existing door handle. Late-model 1981 cars, and all cars from 1982 and 1983, have doors with integrated pull straps.<ref name=\"babbtechnology.com\">{{cite web|url=http://babbtechnology.com/thecar/Prod_changes/index.htm|title=DeLorean \u2013 The Car: Production Changes|work=babbtechnology.com|access-date=August 10, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304035413/http://babbtechnology.com/thecar/Prod_changes/index.htm|archive-date=March 4, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe side [[bolster]]ing in the DeLorean was originally separate from the main interior pieces. In cars with this construction, is a tendency to place pressure on this piece when entering and exiting the vehicle, which eventually causes the bolstering to separate from the trim panel. To solve this problem, cars built in and after late 1981 have one solid trim piece with the bolster permanently attached.<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9|date= 2014 | pages = 38\u201339}}</ref>\n\nAs an addition to later cars, a foot rest, or [[dead pedal]], was added to help prevent [[fatigue (physical)|fatigue]] while driving. This is one of the few changes that is directly tied to a model year. These were built into only a few of the late-1981 vehicles and were added to all cars starting with 1982 production.<ref name=\"babbtechnology.com\"/>\n\nAlthough the styling of the DeLorean's wheels remained unchanged, the wheels of early-model 1981 vehicles were painted grey. These wheels sported matching grey centre caps with an embossed DMC logo. Early into the 1981 production run, these were changed to a polished silver look, with a contrasting black center cap. The embossed logo on the center caps was painted silver to add contrast.<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9|date= 2014 | pages = 25\u201326}}</ref>\n\nIn 1981, the DeLorean came with an AM/FM stereo radio with cassette made by Craig. Since the Craig radio did not have a built-in clock, one was installed in front of the [[gear shift]] on the console. DeLorean switched to an ASI stereo in the middle of the 1982 production run. Since the ASI radio featured an on-board clock, the clock on the console was removed at the same time.<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9|date= 2014 | pages = 44\u201345}}</ref>\n\nThe first 2,200 cars produced used a windshield-embedded [[antenna (radio)|antenna]]. This type of antenna proved to be unsuitable with poor radio reception. Oftentimes the radio would continually \"seek\", attempting to find a signal. A standard whip antenna, which was later changed to a manually retractable antenna, was added to the outside of the front right fender. While improving radio reception, this resulted in a hole in the stainless steel, and an unsightly antenna. As a result, the antenna was again moved. The final antenna was an automatic retractable version installed under the rear induction grill behind the rear driver's-side window.<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9|date= 2014 | pages = 28\u201329}}</ref>\n\nThe small [[visor|sun visors]] on the DeLorean have [[Polyvinyl chloride|vinyl]] on one side and headliner [[Textile|fabric]] on the other side. Originally these were installed such that the headliner side would be on the bottom when not in use. Later on in 1981, they were reversed so that the vinyl side would be on the bottom.<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage |date= 2014 |ISBN=978-0-9856578-1-9| pages = 40}}</ref>\n\nThe original 80 amp Ducellier [[Alternator (auto)|alternator]] supplied with the early-production DeLoreans could not provide enough [[electric current|current]] to supply the car when all lights and electrical options were on; as a result, the [[battery (electricity)|battery]] would gradually discharge, leaving the driver stranded on the road. Beginning with cars built in late 1981, DeLoreans were fitted from the factory with a 90 amp [[Motorola]] alternator, which solved this problem. Additional battery drainage problems were caused by faulty or improperly adjusted door jamb switches. This switch activated the \"safety\" lights located around the door perimeter when it was open. When the door was closed, the door seals prevented the light from being seen. Due to the faulty switches the lights remained on, draining the battery. This happened to DeLorean owner [[Johnny Carson]] shortly after he was presented with the vehicle.\n\n<gallery>\n|align=\n\nFile:De Lorean add-on Pull strap.jpg|Early pull strap\nFile:Delorean dmc-12 later style side bolster.jpg|Later-style one-piece bolster\nFile:mid 1981 De Lorean silver wheel.JPG|Mid-1981 silver wheel\n</gallery>\n\n==Notable and unique DeLoreans==\n===Wooden Mock-up===\n[[File:Ulster Transport Museum, Cultra, DMC-12 Coupe clay model of Italdesign, Moncalieri, Turin for the De Lorean Company, 1975 04.jpg|thumb|DMC-12 Coupe model]]\nIn March 1975, DMC entered into a contract with Ital Design to have Giorgetto Giugiaro design the DeLorean Sports Car.  John DeLorean and Bill Collins approved one of the many designs and subsequently the styling mock-up that was made from \u201cepo-wood\u201d was scheduled to be shipped to the DMC office in Michigan on July 31, 1975.  This mockup would serve as the platform in which the prototype was developed.\n\nThe original full-size epowood DeLorean styling model which was modified in the first quarter of 1979 to reflect the refreshed design used in production, was donated to the [[Ulster Folk and Transport Museum]], in [[Cultra]], [[Northern Ireland]] where it is now on display.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nmni.com/uftm/Collections/Transport-(1)/|title=Ulster Folk and Transport Museum - Online Collections|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n\n===Prototypes and pilot cars===\nOnly one of two DeLorean prototypes still exists.<ref>{{cite web |author=PJ Grady Europe |url=http://www.pjgrady.co.uk/GenericContent.aspx?PageType=Delorean_Repairs&ShowContent=Prototype_Restoration.html |publisher=DeLorean PJ Grady Europe |title=Delorean Repairs |accessdate=January 13, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140421053458/http://www.pjgrady.co.uk/GenericContent.aspx?PageType=Delorean_Repairs&ShowContent=Prototype_Restoration.html |archivedate=April 21, 2014  }}</ref> Prototype 1 sold at the bankruptcy auction in 1984 for $37,000.<ref name=\"upi.com\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1984/11/25/DeLorean-prototype-cars-sell-at-auction-for-total-58000/3565470206800/ |title=DeLorean prototype cars sell at auction for total $58,000 |access-date=June 2, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190602233213/https://www.upi.com/Archives/1984/11/25/DeLorean-prototype-cars-sell-at-auction-for-total-58000/3565470206800/ |archive-date=June 2, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>  The car remained in a private collection until 2005 when it was sold to the owner of DeLorean Motor Company of Florida (DMCFL) where it received a complete restoration.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.liveauctioneers.com/item/4041986_1587-1976-delorean-dmc-12-original-prototype |title=1587: 1976 DeLorean DMC-12 Original Prototype |access-date=June 2, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190602234250/https://www.liveauctioneers.com/item/4041986_1587-1976-delorean-dmc-12-original-prototype |archive-date=June 2, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Proto 1 is now on display at DMCFL. Proto 2 was sent to [[Lotus Cars]] for development and evaluation in 1978. It was reported to have been destroyed in the 1990s.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Car |url=http://www.deloreanmuseum.org/car.html |website=The Delorean Museum |publisher=The Delorean Museum |accessdate=October 7, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151006112343/http://www.deloreanmuseum.org/car.html |archivedate=October 6, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nAn estimated 28 pilot cars were built by DMC. The pilot cars are best identified by the subtly different interiors and sliding side windows. These cars, used for evaluation and regulatory testing of the DeLorean, were previously thought to have been destroyed. Subsequently, several of the pilot cars were found to have survived.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dmctalk.org/showthread.php?1167-Earliest-known-Pilot-car-found-photographed |title=Earliest known Pilot car found/photographed |publisher=Dmctalk.org |date=November 5, 1955 |accessdate=January 13, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140114132601/http://dmctalk.org/showthread.php?1167-Earliest-known-Pilot-car-found-photographed |archive-date=January 14, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=PJ Grady Europe |url=http://www.pjgrady.co.uk/GenericContent.aspx?PageType=Pilot_Chronology&ShowContent=Pilot_Cars.html |title=Pilot Chronology |publisher=Pjgrady.co.uk |date=November 24, 1980 |accessdate=January 13, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140421051421/http://www.pjgrady.co.uk/GenericContent.aspx?PageType=Pilot_Chronology&ShowContent=Pilot_Cars.html |archivedate=April 21, 2014  }}</ref> Pilot car 25 which was featured on the front cover of [[Autocar (magazine)|Autocar]] in 1981 was found in 2003 in a barn in Northern Ireland.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pjgrady.co.uk/pilot-25 |title=pilot-25 |access-date=September 5, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905040305/https://www.pjgrady.co.uk/pilot-25 |archive-date=September 5, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Visioneering car===\nWith the 1980 [[National Automobile Dealers Association|NADA]] meeting approaching, DMC planned to show a final \u201cproduction\u201d version of the DeLorean, however there were no production cars ready at the time or even any production stainless steel panels.\n\nEarlier, in the summer of 1979, the revised Giugiaro styling mock-up was shipped to Visioneering, a [[Detroit]] based company, to create data needed to make the stamping dies for the stainless panels. This project would expand to create dies used to create a \u201cproduction\u201d car for the NADA show.\n\nUsing a prototype chassis supplied by Lotus in late 1979, Visioneering completed the assembly of this car at a cost of $750,000. The car was presented at the 1980 NADA show and was later used for engineering development and technical training as well as press photos. The Visioneering car would eventually be sold at the bankruptcy auction in late 1984 for $21,000.<ref name=\"upi.com\"/> Today, the car is in a private collection.<ref>{{Cite book | title = The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | author=James Espey| publisher = DeLorean Garage| ISBN = 978-0-9856578-1-9 |date= 2012 | page = 108}}</ref>\n\n===Legend turbo cars===\nIt was determined that the DeLorean needed additional power when automotive magazine road tests showed {{convert|0|\u2013|60|mph|abbr=on}} times for the DeLorean between 9.5 and 10.5 seconds, while its rivals were in the 7.5\u20138.5 second range. There had been interest in [[turbocharger|turbocharging]] the DeLorean early on, but the DMC engineering staff was busy with other projects, so DeLorean decided to go outside to develop a turbocharged version of the DeLorean.<ref name=\"Stainless Steel Illusion\">{{Cite book | title = Stainless Steel Illusion | isbn=0-9744141-0-7 | author=John Lamm| publisher = Red Lion Press |date= 2003 | pages = 110\u2013111}}</ref>\n\nHaving had previous success with turbocharging [[Fiat 124 Sport Spider|Fiat Spiders]], DeLorean entered into a contract with Legend Industries, based in [[Hauppauge, New York|Hauppauge]], [[New York (state)|New York]]. DMC wanted to increase power without sacrificing fuel efficiency. DMC wanted a wide power band and did not want a surge of power similar to the [[Porsche 930]] Turbo. Legend used twin [[IHI Corporation|IHI]] RHB52 turbos along with twin [[intercooler]]s. The results were an engine capable of accelerating smoothly in fifth gear from 1,500&nbsp;rpm to full turbo boost at 2,500&nbsp;rpm, reaching {{convert|150|mph|abbr=on}} at 6,500&nbsp;rpm.<ref name=\"Stainless Steel Illusion\" />\n[[File:Legend engine.jpg|thumb|Legend Twin Turbo setup from VIN 530]]\n\nIn addition, Legend Industries developed a single turbocharged setup that was never finished.\nThe company converted a total of four DeLoreans and two Renault Alpines, which were the first development cars.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pjgrady.co.uk/#!vin-530/cjd7|title=Delorean Car Sales Europe UK. Canvey Island Essex SS8 OPQ|publisher=|access-date=February 18, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130513040331/http://www.pjgrady.co.uk/#!vin-530/cjd7|archive-date=May 13, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> [[VIN]] 530 was written in numerous press articles as the fastest production car of its era.\n\nIn a test run of VIN 530 at [[Bridgehampton Race Circuit|Bridgehampton Raceway]] in 1981, the twin-turbo DeLorean was quicker than a [[Ferrari 308 GTB/GTS|Ferrari 308]] and a [[Porsche 928]]. It has been a misconception for many years that VIN 502 was at Bridgehampton and used in testing; however, evidence from pictures, along with information from a Legend employee published by PJ Grady, indicates that 530 was used along with VIN 558.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pjgrady.co.uk/identifying-the-legend-cars |title=identifying-the-legend-cars |access-date=September 5, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905041236/https://www.pjgrady.co.uk/identifying-the-legend-cars |archive-date=September 5, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> By the time of Bridgehampton, Legend had perfected modular boosting, which the earlier prototypes did not have installed apart from one of the Alpine mules and VIN 530.<ref>{{cite web | title=DeLorean DMC-12 | website=Silodrome | date=March 3, 2018 | url=https://silodrome.com/delorean-dmc-12-buying-guide/ | access-date=September 5, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905042552/https://silodrome.com/delorean-dmc-12-buying-guide/ | archive-date=September 5, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nVIN 530 tested 0\u201360&nbsp;mph in 5.8 seconds and the [[Dragstrip|{{convert|1/4|mi|m|0}}]] in 14.7 seconds. John DeLorean was so impressed with the engine, he committed to ordering 5,000 engines from Legend Industries. DMC planned to offer a turbocharged engine as a $7,500 option in 1984 (presumably to compete with the newly redesigned [[Chevrolet Corvette (C4)|1984 Corvette]]). Before any of the 5,000 cars could be put into production, DMC had declared bankruptcy, which drove Legend Industries, as well as other suppliers, into bankruptcy.<ref name=\"DeLorean Gold Portfolio\">{{Cite book | title = DeLorean Gold Portfolio | author=R. M. Clarke| publisher = Brookland Books LTD. |ISBN=1-85520-331-6 |date= 1996 | pages = 137\u2013143}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" Style=\"text-align:center\"\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n|-\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n!\tVIN\t!!\tConfiguration\t!!\tLast known location\t!!\tComments\n|-\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n|\t502\t||\tTwin\t||\tNew Zealand\t||\tOriginal prototype\n|-\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n|\t528\t||\tSingle\t||\tNew York\t||\t\n|-\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n|\t530\t||\tTwin\t||\tUnited Kingdom\t||\tSister twin-turbo\n|-\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n|\t558\t||\tSingle\t||\tUnknown\t||\t\n|}\n\n===Gold-plated===\n[[File:gold-D.jpg|thumb|A gold-plated DeLorean in Reno, Nevada]]\nFor Christmas 1980, a DeLorean/[[American Express]] promotion planned to sell 100 [[Karat|24K]]-[[Gilding|gold-plated]] DeLoreans for US$85,000 each to its gold-card members, but only two were sold.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.caranddriver.com/in-1980-you-could-buy-an-85000-24k-gold-plated-delorean/|title=In 1980, You Could Buy an $85,000, 24K-Gold-Plated DeLorean|publisher=|access-date=September 4, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160920152935/http://blog.caranddriver.com/in-1980-you-could-buy-an-85000-24k-gold-plated-delorean/|archive-date=September 20, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> One of these was purchased by Roger Mize, president of Snyder National Bank in [[Snyder, Texas]]. VIN #4301 sat in the bank lobby for over 20 years before being loaned to the [[Petersen Automotive Museum]] in [[Los Angeles]]. It has a black interior and an automatic transmission.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigtexas.com/dmc/ |title=The 24-Karat Gold Plated DeLorean Car |publisher=Bigtexas.com |accessdate=January 22, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120224111825/http://www.bigtexas.com/dmc/ |archivedate=February 24, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nThe second gold-plated American Express DeLorean was purchased by Sherwood Marshall, an entrepreneur and former [[Royal Canadian Navy|Royal Canadian Naval]] Officer. Marshall donated his DeLorean to the [[William F. Harrah]] Foundation/[[National Automobile Museum]] in [[Reno, Nevada]]. This car, VIN #4300, is equipped with a manual transmission and a saddle-brown interior.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.automuseum.org |title=National Automobile Museum |publisher=National Automobile Museum |date= |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101207005657/http://www.automuseum.org/ |archive-date=December 7, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nA third gold-plated car exists that was assembled with spare parts that were required by American Express in case one of the other two that were built were damaged. All necessary gold-plated parts were on hand, with the exception of one door that was sourced later.<ref name=bigtexas>{{cite web|url=http://bigtexas.com/dmc/gold/ |title=Gold DeLorean for sale in LaVale, Maryland |publisher=Bigtexas.com |date= |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110812111029/http://bigtexas.com/dmc/gold/|archivedate=August 12, 2011 }}</ref> The car was first acquired by the winner of a [[Big Lots]] store raffle. Consolidated International, which owned the department store, had purchased 1374 DeLoreans during the DeLorean Motor Company's financial troubles, acquiring the remaining stock after the company went into receivership. It was listed for sale online at a price of US$250,000,<ref name=bigtexas/> but it is unclear whether it ever sold.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bigtexas.com/dmc/gold/ |title=Delorean for sale in LaVale, Maryland |publisher=Archive.is |accessdate=January 13, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120524094241/http://bigtexas.com/dmc/gold/ |archivedate=May 24, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nA gold-plated DeLorean was reproduced privately by an enthusiast.<ref>{{cite web |author= |url=http://mycarquest.com/2013/02/gold-plated-deloreans-yes-there-were-four.html |title=Gold Plated DeLoreans? \u2013 Yes There Were Four |publisher=Mycarquest.com |date=February 21, 2013 |accessdate=January 13, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140421051720/http://mycarquest.com/2013/02/gold-plated-deloreans-yes-there-were-four.html |archive-date=April 21, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Right-hand-drive models===\nDeLoreans were primarily intended for the American market. All production models were therefore [[left-hand-drive]]. DeLorean Motor Company was aware as early as April 1981 of the need to produce a [[right-hand-drive]] (RHD) version to supply to world markets, specifically the United Kingdom.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pjgrady.co.uk/woller-hodec |title=woller-hodec |access-date=September 5, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905043041/https://www.pjgrady.co.uk/woller-hodec |archive-date=September 5, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe company faced the choice of building right-hand-drive models from scratch or performing a post-production conversion exercise. Given the cost of new body molds, tooling, and a host of specific parts that a factory-built right-hand-drive configuration would require, the company opted to investigate the idea of a post-production conversion using a UK company based in [[Hampshire]] called Wooler-Hodec Ltd.<ref>{{cite book | last=Narus | first=D. | title=Independent Sports Cars | publisher=Lulu.com | year=2017 | isbn=978-1-387-15601-6 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HolUDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA48 | access-date=August 30, 2019 | page=48}}</ref>{{self-published inline|date=February 2020}}\n\n[[File:De Lorean DMC12 - Flickr - foshie (1).jpg|thumb|RHD DeLorean]]\nOnly 16 right-hand-drive factory-authorized DeLoreans were ever produced.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deloreans.co.uk/rhd-euro/index.html |title=DeLorean: Euro Spec DeLoreans |publisher=Deloreans.co.uk |accessdate=May 4, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100617185502/http://www.deloreans.co.uk/rhd-euro/index.html |archivedate=June 17, 2010 }}</ref> These cars can be divided into two distinct groups:\n# The first batch, known by enthusiasts as the \"Wooler-Hodec cars\", were converted by the UK company of that name. Evidence still exists in the form of a DMC factory memo, which orders 20 cars to be converted to right-hand drive.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://docs.wixstatic.com/ugd/3d11d1_78b371c4af664be7ba130b81c1ddd557.pdf |title=DMC Inter-Office Memo: RHD Conversion Programme |access-date=September 5, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905045408/https://docs.wixstatic.com/ugd/3d11d1_78b371c4af664be7ba130b81c1ddd557.pdf |archive-date=September 5, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Due to the factory's closure, this order was never completed, and today a total of 13 cars survive, carrying the VINs 510, 12171\u201312181 and 12199.\n# The second batch were registered and used by the factory in Northern Ireland, with registration numbers (license plates), AXI 1697, AXI 1698, AXI 1699 and are referred to by enthusiasts as the \"AXI cars\". These three cars (VINs 5565, 5592 and 5638) differ from the first Wooler-Hodec cars in several ways. They all had roof-mounted radio antennas, indicator repeater lights, no side marker lights, white forward-facing door lights, fog-light switch, and textured body rubstrips on the stainless panels. No [[catalytic converters]] or [[Oxygen sensor|lambda equipment]] were fitted, as British legislation did not require them. \n\nOwners who bought these cars at auction in the early 1980s encountered difficulty in registering them as new vehicles in the UK. At this point a former DeLorean Motor Cars executive offered to modify and register the cars so that they could be used in the UK. These modifications included:\n* Different seat-belt units fitted.<ref name=\"foglight\">{{cite web|url=http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/fogswitch01.jpg |publisher=DeLorean Owners Club UK |title=Reference image illustrating modified seat belt unit in right-hand drive car |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724223213/http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/fogswitch01.jpg |archivedate=July 24, 2011 }}</ref>\n* The fitting of Rubbolite tail light clusters with a built-in fog light function.<ref name=\"rubberlight\">{{cite web|url=http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/rubberlight02.jpg |publisher=DeLorean Owners Club UK |title=Reference image illustrating so-called \"Euro-spec\" tail light unit |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724223141/http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/rubberlight02.jpg |archivedate=July 24, 2011 }}</ref>\n* The fitting of a fog light switch to one of the center-console dummy switches.<ref name=\"foglight\"/>\n* A custom-made tail light surround and number (license) plate bezel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/rubberlight01.jpg |publisher=DeLorean Owners Club UK |title=Reference image illustrating custom fabricated tail light and number (license) plate bezel fitted on an official right-hand drive car |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724223225/http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/rubberlight01.jpg |archivedate=July 24, 2011 }}</ref>\n* Swapping the front turn signal lenses for ones of a different, more rounded style.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/frontrepeater02.jpg |publisher=DeLorean Owners Club UK |title=Reference image illustrating rounded turn signal lens on an official right-hand drive car |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110712013912/http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/frontrepeater02.jpg |archivedate=July 12, 2011 }}</ref>\n* Swapping the rear side marker lenses for amber ones.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/rearmarker01.jpg |publisher=DeLorean Owners Club UK |title=Reference image illustrating amber rear side marker lens fitted on an official right-hand drive car |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724223301/http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/rearmarker01.jpg |archivedate=July 24, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nAll of the 13 Wooler-Hodec cars were modified to the OEM front turn-signal lens fixing method in order to make them fit flush with the front fascia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/frontrepeater01.jpg |publisher=DeLorean Owners Club UK |title=Reference image illustrating modified front turn signal lens |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110712013859/http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/frontrepeater01.jpg |archivedate=July 12, 2011 }}</ref> The cars' headlights were also changed for right-hand-drive spec lights that incorporate a UK sidelight feature. \n\n\nBy contrast, the three AXI cars had further modifications to the amber front door lights, which were exchanged for clear lenses of the same style.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/whitedoorlight01.jpg |publisher=DeLorean Owners Club UK |title=Reference image illustrating clear door light lens |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724223348/http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/whitedoorlight01.jpg |archivedate=July 24, 2011 }}</ref> Perhaps the most significant alteration on the AXI cars is the deletion of the front and rear side markers. These are replaced by a single small round European-style indicator side repeater, situated on the front wing (fender). The body rubstrips are also of a different configuration in order to cover the areas that would otherwise have had federal side marker lenses fitted.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/flasherrepeater02.jpg |publisher=DeLorean Owners Club UK |title=Reference image illustrating modified rubstrips and single round marker light |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724223415/http://www.deloreans.co.uk/features/eurospec/big_pics/flasherrepeater02.jpg |archivedate=July 24, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n===''Back to the Future''===\n{{Main|DeLorean time machine}}\n[[File:'81-'82 DeLorean DMC-12.jpg|thumb|A DeLorean \"time machine\" from the ''Back to the Future'' trilogy exhibited at [[Universal Studios Florida]]]]\nSeveral special-edition DeLorean cars have been produced over the years, and the car is most notably featured as the time machine in the [[Back to the Future (franchise)|''Back to the Future'' film trilogy]]. Six DeLorean chassis were used during the production, along with one manufactured out of fiberglass for scenes where a full-size DeLorean was needed to \"fly\" on-screen; only three of the cars still exist, with one that was destroyed at the end of ''[[Back to the Future Part III]]'', two additional cars were abandoned, and the fiberglass replica was scrapped. Universal Studios owns two of the remaining cars, occasionally putting them on display or using them for other productions, and the last resides in a private collection after having been extensively restored.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bttf3delorean.com/Where_are_they.html |title=BTTF3 DeLorean: Where Are They? |date= |accessdate=January 1, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111005125859/http://bttf3delorean.com/Where_are_they.html |archive-date=October 5, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> The official ''[[Back to the Future]]'' DeLorean can be viewed at the [[Petersen Automotive Museum]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://petersen.org/backtothefuture/ |title=Petersen Automotive Museum |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160320133259/http://petersen.org/backtothefuture/ |archivedate=March 20, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nA number of production DeLoreans have been modified by the [[Automotive aftermarket|aftermarket]] into ''Back to the Future'' time machine replicas, whose bodies and interiors are modified to mirror the appearance and functions of the film cars.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bobspropshop.com/bttf.html|title=Bob's Prop Shop|work=bobspropshop.com|access-date=November 13, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141016005640/http://www.bobspropshop.com/bttf.html|archive-date=October 16, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==DMC Texas==\n[[File:\" 12 - ITALY (Milan) Electro Vehicles Europe ( EVE ) DeLorean DMC-12.JPG|thumb|[[Electric car|All-electric model]] DMCev in Milan (2012)]]\nIn 1995, Stephen Wynne from Liverpool created a separate company based in Texas using the [[DeLorean Motor Company (Texas)|DeLorean Motor Company]] name. Wynne acquired the trademark on the stylized DMC logo, along with the remaining parts inventory of the original DeLorean Motor Company. The company rebuilds cars at its [[Humble, Texas]], location using a combination of [[new old stock]] (NOS) parts, original equipment manufacturer (OEM), and reproduction parts on a made-to-order basis.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.delorean.com/index-5.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718103728/http://www.delorean.com/index-5.html|archivedate=July 18, 2011|title=New build cars|publisher=DeLorean Motor Company|accessdate=May 26, 2010}}</ref>\n\nDMC Texas (based in [[Humble, Texas]]) announced on July 30, 2007, that the car would be returning into very limited production (about 20 cars a year) in 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-garage28jul28,1,6560463.story |title=For the DeLorean, it's back to the present |work=LA Times |date=July 28, 2007 |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110310115947/http://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-garage28jul28,1,6560463.story |archive-date=March 10, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> They were subsequently sued by John DeLorean's widow for illegally licensing the family name. DMC Texas settled this lawsuit in September 2015 by paying his widow an undisclosed sum and in turn received rights to use the name, images, and trademark in the future.<ref>{{cite web|title = Lawyers Settle DeLorean Lawsuit Just in Time for 'Back to the Future' Day|url = https://blogs.wsj.com/law/2015/10/21/lawyers-settle-delorean-lawsuit-just-in-time-for-back-to-the-future-day/|website = WSJ Blogs \u2013 Law Blog|date = October 21, 2015|accessdate = December 26, 2015|first = Jacob|last = Gershman|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20151222085854/http://blogs.wsj.com/law/2015/10/21/lawyers-settle-delorean-lawsuit-just-in-time-for-back-to-the-future-day/|archive-date = December 22, 2015|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nThe cars were announced to have a new stainless-steel frame; with optional extras such as GPS, an enhanced \"Stage 2\" engine, and possibly a new modern interior. Given that the cars were made with 80% old parts,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,293814,00.html |title=Texas Entrepreneur Set to Start Building DeLorean Cars |publisher=Fox News |date=August 21, 2007 |accessdate=December 4, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130511132411/http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,293814,00.html |archive-date=May 11, 2013 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> the term \"return to production\" is something of a misnomer; the cars are constructed on DeLorean underbodies built by the original company in the 1980s and retaining their VINs. The cars' titles show the year of the underbody's manufacture. Therefore, they are not new DeLoreans, but complete rebuilds of the car from the underbody with enhancements. In 2009, the price of a refurbished DeLorean from DMC Texas started at US$57,500, and the project was featured in an episode of ''[[Modern Marvels]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.motorauthority.com/news/1040516_anything-but-rusty-reviewing-the-delorean-in-2009/page-2|title=Anything But Rusty: Reviewing The DeLorean In 2009|first=Ryan|last=McCaffrey|publisher=Motor Authority|date=December 20, 2009|accessdate=November 6, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222115538/http://www.motorauthority.com/news/1040516_anything-but-rusty-reviewing-the-delorean-in-2009/page-2|archive-date=December 22, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn October 18, 2011, it was announced that an all-electric model would be available for sale by 2013. It was said to have a {{Convert|200|hp|0|abbr=on|adj=on}} motor, accelerate from {{Convert|0|to|60|mph|abbr=on|km/h}} in 8 seconds, and sell for US$90,000.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.foxnews.com/leisure/2011/10/18/electric-delorean-coming-in-2013/ |title=Electric DeLorean Coming in 2013 |work=Fox News |date=October 18, 2011 |accessdate=October 28, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111029024300/http://www.foxnews.com/leisure/2011/10/18/electric-delorean-coming-in-2013/ |archivedate=October 29, 2011  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://automotivediscovery.com/the-new-2013-delorean-ev-gets-some-test-runs-by-enthusiasts/9210689/ |title=The New DeLorean EV Gets Some Test Runs by Enthusiasts |work=Automotive Discovery |date=October 26, 2011 |accessdate=October 28, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141026195129/http://automotivediscovery.com/the-new-2013-delorean-ev-gets-some-test-runs-by-enthusiasts/9210689/ |archive-date=October 26, 2014 |url-status=dead  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/eco-nomics/2011/10/19/back-to-the-future-all-electric-delorean-coming-in-2013/ |title=Back To The Future: All Electric DeLorean Coming in 2013 |work=Forbes |date=October 19, 2011 |accessdate=October 28, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111101212905/http://www.forbes.com/sites/eco-nomics/2011/10/19/back-to-the-future-all-electric-delorean-coming-in-2013/ |archive-date=November 1, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> Initial test drives revealed that the prototype had a range of {{Convert|70|mi|km}}, approaching the {{Convert|100|mi|km}} that was announced.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jalopnik.com/5850448/electric-delorean-first-drive|title=Electric DeLorean: First Drive|first=Kevin|last=McCauley|publisher=Jalopnik|date=October 17, 2011|accessdate=November 6, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151025045755/http://jalopnik.com/5850448/electric-delorean-first-drive|archive-date=October 25, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> However, 2014 saw criticism from fans who tried to buy the electric DeLorean only to learn that it was still unavailable.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cardebater.com/it-seems-delorean-has-gone-back-to-the-past-again/|title=It Seems DeLorean Has Gone Back To The Past Again|first=Wes|last=Lungwitz|publisher=Car Debater|date=February 14, 2014|accessdate=November 6, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106215825/http://www.cardebater.com/it-seems-delorean-has-gone-back-to-the-past-again/|archive-date=November 6, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDue to the passage of the [[Low Volume Motor Vehicle Manufacturers Act of 2015|Low Volume Vehicle Manufacturing Act]], DMC Texas announced that it would be producing replica DeLoreans with an expected release date in 2017. DMC anticipated building approximately 50 vehicles per year over six years with an estimated retail price of US$100,000.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://jalopnik.com/the-delorean-is-coming-back-thanks-to-this-new-law-1755528406 |title=The DeLorean Is Coming Back Thanks To This New Law, Will Have 300-400 HP |first=Jason |last=Torchinsky |publisher= |access-date=January 21, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190830195816/https://jalopnik.com/the-delorean-is-coming-back-thanks-to-this-new-law-1755528406 |archive-date=August 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.roadandtrack.com/car-culture/classic-cars/news/a28016/new-delorean-replicas-coming/ |title=Brand-New DeLorean Replicas Are on the Way |date=January 27, 2016 |publisher= |access-date=January 21, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190914085258/https://www.roadandtrack.com/car-culture/classic-cars/news/a28016/new-delorean-replicas-coming/ |archive-date=September 14, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In October 2016, DMC announced that it was expecting to build 12 units in the first production year with as many as 50 in the second year of production.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newdelorean.com/blog/ |title=DMC Blog - DeLorean - The New DMC DeLorean |publisher= |access-date=December 18, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160827145747/http://www.newdelorean.com/blog/ |archive-date=August 27, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>   In December 2019, the NHTSA issued guidelines for the Low Volume Vehicle Manufacturing Act<ref>https://www.nhtsa.gov/sites/nhtsa.dot.gov/files/documents/replica_vehicle_program_nprm_12172019.pdf</ref> and DMC Texas is now projecting they will begin production in 2021.<ref>https://www.autoblog.com/2020/01/24/delorean-motor-company-dmc-12-new-cars/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}<!-- Dead note \"production2\": [http://www.dmcnews.com/faq/img/news/n_vinrat.pdf DMC-12 Estimated Production Volumes by Month] (PDF) by Knut Grimsrud -->\n<!-- Dead note \"production3\": [http://www.delorean-owners.org/legend/index.html DMC - The legend - DeLorean: Stainless Style] -->\n<!-- Dead note \"production3\": [http://www.delorean.hu/ - Delorean Club Hungary- DeLorean: Stainless Style] -->\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book |first1= John Z. |last1= DeLorean |first2= Ted |last2= Schwarz |title= DeLorean |location= Grand Rapids, MI |publisher= Zondervan |year= 1985 |isbn= 0-310-37940-7 |url-access= registration |url= https://archive.org/details/delorean00delo }}\n* {{cite book |first= John |last= Lamm |title= DeLorean Stainless Steel Illusion |edition= 2nd |year= 2003 |location= Fort Jones, CA |publisher= Red Lion Press |isbn= 0-9744141-0-7}}\n* {{cite book |first= R. M. |last= Clarke |title= DeLorean: 1977\u20131995 Gold Portfolio |year= 1995 |location= Cobham |publisher= Brooklands |isbn= 1-85520-331-6}}\n* {{cite book |first= James |last= Espey |title= The Illustrated Buyer's Guide to DeLorean Automobiles | edition= 2nd |year= 2014 |publisher= the DeLorean Garage |isbn= 978-0-9856578-1-9}}\n* {{cite book |first= Chris | last= Parnham |first2= Andrew | last2= Withers |title= DeLorean Celebrating the Impossible |year= 2015| location = | publisher= DeLorean Motor Cars (1978) Ltd.| isbn= 978-0-9928594-0-4}}\n* {{cite book |first= Chris |last= Williams|title= DeLorean DMC-12 [sic], The Essential Buyers Guide (2018) |year=2018 | location= |publisher= Veloce Publishing| isbn= 978-1-787112-32-2}}\n\n==External links==\n<!--======================== {{No more links}} ============================\n | PLEASE BE CAUTIOUS IN ADDING MORE LINKS TO THIS ARTICLE. Wikipedia |\n | is not a collection of links nor should it be used for advertising. |\n | |\n | Excessive or inappropriate links WILL BE DELETED. |\n | See [[Wikipedia:External links]] & [[Wikipedia:Spam]] for details. |\n | |\n | If there are already plentiful links, please propose additions or |\n | replacements on this article's discussion page, or submit your link |\n | to the relevant category at the Open Directory Project (dmoz.org) |\n | and link back to that category using the {{dmoz}} template. |\n==={{No more links}}=========-->\n\n{{Commons category|DeLorean DMC-12}}\n* [http://www.delorean.com/ DeLorean Motor Company]\n* {{curlie|Recreation/Autos/Makes_and_Models/DeLorean/|DeLorean}