{"title_page": "Earlham College", "text_new": "{{Primary sources|date=November 2019}}{{Infobox university\n| name = Earlham College\n| image = Earlham College Seal.png\n| motto = ''Vita Lux Hominum'' (Life is the Light of Man)\n| established = 1847\n| type = [[private university|Private]] [[coeducational]] [[liberal arts college]]\n| religious_affiliation = [[Quakers]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://quakerfahe.com/quaker-colleges-universities-and-study-centers/|title=Quaker Colleges, Universities & Study Centers|date=25 June 2012|publisher=|accessdate=20 February 2018}}</ref>\n| endowment = $438 million (2018)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2018/08/01/earlham-college-seeks-roll-back-expense-budget-decade-after-presidents-resignation|title=Earlham College seeks to roll back expense budget by a decade after president's resignation|website=insidehighered.com|date=1 August 2018|accessdate=28 February 2020}}</ref>\n| president = Anne M. Houtman\n| students = 1,019\n| city = [[Richmond, Indiana|Richmond]]\n| state = [[Indiana]]\n| country = United States\n| coor = {{coord|39|49|28.44|N|84|54|47.78|W|display=title}}\n| campus = Rural, {{convert|800|acre|km2}}\n| colors = Maroon and White<ref>{{cite manual|url=http://www.earlham.edu/styleguide/Earlham_Brand_Guide.pdf |title=Earlham Brand Guidelines |accessdate=2016-09-11}}</ref><br/>{{color box|#861F41}}&nbsp;{{color box|#FFFFFF}}\n| sporting_affiliations = [[NCAA Division III]] \u2013 [[Heartland Collegiate Athletic Conference|HCAC]]\n| nickname = [[#Athletics|Quakers]]\n| mascot = Big Earl\n| website = {{URL|https://www.earlham.edu}}\n| logo = Earlham College wordmark.svg\n| logo_size = 250px\n}}\n'''Earlham College''' is a private [[Liberal arts colleges in the United States|liberal arts college]] in [[Richmond, Indiana]]. The college was established in 1847 by the [[Religious Society of Friends]] (Quakers) and has a strong focus on Quaker values such as integrity, a commitment to peace and social justice, mutual respect, and community decision-making. It is primarily a residential undergraduate college but it offers a [[Master of Arts in Teaching]] and has an affiliated graduate seminary, the [[Earlham School of Religion]], which offers three master's degrees: a [[Master of Divinity]], Master of Ministry, and [[Master of Arts in Religion]].\n\n==History==\nEarlham was founded in 1847 as a boarding high school for the religious education of Quaker adolescents.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.earlham.edu/about/history|title=A Brief History of Earlham College|publisher=Earlham.edu|accessdate=2011-11-12}}</ref> In 1859, Earlham became Earlham College, upon the addition of collegiate academics. At this time, Earlham was the third Quaker college in the [[United States]] ([[Haverford College]] was first, [[Guilford College]] the second), and the second U.S. institution of higher education to be coeducational ([[Oberlin College]] was first). Though the college initially only admitted students who belonged to the Religious Society of Friends, Earlham began admitting non-Quakers in 1865. The college was named for [[Earlham Hall]], home of the [[Joseph John Gurney|Gurneys]], an important English Quaker family.\n\nOver time, as Quakerism in America became more progressive, Earlham's practices changed with them, though the college has remained faithful to its Quaker roots. In 1942 Earlham enrolled several dozen Japanese-American students to prevent their [[Japanese American internment|internment]] during [[World War II]], a decision that was very controversial in Richmond. 1960 marked the establishment of the [[Earlham School of Religion]], then the only Friends [[seminary]] in the world.\n\nEarlham College has been facing declining revenues for years.<ref name=\"pal-item.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pal-item.com/story/news/local/2018/08/09/amid-financial-strains-earlham-banks-100-million-campus-updates/885145002/|title=Amid financial strains, Earlham puts $100 million into campus updates|website=Pal-Item}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pal-item.com/story/news/local/2018/07/29/earlham-faces-big-questions-deficit-ahead-new-school-year/828182002/|title=Earlham College faces big deficit, questions ahead of new school year|website=Pal-Item}}</ref><ref name=\"pal-item.com\"/>\n\n==Campus==\nEarlham's {{convert|800|acre|km2|adj=on}} campus lies at the southwestern edge of [[Richmond, Indiana]], a city of 36,812 (2010 census). The main quadrangle of the campus is called \"the Heart\".  It is surrounded by Earlham Hall (with the Runyan Center student union directly behind it), Olvey-Andis Hall, Lilly Library, Carpenter Hall, Landrum Bolling Center, the science buildings (Stanley Hall, Noyes Hall and Dennis Hall), Tyler Hall, Bundy Hall and Barrett Hall. Ninety-four percent of Earlham students live on campus in a variety of settings.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.earlham.edu/about/collegiate-profile|publisher=Earlham.edu|title=About|accessdate=2011-11-12}}</ref> The campus includes eight residence halls (Barrett Hall, Bundy Hall, Earlham Hall, Mills Hall, Hoerner Hall, Olvey-Andis Hall, Warren Hall and Wilson Hall)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.earlham.edu/~sas/reslife/reshalls.html|title=Residence Halls |publisher=Earlham.edu |accessdate=2010-01-18}}</ref> and 28 theme and friendship houses, which border the North and East edges of the campus.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.earlham.edu/~sas/reslife/houses/themehouses.html|title=Theme Houses|publisher=Earlham.edu|accessdate=2010-01-18}}</ref> [[U.S. Route 40 in Indiana|U.S. Route 40]] runs along the edge of the campus.\n\n[[File:Earlham Cupola.jpg|thumb|250px|left| Carpenter Hall at Earlham College]] The [[Joseph Moore Museum]] is a [[natural history museum]] located on campus and run by students and biology [[Academic department|department]] faculty, focusing on [[Indiana]]'s natural history. It is open to the public (free of charge) and [[Tour guide|tours]] are available upon request. Since 2015, themed ecotours were founded and visitors can register for these outings to the school's properties of natural areas led by biology students for interpretation. The majority of Earlham College's campus is undeveloped [[forest]] and [[meadow]], including the undeveloped \"back campus\" area, which serves as an outdoor [[classroom]]. The Biology Department also maintains and manages wildman woods a short drive from the campus which is also used for field work and class field trips.\n\nThe school has embarked on major campus improvement projects which cost a combined $62.3 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.earlham.edu/facilities/construction-projects/ |publisher=Earlham.edu|title=Construction Projects|accessdate=2013-02-10}}</ref> The science complex (Stanley and Noyes Halls) has undergone a complete renovation. Stanley Hall was completed by fall 2013 and received a LEED Silver certification and a new Center for Science and Technology was completed in 2015 and is expected to obtain a LEED gold rating.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.earlham.edu/sustainability/across-the-campus/green-buildings/ |publisher=Earlham.edu|title=Sustainability - Green Buildings|accessdate=2016-10-20}}</ref> Tyler Hall, originally built thanks to an [[Andrew Carnegie]] Grant, fell into a mild state of disrepair over the last several decades{{when|date=February 2016}} and has been renovated to a LEED Silver standard. Tyler Hall now houses Earlham's Admissions department. A new [[Fine Arts|fine arts]] building was constructed and opened in August 2014 and obtained a LEED gold certification. A new [[baseball]] stadium was completed (fall 2013), and major renovations to the [[American football|football]] field were completed prior to the 2012 season.\n\nEarlham College has been singled out in the [[National Wildlife Federation]]'s national report card on sustainability in higher education as having exemplary programs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pressroom.earlham.edu/articles/2008/08/earlham-recognized-national-campus-sustainability-report|title=Earlham Recognized in National Campus Sustainability Report|publisher=Pressroom.earlham.edu|accessdate=2010-01-18}}{{Dead link|date=August 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Earlham's Environmental Plan (approved 2005) is an assessment of how Earlham impacts the environment, what steps have been or can be taken to reduce impacts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.earlham.edu/%7epres/content/planning.html|title=Planning at Earlham|publisher=Earlham.edu|accessdate=2010-01-18}}</ref>\n\n==Curriculum and community==\n{{Infobox US university ranking\n<!-- U.S. rankings -->\n<!-- | ARWU_NU  = ? -->\n| USNWR_LA = 68\n| Forbes   = 132\n| Wamo_LA  = 62 \n}}\nIn keeping with [[Quaker|Friends]]' belief in equality, everyone addresses each other at Earlham by his or her first name, without the use of titles such as \"doctor\" or \"professor\"; likewise, \"freshmen\" are referred to as \"first year (students)\".\n\nRoughly 70% of Earlham students go on a semester-length [[study abroad|off-campus program]] to such destinations as [[Mexico]], the U.S./ Mexican border, [[Vienna]], [[Martinique]], [[Northern Ireland]], [[Great Britain]], [[France]], [[Germany]], [[Spain]], [[New Zealand]], [[Japan]] and [[Tanzania]].<ref name=\"earlham.edu\">{{cite web|title=Collegiate Profile |url=http://www.earlham.edu/about/collegiate-profile|publisher=Earlham College|accessdate=26 January 2012}}</ref> This high rate is possible because a student's [[Student financial aid (United States)|financial aid]] helps to offset the full cost of one semester on any Earlham-approved program. In addition, there are a number of shorter off-campus May terms, with destinations both within the U.S. and abroad ([[Australia]], [[Galapagos]], [[Senegal]], [[Menorca]], and [[Turkey]], as recent examples). Earlham has an exchange program with [[Waseda University]] in [[Japan]], which has existed since 1963. In addition, Earlham College offers the [[SICE]] program<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.earlham.edu/curriculumguide/offcampus/programs.html|title=Earlham College - A national liberal arts college in the Midwest|publisher=|accessdate=21 December 2014}}</ref> in [[Morioka, Japan|Morioka]], Japan, a program in which about twelve to fourteen students teach [[English language|English]] in [[middle school]]s in [[Morioka]]. Students prepare for these programs by studying German, Spanish, Arabic, Japanese, French and Chinese which are offered on campus during the school year. Tibetan, Creole, and Kiswalli have been offered during some of these off campus programs.\n\nIn the sciences, Earlham places a large emphasis on integrating research into the undergraduate curriculum. Through Ford/Knight grants, most science faculty have been or are currently involved with students in research.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.earlham.edu/curriculum-guide/elective-opportunities/studentfaculty-research|title=Student/Faculty Research|accessdate=2011-11-13}}</ref> Earlham has good representation in the [[Butler University|Butler]] Undergraduate Research Conference, held each year in the spring.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.butler.edu/media/1196327/program2011_rev.pdf|title=2011 Butler Undergraduate Research Conference Schedule|access-date=2011-11-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120406090728/http://www.butler.edu/media/1196327/program2011_rev.pdf|archive-date=2012-04-06|url-status=dead}}</ref> The [[pre-medicine]] program is particularly distinguished, in that over the last ten years all but one of its graduates have been accepted into medical school. Earlham's biology and chemistry departments have a long history of producing distinguished graduates, such as [[Warder Clyde Allee]], [[Jim Fowler]], [[Larry E. Overman]], [[Harold Urey]], and [[Wendell Stanley]], the latter two of which won the [[Nobel Prize in Chemistry]] (in 1934 and 1946, respectively). Students and Faculty in Earlham's CS applied groups jointly provide computer infrastructure support for the college.\n\nThe [[choir]] department organizes regional and national tours every year for its ensembles. In January 2012, the concert choir performed in [[Indianapolis]], the [[Cathedral Basilica of St. Louis]], and [[Chicago]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.earlham.edu/music/midwest-choir-tour|title=Midwest Choir Tour|publisher=Earlham.edu|accessdate=2012-09-30}}</ref> The choral and instrumental music departments collaborate on a biennial basis, performing works such as [[Carmina Burana (Orff)|Carmina Burana]] and [[Michael Tippett|Michael Tippett's]] [[A Child of Our Time]]. The College has a full [[Gamelan]] ensemble, which performs concerts in the Spring.<ref>{{cite web|title=Instrumental Music|url=http://www.earlham.edu/music/instrumental-music|publisher=Earlham College|accessdate=26 January 2012}}</ref> Earlham has an entirely student-managed public [[radio station]], [[WECI]] 91.5FM. In addition, 6-10 theater performances occur throughout the year on campus through either the academic department, senior projects or the student company.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.weciradio.org/ |title=WECI 91.5FM Richmond Public Radio |publisher=Weciradio.org |date=2010-04-12 |accessdate=2010-09-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://earlham.edu/theatre-arts/|title=Theatre Arts, Academics - Earlham College|website=earlham.edu|accessdate=20 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nEarlham has students from 77 countries, the most out of any liberal arts college in the United States. This equates to roughly 200 students, which is the highest total number of international students for any co-educational liberal arts college in the country. This high diversity is due in part to a strong relationship with the [[United World College]] network of international boarding high schools. Since 2004, Earlham College has been a part of the Davis United World Scholars program, which offers need-based scholarships for UWC graduates to continue their education at select institutions in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.earlham.edu/alumni/whats-happening/news/?id=13468&r=3867|title=Earlham Joins Worldwide 50th Anniversary Celebration for United World Colleges|publisher=earlham.edu|accessdate=2013-02-17}}</ref> The Davis Cup, which is awarded to the college with the most current students from this program, has been awarded to Earlham several times. The college also draws from all regions of the United States, with students from 42 states. Domestic minorities represent 15% of the student body.<ref name=\"earlham.edu\"/>\n\nEarlham is orienting some of the curriculum around exploring local and global problems as well as possible solutions.  In 2016, Earlham students won the million dollar [[Hult Prize]] for their \"Magic Bus\" proposal to help with transportation problems in developing urban environments.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2016/09/26/495466938/a-million-dollars-goes-to-an-app-that-leads-to-a-better-bus-commute |title=$1 Million Goes To An App That Leads To A Better Bus Commute |first=Angus |last=Chen |publisher=[[NPR]] |date=September 26, 2016 |accessdate=October 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\nEarlham has the United States' only [[equestrianism|Equestrian]] program which is run entirely by students. Lessons are available for students of the college and community members. The equestrian center is adjacent to the college owned 11 acre Miller farm which hosts agricultural interns during the school year and summer and \"work days\" on Saturdays for the rest of the community during the school year. Miller farm also serves as a residence for upper class students.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://legacy.earlham.edu/equestrianprogram/content/coop.html|title=Co-Operative Program|publisher=Earlham.edu|accessdate=2012-09-30}}</ref>\n\nIn keeping with Quaker tradition, Earlham students voluntarily invest many hours of community service into the Richmond community. Students report an average of 23,000 hours of volunteering work every year and Earlham's Bonner program offers financial aid in exchange for volunteering work for students with high financial need.<ref name=\"earlham.edu\"/>\n\nEarlham College is a member of the [[Great Lakes Colleges Association]].\n\n== Adjacent institutions ==\nThere are two institutions located adjacent to the Earlham College undergraduate campus: [[Earlham School of Religion]], a Quaker theological graduate school, and [[Bethany Theological Seminary]], an independent [[Church of the Brethren]] institution offering graduate and non-degree programs. Earlham College students can take courses at these institutions (which share facilities with the college).\n\nWhile Earlham is predominately an undergraduate institution, it also offers a Master of Arts in Teaching degree.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://earlham.edu/master-of-arts-in-teaching/|title=Master of Arts in Teaching |publisher=earlham.edu|accessdate=2016-10-20}}</ref>\n\n==Athletics==\nEarlham competes in NCAA Division III and in the [[Heartland Collegiate Athletic Conference]]. The women's sports are basketball, cross country, field hockey, golf, indoor track, outdoor track, soccer, tennis, and volleyball. The men's sports are baseball, basketball, cross country, football, golf, indoor track, outdoor track, soccer, and tennis.<ref name=ath>{{cite web |url=http://www.earlham.edu/~awpe/ |title=Athletics|publisher=Earlham.edu|accessdate=2010-01-18}}</ref>\n\nThe football team was organized in 1888 and been playing games since the 1889 season. As one of the earliest college programs, Earlham has competed against larger foes such as Indiana University, Purdue University, the University of Kentucky, Ball State University, and Butler University. Perhaps the Quakers' most notable football game was an exhibition game against Japan's Doshisha University Hamburgers in 1989.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/09/10/style/campus-life-earlham-week-s-lessons-extend-beyond-football-practice.html?scp=1&sq=Earlham%20Hamburgers&st=cse|title=Week's Lessons Extend Beyond Football Practice|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=September 10, 1989|page=151|accessdate=2010-01-18|url-access=registration }}</ref> The Earlham football team has not won a football game since October 26, 2013, the longest [[losing streak]] in NCAA Division III history at 53 games. In November 2018, the school chose to cancel the program for the remainder of the 2018 season and all of 2019.<ref>[https://www.southbendtribune.com/sports/college/earlham-college-suspends-football-program-after-straight-losses/article_a0180472-5b89-599e-b518-678bd26bc94b.html Earlham College suspends football program after 53 straight losses]</ref> The team was featured on ESPN in 2016 <ref> https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TItx9CNv7jc]</ref>\n\nThe baseball team won its first HCAC Conference title in 2017.\n\n[[National Basketball Association|NBA]] coach [[Del Harris]] was the head coach at Earlham for 9 years (1965-1974).  He twice led the Quakers to a Top 10 ranking in the NAIA final poll and won a school-record 175 games and three Hoosier Collegiate Conference championships.  He led them to the NAIA National Tournament in 1971 with a record of 24-5.\n\nEarlham was an NAIA member in all sports until 19xx; they won the NAIA Men's Soccer National title in 1963.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.naia.org/fls/27900/1NAIA/SportsInfo/Championships/MSOC_Championship.pdf?SPSID=646079&SPID=100398&DB_LANG=C&DB_OEM_ID=27900 |title=MSOC Championship |website=www.naia.org |access-date=2019-05-15}}</ref>\nIn the 2010\u201311 season, the Earlham College Men's Tennis team became the first squad in Earlham history to qualify for the NCAA Div. III Championships by winning the Heartland Collegiate Athletic Conference Tournament title.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://goearlham.com/index.aspx?path=mten |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-01-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110911054011/http://www.goearlham.com/index.aspx?path=mten |archive-date=2011-09-11 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Since the 2011 conference championship, the men's tennis team has won the conference title in 2012 and 2013. In February 2013 the men's tennis team earned its first national ranking in NCAA Division III athletics at no. 30, the first Earlham team to do so since 1999 when the men's soccer team was ranked no. 16.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goearlham.com/news/2013/2/28/MTEN_0228135006.aspx|title=Earlham College Athletics|work=Earlham College|accessdate=21 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141221201457/http://www.goearlham.com/news/2013/2/28/MTEN_0228135006.aspx|archive-date=21 December 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nEarlham's club teams include Ultimate Frisbee, Women's and Men's rugby, the Bike Co-Op, Cheerleaders, Earthquakers (Competitive Dance), Equestrian Program, [[martial arts]] groups, Men's Volleyball, and Outdoors Club.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.earlham.edu/handbook/student/content/wellness/club.html|title=Student Handbook - Club Sports|publisher=Earlham.edu|accessdate=2010-01-18}}</ref> A $13-million Athletics and Wellness Center opened at the beginning of the Fall 1999 semester. Students are not charged to use the facility, which features an energy center for cardiovascular and strength training, a group fitness studio for aerobics and yoga, Weber Pool (25 meters by six lanes), racquetball courts, tennis courts, a running track, a climbing wall and Schuckman Court (a performance gymnasium with seating for 1,800).<ref name=ath/> In 2007, Earlham opened its new 2,000 seat Darrell Beane Stadium, with a football field and running track.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.earlham.edu/~awpe/content/sports/men/football/beane_stadium.html|title=Darrell Beane Stadium|publisher=Earlham.edu|accessdate=2010-01-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070610022517/http://www.earlham.edu/%7Eawpe/content/sports/men/football/beane_stadium.html|archive-date=2007-06-10|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Wilderness programs==\nEarlham was one of the first colleges in the country to initiate student and faculty-led wilderness programs, back in 1970.<ref>Earlham College Wilderness Program Instructors Manual, 1975, by Douglas Steeples, Phil Shore, Alan Kesselheim, Henry Merrill \"and others\", edited by Phil Shore and Alan Kesselheim</ref> These programs were designed for incoming first-year and transfer students who received credit for them. The program is divided into the Water August Wilderness and the Mountain August Wilderness and lasts for approximately three weeks; the former canoes in [[Wabakimi Provincial Park]] in Ontario and the latter hikes in the Uinta Mountains in Utah. Students have taken ice climbing, dog sledding, caving, white water kayaking, rock climbing, trail construction and canoeing courses for credit. The program in the past has led spring break canoeing trips to  [[Big Bend National Park]] in southwestern [[Texas]], a semester course to  New Zealand and a  May Term (a condensed three-week term after the spring semester) instructor training  course for its August Wilderness program. Challenge/experiential education courses on the college's own high and low ropes is offered as well as the chance to be certified as a Wilderness First Responders in an intensive spring break course where students must complete mock rescues. In the past students have also had the opportunity to rappel off the College's three-story science building.\n\n==Notable people==\n{{main|List of Earlham College people}}\n\n*[[Michael Shellenberger]]\n*[[Michael C. Hall]]\n*[[Eva Feldman]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Hamm, Thomas D. ''Earlham College: A History, 1847-1997''. Bloomington: Indiana University Press, 1997. {{ISBN|9780253332561}}.\n* Kashatus, William C. ''Beyond the Touchlines: A History of Earlham Men's Soccer''. Richmond, IN:  Earlham College, 2017.\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.earlham.edu/}}\n* [http://www.goearlham.com/landing/index Earlham Athletics website]\n\n{{Navboxes\n|titlestyle = {{CollegePrimaryStyle|Earlham Quakers|color=white}}\n|list =\n{{GLCA}}\n{{Annapolis Group}}\n{{Oberlin Group}}\n{{CLAC}}\n{{Heartland Collegiate Athletic Conference navbox}}\n{{Indiana Colleges and Universities}}\n{{Global Liberal Arts Alliance}}\n}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Earlham College|*]]\n[[Category:Quaker universities and colleges]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Richmond, Indiana]]\n[[Category:Members of the Annapolis Group]]\n[[Category:Members of the Oberlin Group]]\n[[Category:Education in Richmond, Indiana]]\n[[Category:1847 establishments in Indiana]]\n", "text_old": "{{Primary sources|date=November 2019}}{{Infobox university\n| name = Earlham College\n| image = Earlham College Seal.png\n| motto = ''Vita Lux Hominum'' (Life is the Light of Man)\n| established = 1847\n| type = [[private university|Private]] [[coeducational]] [[liberal arts college]]\n| religious_affiliation = [[Quakers]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://quakerfahe.com/quaker-colleges-universities-and-study-centers/|title=Quaker Colleges, Universities & Study Centers|date=25 June 2012|publisher=|accessdate=20 February 2018}}</ref>\n| endowment = $438 million (2018)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2018/08/01/earlham-college-seeks-roll-back-expense-budget-decade-after-presidents-resignation|title=Earlham College seeks to roll back expense budget by a decade after president's resignation|website=insidehighered.com|date=1 August 2018|accessdate=28 February 2020}}</ref>\n| president = Anne M. Houtman\n| students = 1,019\n| city = [[Richmond, Indiana|Richmond]]\n| state = [[Indiana]]\n| country = United States\n| coor = {{coord|39|49|28.44|N|84|54|47.78|W|display=title}}\n| campus = Rural, {{convert|800|acre|km2}}\n| colors = Maroon and White<ref>{{cite manual|url=http://www.earlham.edu/styleguide/Earlham_Brand_Guide.pdf |title=Earlham Brand Guidelines |accessdate=2016-09-11}}</ref><br/>{{color box|#861F41}}&nbsp;{{color box|#FFFFFF}}\n| sporting_affiliations = [[NCAA Division III]] \u2013 [[Heartland Collegiate Athletic Conference|HCAC]]\n| nickname = [[#Athletics|Quakers]]\n| mascot = Big Earl\n| website = {{URL|https://www.earlham.edu}}\n| logo = Earlham College wordmark.svg\n| logo_size = 250px\n}}\n'''Earlham College''' is a private [[Liberal arts colleges in the United States|liberal arts college]] in [[Richmond, Indiana]]. The college was established in 1847 by the [[Religious Society of Friends]] (Quakers) and has a strong focus on Quaker values such as integrity, a commitment to peace and social justice, mutual respect, and community decision-making. It is primarily a residential undergraduate college but it offers a [[Master of Arts in Teaching]] and has an affiliated graduate seminary, the [[Earlham School of Religion]], which offers three master's degrees: a [[Master of Divinity]], Master of Ministry, and [[Master of Arts in Religion]].\n\n==History==\nEarlham was founded in 1847 as a boarding high school for the religious education of Quaker adolescents.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.earlham.edu/about/history|title=A Brief History of Earlham College|publisher=Earlham.edu|accessdate=2011-11-12}}</ref> In 1859, Earlham became Earlham College, upon the addition of collegiate academics. At this time, Earlham was the third Quaker college in the [[United States]] ([[Haverford College]] was first, [[Guilford College]] the second), and the second U.S. institution of higher education to be coeducational ([[Oberlin College]] was first). Though the college initially only admitted students who belonged to the Religious Society of Friends, Earlham began admitting non-Quakers in 1865. The college was named for [[Earlham Hall]], home of the [[Joseph John Gurney|Gurneys]], an important English Quaker family.\n\nOver time, as Quakerism in America became more progressive, Earlham's practices changed with them, though the college has remained faithful to its Quaker roots. In 1942 Earlham enrolled several dozen Japanese-American students to prevent their [[Japanese American internment|internment]] during [[World War II]], a decision that was very controversial in Richmond. 1960 marked the establishment of the [[Earlham School of Religion]], then the only Friends [[seminary]] in the world.\n\nEarlham College has been facing declining revenues for years.<ref name=\"pal-item.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pal-item.com/story/news/local/2018/08/09/amid-financial-strains-earlham-banks-100-million-campus-updates/885145002/|title=Amid financial strains, Earlham puts $100 million into campus updates|website=Pal-Item}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pal-item.com/story/news/local/2018/07/29/earlham-faces-big-questions-deficit-ahead-new-school-year/828182002/|title=Earlham College faces big deficit, questions ahead of new school year|website=Pal-Item}}</ref><ref name=\"pal-item.com\"/>\n\n==Campus==\nEarlham's {{convert|800|acre|km2|adj=on}} campus lies at the southwestern edge of [[Richmond, Indiana]], a city of 36,812 (2010 census). The main quadrangle of the campus is called \"the Heart\".  It is surrounded by Earlham Hall (with the Runyan Center student union directly behind it), Olvey-Andis Hall, Lilly Library, Carpenter Hall, Landrum Bolling Center, the science buildings (Stanley Hall, Noyes Hall and Dennis Hall), Tyler Hall, Bundy Hall and Barrett Hall. Ninety-four percent of Earlham students live on campus in a variety of settings.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.earlham.edu/about/collegiate-profile|publisher=Earlham.edu|title=About|accessdate=2011-11-12}}</ref> The campus includes eight residence halls (Barrett Hall, Bundy Hall, Earlham Hall, Mills Hall, Hoerner Hall, Olvey-Andis Hall, Warren Hall and Wilson Hall)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.earlham.edu/~sas/reslife/reshalls.html|title=Residence Halls |publisher=Earlham.edu |accessdate=2010-01-18}}</ref> and 28 theme and friendship houses, which border the North and East edges of the campus.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.earlham.edu/~sas/reslife/houses/themehouses.html|title=Theme Houses|publisher=Earlham.edu|accessdate=2010-01-18}}</ref> [[U.S. Route 40 in Indiana|U.S. Route 40]] runs along the edge of the campus.\n\n[[File:Earlham Cupola.jpg|thumb|250px|left| Carpenter Hall at Earlham College]] The [[Joseph Moore Museum]] is a [[natural history museum]] located on campus and run by students and biology [[Academic department|department]] faculty, focusing on [[Indiana]]'s natural history. It is open to the public (free of charge) and [[Tour guide|tours]] are available upon request. Since 2015, themed ecotours were founded and visitors can register for these outings to the school's properties of natural areas led by biology students for interpretation. The majority of Earlham College's campus is undeveloped [[forest]] and [[meadow]], including the undeveloped \"back campus\" area, which serves as an outdoor [[classroom]]. The Biology Department also maintains and manages wildman woods a short drive from the campus which is also used for field work and class field trips.\n\nThe school has embarked on major campus improvement projects which cost a combined $62.3 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.earlham.edu/facilities/construction-projects/ |publisher=Earlham.edu|title=Construction Projects|accessdate=2013-02-10}}</ref> The science complex (Stanley and Noyes Halls) has undergone a complete renovation. Stanley Hall was completed by fall 2013 and received a LEED Silver certification and a new Center for Science and Technology was completed in 2015 and is expected to obtain a LEED gold rating.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.earlham.edu/sustainability/across-the-campus/green-buildings/ |publisher=Earlham.edu|title=Sustainability - Green Buildings|accessdate=2016-10-20}}</ref> Tyler Hall, originally built thanks to an [[Andrew Carnegie]] Grant, fell into a mild state of disrepair over the last several decades{{when|date=February 2016}} and has been renovated to a LEED Silver standard. Tyler Hall now houses Earlham's Admissions department. A new [[Fine Arts|fine arts]] building was constructed and opened in August 2014 and obtained a LEED gold certification. A new [[baseball]] stadium was completed (fall 2013), and major renovations to the [[American football|football]] field were completed prior to the 2012 season.\n\nEarlham College has been singled out in the [[National Wildlife Federation]]'s national report card on sustainability in higher education as having exemplary programs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pressroom.earlham.edu/articles/2008/08/earlham-recognized-national-campus-sustainability-report|title=Earlham Recognized in National Campus Sustainability Report|publisher=Pressroom.earlham.edu|accessdate=2010-01-18}}{{Dead link|date=August 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Earlham's Environmental Plan (approved 2005) is an assessment of how Earlham impacts the environment, what steps have been or can be taken to reduce impacts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.earlham.edu/%7epres/content/planning.html|title=Planning at Earlham|publisher=Earlham.edu|accessdate=2010-01-18}}</ref>\n\n==Curriculum and community==\n{{Infobox US university ranking\n<!-- U.S. rankings -->\n<!-- | ARWU_NU  = ? -->\n| USNWR_LA = 68\n| Forbes   = 132\n| Wamo_LA  = 62 \n}}\nIn keeping with [[Quaker|Friends]]' belief in equality, everyone addresses each other at Earlham by his or her first name, without the use of titles such as \"doctor\" or \"professor\"; likewise, \"freshmen\" are referred to as \"first year (students)\".\n\nRoughly 70% of Earlham students go on a semester-length [[study abroad|off-campus program]] to such destinations as [[Mexico]], the U.S./ Mexican border, [[Vienna]], [[Martinique]], [[Northern Ireland]], [[Great Britain]], [[France]], [[Germany]], [[Spain]], [[New Zealand]], [[Japan]] and [[Tanzania]].<ref name=\"earlham.edu\">{{cite web|title=Collegiate Profile |url=http://www.earlham.edu/about/collegiate-profile|publisher=Earlham College|accessdate=26 January 2012}}</ref> This high rate is possible because a student's [[Student financial aid (United States)|financial aid]] helps to offset the full cost of one semester on any Earlham-approved program. In addition, there are a number of shorter off-campus May terms, with destinations both within the U.S. and abroad ([[Australia]], [[Galapagos]], [[Senegal]], [[Menorca]], and [[Turkey]], as recent examples). Earlham has an exchange program with [[Waseda University]] in [[Japan]], which has existed since 1963. In addition, Earlham College offers the [[SICE]] program<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.earlham.edu/curriculumguide/offcampus/programs.html|title=Earlham College - A national liberal arts college in the Midwest|publisher=|accessdate=21 December 2014}}</ref> in [[Morioka, Japan|Morioka]], Japan, a program in which about twelve to fourteen students teach [[English language|English]] in [[middle school]]s in [[Morioka]]. Students prepare for these programs by studying German, Spanish, Arabic, Japanese, French and Chinese which are offered on campus during the school year. Tibetan, Creole, and Kiswalli have been offered during some of these off campus programs.\n\nIn the sciences, Earlham places a large emphasis on integrating research into the undergraduate curriculum. Through Ford/Knight grants, most science faculty have been or are currently involved with students in research.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.earlham.edu/curriculum-guide/elective-opportunities/studentfaculty-research|title=Student/Faculty Research|accessdate=2011-11-13}}</ref> Earlham has good representation in the [[Butler University|Butler]] Undergraduate Research Conference, held each year in the spring.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.butler.edu/media/1196327/program2011_rev.pdf|title=2011 Butler Undergraduate Research Conference Schedule|access-date=2011-11-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120406090728/http://www.butler.edu/media/1196327/program2011_rev.pdf|archive-date=2012-04-06|url-status=dead}}</ref> The [[pre-medicine]] program is particularly distinguished, in that over the last ten years all but one of its graduates have been accepted into medical school. Earlham's biology and chemistry departments have a long history of producing distinguished graduates, such as [[Warder Clyde Allee]], [[Jim Fowler]], [[Larry E. Overman]], [[Harold Urey]], and [[Wendell Stanley]], the latter two of which won the [[Nobel Prize in Chemistry]] (in 1934 and 1946, respectively). Students and Faculty in Earlham's CS applied groups jointly provide computer infrastructure support for the college.\n\nThe [[choir]] department organizes regional and national tours every year for its ensembles. In January 2012, the concert choir performed in [[Indianapolis]], the [[Cathedral Basilica of St. Louis]], and [[Chicago]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.earlham.edu/music/midwest-choir-tour|title=Midwest Choir Tour|publisher=Earlham.edu|accessdate=2012-09-30}}</ref> The choral and instrumental music departments collaborate on a biennial basis, performing works such as [[Carmina Burana (Orff)|Carmina Burana]] and [[Michael Tippett|Michael Tippett's]] [[A Child of Our Time]]. The College has a full [[Gamelan]] ensemble, which performs concerts in the Spring.<ref>{{cite web|title=Instrumental Music|url=http://www.earlham.edu/music/instrumental-music|publisher=Earlham College|accessdate=26 January 2012}}</ref> Earlham has an entirely student-managed public [[radio station]], [[WECI]] 91.5FM. In addition, 6-10 theater performances occur throughout the year on campus through either the academic department, senior projects or the student company.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.weciradio.org/ |title=WECI 91.5FM Richmond Public Radio |publisher=Weciradio.org |date=2010-04-12 |accessdate=2010-09-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://earlham.edu/theatre-arts/|title=Theatre Arts, Academics - Earlham College|website=earlham.edu|accessdate=20 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nEarlham has students from 77 countries, the most out of any liberal arts college in the United States. This equates to roughly 200 students, which is the highest total number of international students for any co-educational liberal arts college in the country. This high diversity is due in part to a strong relationship with the [[United World College]] network of international boarding high schools. Since 2004, Earlham College has been a part of the Davis United World Scholars program, which offers need-based scholarships for UWC graduates to continue their education at select institutions in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.earlham.edu/alumni/whats-happening/news/?id=13468&r=3867|title=Earlham Joins Worldwide 50th Anniversary Celebration for United World Colleges|publisher=earlham.edu|accessdate=2013-02-17}}</ref> The Davis Cup, which is awarded to the college with the most current students from this program, has been awarded to Earlham several times. The college also draws from all regions of the United States, with students from 42 states. Domestic minorities represent 15% of the student body.<ref name=\"earlham.edu\"/>\n\nEarlham is orienting some of the curriculum around exploring local and global problems as well as possible solutions.  In 2016, Earlham students won the million dollar [[Hult Prize]] for their \"Magic Bus\" proposal to help with transportation problems in developing urban environments.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2016/09/26/495466938/a-million-dollars-goes-to-an-app-that-leads-to-a-better-bus-commute |title=$1 Million Goes To An App That Leads To A Better Bus Commute |first=Angus |last=Chen |publisher=[[NPR]] |date=September 26, 2016 |accessdate=October 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\nEarlham has the United States' only [[equestrianism|Equestrian]] program which is run entirely by students. Lessons are available for students of the college and community members. The equestrian center is adjacent to the college owned 11 acre Miller farm which hosts agricultural interns during the school year and summer and \"work days\" on Saturdays for the rest of the community during the school year. Miller farm also serves as a residence for upper class students.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://legacy.earlham.edu/equestrianprogram/content/coop.html|title=Co-Operative Program|publisher=Earlham.edu|accessdate=2012-09-30}}</ref>\n\nIn keeping with Quaker tradition, Earlham students voluntarily invest many hours of community service into the Richmond community. Students report an average of 23,000 hours of volunteering work every year and Earlham's Bonner program offers financial aid in exchange for volunteering work for students with high financial need.<ref name=\"earlham.edu\"/>\n\nEarlham College is a member of the [[Great Lakes Colleges Association]].\n\n== Adjacent institutions ==\nThere are two institutions located adjacent to the Earlham College undergraduate campus: [[Earlham School of Religion]], a Quaker theological graduate school and [[Bethany Theological Seminary]], an independent [[Church of the Brethren]] institution offering graduate and non-degree programs. Earlham College students can take courses at these institutions (which share facilities with the college).\n\nWhile Earlham is predominately an undergraduate institution, it also offers a Master of Arts in Teaching degree.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://earlham.edu/master-of-arts-in-teaching/|title=Master of Arts in Teaching |publisher=earlham.edu|accessdate=2016-10-20}}</ref>\n\n==Athletics==\nEarlham competes in NCAA Division III and in the [[Heartland Collegiate Athletic Conference]]. The women's sports are basketball, cross country, field hockey, golf, indoor track, outdoor track, soccer, tennis, and volleyball. The men's sports are baseball, basketball, cross country, football, golf, indoor track, outdoor track, soccer, and tennis.<ref name=ath>{{cite web |url=http://www.earlham.edu/~awpe/ |title=Athletics|publisher=Earlham.edu|accessdate=2010-01-18}}</ref>\n\nThe football team was organized in 1888 and been playing games since the 1889 season. As one of the earliest college programs, Earlham has competed against larger foes such as Indiana University, Purdue University, the University of Kentucky, Ball State University, and Butler University. Perhaps the Quakers' most notable football game was an exhibition game against Japan's Doshisha University Hamburgers in 1989.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/09/10/style/campus-life-earlham-week-s-lessons-extend-beyond-football-practice.html?scp=1&sq=Earlham%20Hamburgers&st=cse|title=Week's Lessons Extend Beyond Football Practice|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=September 10, 1989|page=151|accessdate=2010-01-18|url-access=registration }}</ref> The Earlham football team has not won a football game since October 26, 2013, the longest [[losing streak]] in NCAA Division III history at 53 games. In November 2018, the school chose to cancel the program for the remainder of the 2018 season and all of 2019.<ref>[https://www.southbendtribune.com/sports/college/earlham-college-suspends-football-program-after-straight-losses/article_a0180472-5b89-599e-b518-678bd26bc94b.html Earlham College suspends football program after 53 straight losses]</ref> The team was featured on ESPN in 2016 <ref> https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TItx9CNv7jc]</ref>\n\nThe baseball team won its first HCAC Conference title in 2017.\n\n[[National Basketball Association|NBA]] coach [[Del Harris]] was the head coach at Earlham for 9 years (1965-1974).  He twice led the Quakers to a Top 10 ranking in the NAIA final poll and won a school-record 175 games and three Hoosier Collegiate Conference championships.  He led them to the NAIA National Tournament in 1971 with a record of 24-5.\n\nEarlham was an NAIA member in all sports until 19xx; they won the NAIA Men's Soccer National title in 1963.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.naia.org/fls/27900/1NAIA/SportsInfo/Championships/MSOC_Championship.pdf?SPSID=646079&SPID=100398&DB_LANG=C&DB_OEM_ID=27900 |title=MSOC Championship |website=www.naia.org |access-date=2019-05-15}}</ref>\nIn the 2010\u201311 season, the Earlham College Men's Tennis team became the first squad in Earlham history to qualify for the NCAA Div. III Championships by winning the Heartland Collegiate Athletic Conference Tournament title.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://goearlham.com/index.aspx?path=mten |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-01-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110911054011/http://www.goearlham.com/index.aspx?path=mten |archive-date=2011-09-11 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Since the 2011 conference championship, the men's tennis team has won the conference title in 2012 and 2013. In February 2013 the men's tennis team earned its first national ranking in NCAA Division III athletics at no. 30, the first Earlham team to do so since 1999 when the men's soccer team was ranked no. 16.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goearlham.com/news/2013/2/28/MTEN_0228135006.aspx|title=Earlham College Athletics|work=Earlham College|accessdate=21 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141221201457/http://www.goearlham.com/news/2013/2/28/MTEN_0228135006.aspx|archive-date=21 December 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nEarlham's club teams include Ultimate Frisbee, Women's and Men's rugby, the Bike Co-Op, Cheerleaders, Earthquakers (Competitive Dance), Equestrian Program, [[martial arts]] groups, Men's Volleyball, and Outdoors Club.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.earlham.edu/handbook/student/content/wellness/club.html|title=Student Handbook - Club Sports|publisher=Earlham.edu|accessdate=2010-01-18}}</ref> A $13-million Athletics and Wellness Center opened at the beginning of the Fall 1999 semester. Students are not charged to use the facility, which features an energy center for cardiovascular and strength training, a group fitness studio for aerobics and yoga, Weber Pool (25 meters by six lanes), racquetball courts, tennis courts, a running track, a climbing wall and Schuckman Court (a performance gymnasium with seating for 1,800).<ref name=ath/> In 2007, Earlham opened its new 2,000 seat Darrell Beane Stadium, with a football field and running track.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.earlham.edu/~awpe/content/sports/men/football/beane_stadium.html|title=Darrell Beane Stadium|publisher=Earlham.edu|accessdate=2010-01-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070610022517/http://www.earlham.edu/%7Eawpe/content/sports/men/football/beane_stadium.html|archive-date=2007-06-10|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Wilderness programs==\nEarlham was one of the first colleges in the country to initiate student and faculty-led wilderness programs, back in 1970.<ref>Earlham College Wilderness Program Instructors Manual, 1975, by Douglas Steeples, Phil Shore, Alan Kesselheim, Henry Merrill \"and others\", edited by Phil Shore and Alan Kesselheim</ref> These programs were designed for incoming first-year and transfer students who received credit for them. The program is divided into the Water August Wilderness and the Mountain August Wilderness and lasts for approximately three weeks; the former canoes in [[Wabakimi Provincial Park]] in Ontario and the latter hikes in the Uinta Mountains in Utah. Students have taken ice climbing, dog sledding, caving, white water kayaking, rock climbing, trail construction and canoeing courses for credit. The program in the past has led spring break canoeing trips to  [[Big Bend National Park]] in southwestern [[Texas]], a semester course to  New Zealand and a  May Term (a condensed three-week term after the spring semester) instructor training  course for its August Wilderness program. Challenge/experiential education courses on the college's own high and low ropes is offered as well as the chance to be certified as a Wilderness First Responders in an intensive spring break course where students must complete mock rescues. In the past students have also had the opportunity to rappel off the College's three-story science building.\n\n==Notable people==\n{{main|List of Earlham College people}}\n\n*[[Michael Shellenberger]]\n*[[Michael C. Hall]]\n*[[Eva Feldman]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Hamm, Thomas D. ''Earlham College: A History, 1847-1997''. Bloomington: Indiana University Press, 1997. {{ISBN|9780253332561}}.\n* Kashatus, William C. ''Beyond the Touchlines: A History of Earlham Men's Soccer''. Richmond, IN:  Earlham College, 2017.\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.earlham.edu/}}\n* [http://www.goearlham.com/landing/index Earlham Athletics website]\n\n{{Navboxes\n|titlestyle = {{CollegePrimaryStyle|Earlham Quakers|color=white}}\n|list =\n{{GLCA}}\n{{Annapolis Group}}\n{{Oberlin Group}}\n{{CLAC}}\n{{Heartland Collegiate Athletic Conference navbox}}\n{{Indiana Colleges and Universities}}\n{{Global Liberal Arts Alliance}}\n}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Earlham College|*]]\n[[Category:Quaker universities and colleges]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Richmond, Indiana]]\n[[Category:Members of the Annapolis Group]]\n[[Category:Members of the Oberlin Group]]\n[[Category:Education in Richmond, Indiana]]\n[[Category:1847 establishments in Indiana]]\n", "name_user": "Frappyjohn", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAdjacent institutions:comma", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Earlham_College"}
{"title_page": "WCWA Star Wars (1986)", "text_new": "{{short description|Professional wrestling show series}}\n[[World Class Championship Wrestling|World Class Wrestling Association]] (WCWA), based out of [[Dallas, Texas]] held a number of major [[professional wrestling]] super shows under the name '''Wrestling Star Wars'' between 1981 and 1989, with five of these being held in 1986.\n\n==Wrestling Star Wars (January)==\n{{Infobox Wrestling event\n| name=Wrestling Star Wars (January 1986)\n| image=\n| promotion=[[World Class Championship Wrestling]]\n| date=January 26, 1986<ref name=StarWars0186>{{cite web | url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/misc/wccw/miscsw.html#0186 | title=Wrestling Star Wars | date=January 26, 1986 | publisher=Pro Wrestling History}}</ref>\n| venue=[[Fort Worth Convention Center|The Convention Center]]<ref name=StarWars0186/>\n| city=[[Ft. Worth, Texas]]<ref name=StarWars0186/>\n| attendance=8,100<ref name=StarWars0186/>\n| liveevent=y\n| lastevent = [[WCCW Star Wars (1985)#Christmas Star Wars|Christmas Star Wars]]\n| nextevent = [[Parade of Champions#3rd Von Erich Memorial Parade of Champions|3rd Von Erich Memorial Parade of Champions]]\n| event = [[WCWA Star Wars]]\n| lastevent2 = [[WCCW Star Wars (1985)#Christmas Star Wars|Christmas]]\n| nextevent2 = [[#Independence Day Star Wars|Independence Day]]\n}}\n'''Wrestling Star Wars (January 1986)''' was a [[professional wrestling]] [[supercard]] show that was held on January 26, 1986. The show was produced and scripted by the Dallas, Texas based [[World Class Championship Wrestling]] (WCCW) [[professional wrestling promotion]] and held in their home area, Dallas/Ft. Worth, Texas. \n\nSeveral matches from the show were taped for WCCW's television shows and broadcast in the weeks following the show. The show was the 22nd overall show in the \"[[Wrestling Star Wars]]\" event chronology. The show, held at the [[Fort Worth Convention Center]], drew 8,100 spectators out if its estimated 18,000 seat capacity when configured for professional wrestling shows.\n\n===Results===\n{{Pro Wrestling results table\n|results=<ref name=StarWars0186/><ref name=Almanac86>{{cite news|title=Historical Cards: Christmas Star Wars (December 25, 1982. Dallas, Texas) |work=PWI Presents: 2007 Wrestling Almanak and book of facts |publisher=Kappa Publications|id=2007 Edition|page=174}}</ref>\n|times=\n\n|match1=Jerry Allen defeated Tommy Montana\n|stip1=[[Singles match (professional wrestling)|Singles match]]\n|time1=\n\n|match2=[[Chris Adams (wrestler)|Chris Adams]] defeated [[Gino Hernandez]] by disqualification\n|stip2=[[Singles match (professional wrestling)|Singles match]]\n|time2=\n\n|match3=[[Mark Youngblood]] defeated [[Jack Victory]]\n|stip3=[[Singles match (professional wrestling)|Singles match]]\n|time3=\n\n|match4=[[Iceman Parsons]] and [[The Missing Link (wrestler)|The Missing Link]] defeated [[Rick Rude]] and [[Len Denton|The Grappler]]\n|stip4=[[Tag team match]]\n|time4=\n\n|match6=[[John Tatum (wrestler)|John Tatum]] defeated [[Brian Adias]]\n|stip6=[[Singles match (professional wrestling)|Singles match]]\n|time6=\n\n|match7=[[Bruiser Brody]], [[Kerry Von Erich|Kerry]] and [[Lance Von Erich]] defeated The [[Fabulous Freebirds]] ([[Michael Hayes (wrestler)|Michael Hayes]], [[Terry Gordy]] and [[Buddy Roberts]]) (c) by disqualification\n|stip7=[[Six-man tag team match]] for the [[WCWA Six-Man Tag Team Championship]] \n|time7=\n\n|match8=[[Sunshine (wrestling)|Sunshine]] defeated [[Missy Hyatt]] via countout.\n|stip8=[[Singles match (professional wrestling)|Singles match]]\n|time8=\n\n|match9=[[Bruiser Brody]] defeated [[One Man Gang]]\n|stip9=[[Steel Cage Match|steel cage chain match]]\n|time9=\n\n}}\n\n==Independence Day Star Wars==\n{{Infobox Wrestling event\n| name=Independence Day Star Wars (1986)\n| image=\n| promotion=[[World Class Wrestling Association]]\n| date=July 4, 1986<ref name=IndyStarWars>{{cite web | url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/misc/wccw/starwars.html#indy86 | title=Independence Day Star Wars | date=July 4, 1986 | publisher=Pro Wrestling History}}</ref>\n| venue=[[Reunion Arena]]<ref name=IndyStarWars/>\n| city=[[Dallas, Texas]]<ref name=IndyStarWars/>\n| attendance=11,500<ref name=IndyStarWars/>\n| liveevent=y\n| lastevent = [[Parade of Champions#3rd Von Erich Memorial Parade of Champions|3rd Von Erich Memorial Parade of Champions]]\n| nextevent = [[#Labor Day Star Wars|Labor Day Star Wars 1986]]\n| event = [[WCWA Star Wars]]\n| lastevent2 = [[#Wrestling Star Wars (January)|January 1986]]\n| nextevent2 = [[#Labor Day Star Wars|Labor Day]]\n}}\n'''Independence Day Star Wars (1986)''' was a [[professional wrestling]] [[supercard]] show that was held on July 4, 1986. The show was produced and scripted by the Dallas, Texas based [[World Class Wrestling Association]] (WCWA) [[professional wrestling promotion]] and held in their home area, Dallas, Texas. Several matches from the show were taped for WCWA's television shows and broadcast in the weeks following the show. The show was the 23rd overall<!--29th?--> show in the \"[[Wrestling Star Wars]]\" event chronology, drawing 11,500 spectators at the [[Reunion Arena]].\n\n===Results===\n{{Pro Wrestling results table\n|results=<ref name=Almanac86/><ref name=IndyStarWars/>\n|times=\n\n|match1=[[Mark Youngblood]] defeated Jerry Allen\n|stip1=[[Singles match (professional wrestling)|Singles match]]\n|time1=\n\n|match2=The Grapplers ([[Len Denton|Grappler #1]] and [[Tony Anthony|Grappler #2]]) defeated [[The Batten Twins]] (Brad and Bart Batten)\n|stip2=[[Tag team match]]\n|time2=\n\n|match3=[[Buzz Sawyer]] defeated [[Brian Adias]] (c)\n|stip3=[[Singles match (professional wrestling)|Singles match]] for the [[WCWA Texas Heavyweight Championship]]<ref>{{Cite book | author=Royal Duncan & Gary Will | title=Wrestling Title Histories |chapter= (Texas) Dallas: NWA Texas Heavyweight Title | pages= 271 | publisher=Archeus Communications | year=2006|edition=4th | isbn=0-9698161-5-4}}</ref>\n|time3=\n\n|match4=[[Abdullah the Butcher]] defeated The [[Great Kabuki]] (c)\n|stip4=[[Singles match (professional wrestling)|Singles match]] for the [[WCWA Texas Brass Knuckles Championship]]<ref>{{Cite book | author=Royal Duncan & Gary Will | title=Wrestling Title Histories |chapter= (Texas) Dallas: NWA Texas Brass Knuckles Title | pages= 271 | publisher=Archeus Communications | year=2006|edition=4th | isbn=0-9698161-5-4}}</ref>\n|time4=\n\n|match5=[[Sunshine (wrestling)|Sunshine]] defeated The Raven\n|stip5=[[Singles match (professional wrestling)|Singles match]]\n|time5=\n\n|match6=[[Steve Simpson (wrestler)|Steve Simpson]] defeated [[Killer Tim Brooks]]\n|stip6=[[Singles match (professional wrestling)|Singles match]]\n|time6=\n\n|match7=[[Bruiser Brody]] wrestled to a double disqualification against [[Abdullah the Butcher]]\n|stip7=[[Singles match (professional wrestling)|Singles match]]\n|time7=\n\n|match8=[[Chris Adams (wrestler)|Chris Adams]] defeated [[Rick Rude]] (c)\n|stip8=[[Singles match (professional wrestling)|Singles match]] for the [[WCWA World Heavyweight Championship]]<ref>{{Cite book | author=Royal Duncan & Gary Will | title=Wrestling Title Histories |chapter= (Texas) Dallas: NWA American Heavyweight Title | pages= 271 | publisher=Archeus Communications | year=2006|edition=4th | isbn=0-9698161-5-4}}</ref>\n|time8=\n\n|match9=[[Kevin Von Erich|Kevin]], [[Mike Von Erich|Mike]] and [[Lance Von Erich]] (C) defeated [[Butch Reed]], [[Buzz Sawyer]] and [[Matt Borne]]\n|stip9=[[Six-man tag team match]] for the [[WCWA Six-Man Tag Team Championship]]\n|time9=\n}}\n\n==Labor Day Star Wars==\n{{Infobox Wrestling event\n| name=Labor Day Star Wars (1986)\n| image=\n| promotion=[[World Class Wrestling Association]]\n| date=September 1, 1986<ref name=LaborStarWars>{{cite web | url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/misc/wccw/starwars.html#labor86 | title=Labor Day Star Wars | date=September 1, 1986 | publisher=Pro Wrestling History}}</ref>\n| venue=[[Fort Worth Convention Center|The Convention Center]]<ref name=LaborStarWars/>\n| city=[[Ft. Worth, Texas]]<ref name=LaborStarWars/>\n| attendance=5,000<ref name=LaborStarWars/>\n| liveevent=y\n| lastevent = [[#Independence Day Star Wars|Independence Day Star Wars]]\n| nextevent = [[WCCW Cotton Bowl Extravaganza#3rd Cotton Bowl Extravaganza|3rd Cotton Bowl Extravaganza]]\n| event = [[WCWA Star Wars]]\n| lastevent2 = [[#Independence Day Star Wars|Independence Day]]\n| nextevent2 = [[#Thanksgiving Star Wars|Thanksgiving]]\n}}\n'''Labor Day Star Wars (1986)''' was a [[professional wrestling]] [[supercard]] show that was held on September 1, 1986. The show was produced and scripted by the Dallas, Texas based [[World Class Wrestling Association]] (WCWA) [[professional wrestling promotion]] and held in their home area, Dallas/Ft. Worth, Texas. Several matches from the show were taped for WCWA's television shows and broadcast in the weeks following the show. The show was the 24th overall show in the \"[[Wrestling Star Wars]]\" event chronology. The show, held at the [[Fort Worth Convention Center]], drew 5,000 spectators out if its estimated 18,000 seat capacity when configured for professional wrestling shows.\n\n===Results===\n{{Pro Wrestling results table\n|results=<ref name=Almanac86/><ref name=LaborStarWars/>\n|times=\n\n|match1=[[Abdullah the Butcher]] defeated [[Bruiser Brody]] by disqualification\n|stip1=[[WCCW American Tag Team Championship]] tournament bracket match\n|time1=\n\n|match2=[[Chris Adams (wrestler)|Chris Adams]] defeated [[Rick Rude]] by disqualification\n|stip2=[[Singles match (professional wrestling)|Singles match]]\n|time2=\n\n|match3=[[Buzz Sawyer]] and [[Matt Borne]] defeated [[Kevin Von Erich|Kevin]] and [[Mike Von Erich]] by count-out\n|stip3=[[WCWA World Tag Team Championship]] tournament, first round match<ref name=WCWATag>{{Cite book | author=Royal Duncan & Gary Will | title=Wrestling Title 